<FIRST>u a AM-HurricaneGabrielle 2ndLd-Writethru a0752 09-07 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane Gabrielle, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0752,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bermuda Prepares For Hurricane Gabrielle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The hurricane's ..., to UPDATE wind force; SUBS
grafs 9-12, `At 6 p.m. ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. EDT
positions.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm-force winds swept the island of
Bermuda on Thursday, forcing boats to stay in port as a weakened
Hurricane Gabrielle approached. Hurricane Felix, meanwhile, dwindled
into a tropical storm.
   Gabrielle was heading due north, with its center passing about
300 miles east of Bermuda late Thursday, forecasters said.
   The hurricane's winds weakened earlier in the day from 135 mph to
105 mph, but then rose by 10:30 p.m. EDT to 110 mph. Little change
in strength was expected for Gabrielle as it headed towards Tropical
Storm Felix.
   ``The winds won't change much until it reaches cooler waters,''
said Bob Sheets, director of the National Hurricane Center.
   Swells in Bermuda's harbors were reported at 10 feet, and the
island's eastern tip reported swells of 15 to 20 feet. The high
seas, combined with winds of 30 to 35 mph, prevented any seagoing
traffic around the island.
   Otherwise, Bermuda's residents were making few preparations for
the storm, Sheets said.
   Strong winds stretched as far as 1,000 miles from Gabrielle's
center, reaching the U.S. East Coast.
   ``A ship 60 miles off the coast of Long Island reported seeing
12- to 15-foot seas,'' Sheets said. High seas were also reported off
the coast of North Carolina.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT Thursday, Hurricane Gabrielle was centered near
32.6 degrees north latitude and 59.6 degrees west longitude, or 310
miles east of Bermuda. It was traveling north at nearly 17 mph.
   Felix was downgraded from a hurricane to a tropical storm earlier
Thursday as it continued to weaken. The tropical storm posed no
threat to land on its northward trek.
   Forecasters expect Felix to turn toward the northwest and become
engulfed in the larger Gabrielle system. Felix is traveling
northward at 7 mph with winds of 60 mph.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT Thursday, Felix was located near 41.0 degrees
north latitude and 48.5 degrees west longitude, or about 450 miles
southeast of Cape Race, Newfoundland, in Canada.
   Felix was the sixth and Gabrielle the seventh named storms of the
1989 Atlantic hurricane season. Storms are named when their winds
reach 39 mph, and are classified as hurricanes when they grow to 74
mph.
</TEXT>
