<FIRST>u i BC-Poland-CabinetList     09-07 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Cabinet List,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unofficial List of Nominees for 1st Non-Communist-Led Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is an unofficial list of nominees
offered by Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki to fill the ministries
in the East bloc's first non-communist-led government in more than
40 years.
   The list was provided by Solidarity parliamentary deputies who
said late changes could be made before the prime minister's official
announcement Tuesday.
   Solidarity or independent:
   Deputy Prime Minister-Finance Minister (combined post) _ Leszek
Balcerowicz, economist;
   Foreign Affairs _ Krysztof Skubiszewski, church adviser,
international lawyer;
   Education _ Henryk Samsonowicz, former Warsaw University rector;
   Building _ Aleksander Paszynski, journalist-builder;
   Local Government _ Jerzy Regulski, engineer-economist;
   Culture _ Izabela Cywinska, theater director;
   Labor _ Jacek Kuron, veteran opposition activist;
   Industry _ Tadeusz Syryjczyk, private enterprise activist;
   Communist Party
   Deputy Prime Minister-Interior Minister (combined post) _ Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak, incumbent;
   Defense _ Gen. Florian Siwicki, incumbent;
   Transportation _ Adam Wieladek;
   Foreign Trade _ undecided;
   Peasant Party
   Deputy Prime Minister-Agriculture Minister (combined post) _
Czeslaw Janicki, agriculture professor;
   Health _ Andrzej Kosiniak;
   Environment _ Bronislaw Kaminski;
   Justice _ Aleksander Bentkowski, Peasant Party parliament leader;
   Democratic Party
   Deputy Prime Minister-Head of Office of Technology (combined
post) _ Jan Janowski, Democratic Party parliament leader;
   Domestic Trade _ Aleksander Mackiewicz.
   In addition, Mazowiecki nominated communist Politburo member
Wladyslaw Baka to head the Central Planning Office, Solidarity
Senator Witold Trzeciakowski to chair his council of economic
advisers, and Solidarity activist Aleksander Hall to serve as his
liaison with political parties.
   The chairmanship of the committee that oversees state radio and
television was to go to Solidarity, but no individual was nominated.
</TEXT>
