<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-07 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOPLIN, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the green hills of Arkansas to the
granite faces of Mount Rushmore, Brutus the traveling dog has seen
it all _ from the back of a motorcycle.
   Brutus, a 70-pound mix of boxer and Labrador retriever, has
traveled 25,000 miles during the past year standing on the trailer
of a motorcycle driven by Kent Wassenberg.
   Wassenberg, of Marysville, Kan., said the former stray dog hopped
on his bike about two years ago.
   ``I don't tell him to get on. I just hook up the trailer and he
knows it's time to go and gets up there,'' Wassenberg said. ``He
stands up the whole time. Sometimes he takes a break and sits when I
stop at a stoplight or get gas.''
   Brutus wears goggles to protect his eyes and a hooded sweatshirt
when the temperature drops below 30 degrees. A harness keeps him
hitched to the trailer.
   ``He actually prefers to ride on the gas tank, but many states
are against that because he could obscure my vision,'' Wassenberg
said during a recent stop in Joplin en route to Arkansas on a
sightseeing trip.
   Brutus has made two trips with Wassenberg to motorcycle rallies
at Sturgis, S.D. They make weekend jaunts of several hundred miles
through Missouri and Arkansas.
</TEXT>
