<FIRST>r a AM-ActressStalker     09-07 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Actress Stalker,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Trails Actress, Threatens Suicide Outside Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who had been following actress
Justine Bateman, former star of the television series ``Family
Ties,'' was arrested Wednesday after threatening suicide at a
theater where she was appearing, police said.
   John Thomas Smetek, 39, was taken into custody about three hours
after he appeared outside the Berkeley Repertory Theater holding a
loaded revolver to his abdomen, said police Lt. Robert Peters.
   Bateman, 23, best known for her television role as Mallory
Keaton, appeared in the title role of the theater's production of
``Lulu'' at its premiere Wednesday night.
   Smetek, who will undergo a psychiatric evaluation at Highland
Hospital, had been trailing Bateman for months and maintained that
the two shared an intimate relationship, Peters said. ``He just
wants to talk with her and indicate his love-fixation with her,''
Peters said.
   Theater workers first noticed Smetek about 10 a.m. sitting on a
bench in the theater's courtyard. He was holding a .22-caliber
Magnum revolver to his chest, said Berkeley Rep spokesman Richard
Griffoul.
   Another theater worker told police Smetek threatened to kill
himself.
   A team of about 10 police officers and mental health officials
negotiating with Smetek persuaded to take the cocked gun away from
his abdomen and tuck it in his waistband, said Peters.
   At about 12:30 p.m., Smetek surrendered to authorities without
incident, Peters said.
   Smetek was taken to the Hall of Justice, where investigators
arrested him for investigation of possession of a loaded firearm
within city limits and two felony counts of displaying a firearm.
   They were reviewing Smetek's criminal record and also considering
a possible harassment charge, Peters said.
   Bateman's concern about Smetek was raised following two
incidents, which were not described, on the ``Family Ties'' set at
Paramount Studios earlier this year, said the actress' publicist,
Cindy Guagenti.
   ``Justine was aware that he was pursuing her and took the
situation seriously,'' said Guagenti. ``She contacted the police in
Berkeley when she found out he was up there. And she hired a private
security firm.''
   Bateman and theater officials said a temporary restraining order
against Smetek is scheduled to take effect Thursday.
   The slaying of actress Rebecca Schaeffer on July 18, allegedly by
an obsessed fan, has heightened celebrities' uneasiness about
mentally unstable fans.
</TEXT>
