<HEAD>Anne Pollard Denied Early Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anne Pollard, the wife of convicted spy
Jonathan Pollard, has been denied early parole on her conviction as
his accessory, but will probably be released in 1990, a federal
official said Wednesday.
   In denying Mrs. Pollard's request, Daniel Lopez, regional parole
commissioner, accepted a recommendation made last month by a board
of examiners.
   Mrs. Pollard was sentenced March 4, 1987, to five years in prison
as an accessory after the fact in her husbad's case. Her husband is
serving a life sentence at the federal prison at Marion, Ill., for
selling secrets to Israel while he worked as an intelligence analyst
with the U.S. Navy.
   Mrs. Pollard has been earning a 10-day-per-month reduction in her
sentence for good behavior and probably will be released at the end
of March 1990, Joseph Kravisky, a U.S. Parole Commission spokesman
in Washington, said Wednesday.
   Mrs. Pollard is at the federal penitentiary in Danbury, Conn.,
which is part of the Philadelphia region of the U.S. Parole
Commission. Her first appeal for parole was denied last year.
