<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0226EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Kabuki     09-07 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kabuki,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kabuki Troupe Opens in Met Opera House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans who only occasionally see Japanese
kabuki theater may not find Ennosuke's Kabuki as controversial as
publicity before its appearances here and in Washington has led them
to expect.
   Except for some acrobatics, quick costume changes and one exit on
wires through the sky, at Wednesday's first of eight performances at
the Metropolitan Opera, Ennosuke's Kabuki seemed largely to follow
kabuki's traditions such as stylized fights and poses held a moment
to increase tension. The troupe later will perform at Kennedy Center.
   The most remarkable aspect of Ennosuke's Kabuki is its leading
actor, Ichikawa Ennosuke III, who has organized this company of 36
actors and 24 musicians.
   Two pieces are done at each performance, which lasts three and a
half hours, longer than many Americans wish an evening of theater to
last.
   The first is three acts from ``Yoshitsune Senbonzakura,'' an
eight-hour, six-act play which was first done in 1747 with puppets
and adapted to kabuki the following year. In it, Ennosuke plays two
parts, Tadanobu, a warrior faithful to a hero and a fox who has
transformed himself to look like the warrior. The fox did it, the
audience learns, to be near Tadanobu's lover who has a drum made of
the skin of his parents. This illustrates fillial piety.
   Ennosuke, who is 49, is young enough to jump up a flight of steps
two at a time, vault off the back of a porch and crawl under it,
emerging at the front in white fox fur. But more remarkable than
that is the difference in stance the actor has for Tadanobu and for
the fox as Tadanobu, when his hands subtly become paws and his head
is held less militarily.
   Some kabuki companies' strongest actors play young women.
However, the actor playing Tadanobu's lover was simpering and whiney.
   In the second play, ``Kurozuka,'' Ennosuke played an old woman,
actually a demon, whose soul is soothed by a Buddhist priest who
says that even demons can find enlightenment. Ennosuke does a gentle
dance in what looks like a corn field, including deep breaths of
relief.
   Then a comic character, played by Ennosuke's younger brother,
blunders and Ennosuke becomes a demon with red tongue and deep,
angry voice.
   In other kabuki troupes visiting here, older actors have made
characters like the old woman more poignant. But Ennosuke's old
woman isn't superficial. One would like to see his troupe again and
him again, as he deepens farther in conveying human emotion.
   Viewers could rent an apparatus to place in one ear, for English
summary and commentary, while allowing the rise and fall of the
Japanese voices to be heard with the other ear.
</TEXT>
