<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     09-07 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC News Special `Bad Girls' Makes TV Top 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Bad Girls,'' a news special on juvenile
delinquents, helped NBC extend its prime-time Nielsen ratings streak
to 63 weeks in a week dominated by sitcoms.
   ``Bad Girls,'' reported by NBC correspondent Deborah Norville,
tied for seventh place with ABC's ``Who's the Boss?'' It was the
only original show in last week's top 10 during this summer rerun
period.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' was first again in the A.C. Nielsen Co.
survey, followed by NBC's ``Cheers.''
   Fox Broadcasting Co.'s highest-rated show, ``Married...With
Children,'' dropped from 17th to 41st place. Still, most of the Fox
shows were able to hold their newfound positions in the middle of
the ratings.
   NBC extended its record streak at the top with an average
prime-time rating of 10.6. ABC's average was 9.7 and CBS' was 9.0.
   The rating point is the percentage of the nation's estimated 90.4
million homes with televisions.
   The first of the new fall shows for the three networks will make
its appearance this week. CBS' ``Rescue: 911'' had its premiere on
Tuesday. Next week, five more shows will make their debut, and the
fall season begins Sept. 18. Fox has gotten an early start with some
of its shows.
   NBC last week had seven of the top 10 shows. CBS once again
failed to make the top 10. Its highest-rated show was ``Designing
Women'' in 13th place.
   Here are the top 10: ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``A Different World'' and ``Dear John,'' ABC's ``The
Wonder Years,'' NBC News special ``Bad Girls'' and ABC's ``Who's the
Boss?'' tied, NBC's ``Golden Girls'' and NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and
ABC's ``Anything But Love,'' tied.
   ABC was first among the evening news shows with a rating of 9.1.
CBS had a 9.0 and NBC 8.6.
   ``The Joan Rivers Show,'' a new syndicated daytime talk show,
made its premier Tuesday with good ratings in the Nielsen
overnights. It was first in six of 13 cities, according to Tribune
Entertainment.
</TEXT>
