<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MTVAwards 4thLd-Writethru a0402 09-07 0871</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MTV Awards, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0402,0897</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michael Jackson Leads Video Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 25 grafs to UPDATE with final awards; picks up 15th
graf, `Jackson was ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA8,9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Laker Girl Paula Abdul's
energetic ``Straight Up'' video won four trophies at the sixth
annual MTV Video Music Awards as Madonna claimed the Viewers' Choice
and three technical honors Wednesday night.
   ``I owe a lot to being a Laker Girl,'' Abdul, who began her
career as a cheerleader for the National Basketball Association team
here, said backstage at the Universal Amphitheatre. ``It was a great
vehicle to start off.''
   Abdul's video, which drew on cheerleading dance styles, took best
female video, dance, choreography and editing.
   Veteran rocker Neil Young earned best video for the satirical
``This Note's For You,'' which MTV once banned from broadcast,
ostensibly because it contained commercial messages. The video
satirized rock star endorsements of products, and featured Michael
Jackson and Whitney Houston lookalikes.
   Madonna, who was nominated six times, got the Viewer's Choice
award for ``Like a Prayer.'' Her ``Express Yourself'' video earned
direction honors for David Fincher, the art direction trophy for
Vance Lorenzini, and best cinematography for Mark Plummer.
   ``I guess this means you like me, you really like me,'' the
singer said after receiving her Viewers Choice award, in a joking
echo of actress Sally Field's ``You like me'' acceptance speech at
the 1984 Academy Awards.
   ``And I'd like to thank Pepsi for causing so much controversy,''
Madonna added.
   The Pepsi Cola Co. in April withdrew its television commercial
featuring Madonna and also its sponsorship of her tour. The
commercial featured a burning cross and other images that offended
Christian groups, particularly Roman Catholics.
   The Viewers Choice is a popularity award determined by telephone
votes and ballots received by mail and fax machine.
   Funk rockers Living Colour won best group, new artist and stage
performance awards for ``Cult of Personality.'' They accepted their
trophies backstage at Three Rivers Stadium in Pittsburgh, where they
were performing with the Rolling Stones.
   Stones' lead singer Mick Jagger presented the best group video
trophies during the live satellite remote.
   Elvis Costello got the male video honor for ``Veronica,''
R.E.M.'s ``Orange Crush'' captured the post-modern category.
   Madonna, taking a sultry stage pose with a cigarette and a
two-woman entourage, introduced the career-achievement Video
Vanguard award to pop singer George Michael. The award had been
announced in advance.
   D.J. Jazzy Jeff &amp; The Fresh Prince won the rap award for
``Parents Just Don't Understand.''
   ``This is a dream come true,'' said Fresh Prince, 19, who urged
all of the ``kids out there'' to ``Stay away from drugs and all that
stuff.''
   ``Kiss,'' by Art of Noise and featuring vocals by Tom Jones, was
hailed as the year's breakthrough video.
   Guns N' Roses won the heavy metal category for ``Sweet Child O'
Mine'' and the combination of Irish rockers U2 and veteran bluesman
B.B. King earned a best video from film trophy for ``When Love Comes
to Town'' from the concert movie ``Rattle and Hum.''
   The awards show, hosted by Arsenio Hall, lasted 2{ hours and
featured performances by Abdul, Cher, Def Leppard, Jon Bon Jovi,
Richie Sambora, and Madonna.
   A performance by MTV comic Andrew Dice Clay was filled with
obscene, unprintable poems and comments about overweight women and
sex. MTV Vice President Barry Kluger quickly went before reporters
backstage and apologized for the material.
   ``Andrew Dice Clay did not do this in rehearsal and we were very
surprised by it. Based on this experience, Andrew Dice Clay will not
be appearing on MTV in the future,'' Kluger said.
   The comic had already left before Kluger's statement.
   Pop superstar Michael Jackson had the odds in his favor going
into the show, but he cashed in only one of his eight nominations,
earning a special effects trophy for Jim Blashfield.
   Jody Watley came up emptyhanded despite six nominations for
``Real Love.''
   Puerto Rican singer Chayanne won best Latin rock video in the
International Viewers Choice award, a popularity contest determined
by telephone votes and ballots received by mail and fax machine.
   Nominations were made in 18 general and professional categories.
The additional special categories included Hall of Fame, Viewers
Choice and International Viewers Choice, the latter for best
European, Australian, Japanese and Latin rock videos.
   Jackson was a multiple winner at the first MTV Video Music Awards
in 1984, taking the special Viewer's Choice, choreography and
overall performance honors for ``Thriller.'' But even then he was
overshadowed by Herbie Hancock's six awards for ``Rockit.''
   Jackson didn't get another MTV award until last year, when he was
given a special Video Vanguard award.
   And despite an emphasis on stunning visuals, Madonna didn't win
an MTV award until 1986. Her second came in 1987.
   In the short history of the MTV awards, Peter Gabriel was the
biggest winner of a single year, collecting nine silver statuettes
for ``Sledgehammer'' in 1987.
   The first and second MTV awards were staged at Radio City Music
Hall in New York City. The 1986 show originated from both the
Universal Amphitheatre and the Palladium in New York. Since then the
amphitheater has been its home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
