<DOCNO> AP890907-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WheelchairWedding     09-07 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wheelchair Wedding,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paralyzed Woman to Stand up at Wedding</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN HAYWOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KING GEORGE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Cath Tschirn marries Richard Thomas
on Saturday, she plans to get out of her wheelchair for the first
time in five years and stand up to say her vows.
   With the help of the 2-year-old southeastern Virginia branch of
Volunteers for Medical Engineering, Miss Tschirn (pronounced Churn)
said she hopes to fulfill her dreams of a fairy tale wedding.
   ``I got the dress I wanted. If I hadn't had the accident, I'd be
standing up. Plus, I think I'll shock the whole church,'' she said.
   The 20-year-old Miss Tschirn was a junior in high school, a
cheerleader and a drama club member on Oct. 17, 1984, when the car
in which she was riding flipped over.
   ``All that really happened to me is I was paralyzed,'' she said.
``I didn't have a scratch.''
   The organization built a stand for Miss Tschirn to hold herself
up, and on the bottom is a lazy susan, which will allow her to turn
around and greet the congregation when she and her husband are
introduced as Mr. and Mrs. Richard Thomas.
   Founded in 1982 by John Staehlin, the organization has grown from
the first club in Baltimore to 400 members and 12 chapters,
according to Carole Forsythe, its executive director.
   Ms. Forsythe said Staehlin, an engineer at a defense plant in
Baltimore, had wanted for years to do something other than defense
work. ``He was sitting in church and heard a sermon on using your
talents'' and decided to do it, she said.
   Besides the stand for Miss Tschirn, projects have included
software and switches that enable an immobilized person to use a
computer by blinking one's eyes; research on an artificial muscle;
and voice-controlled videocassette recorders.
   Using donated funds, the Newport News chapter bought the
materials to make the device for Miss Tschirn, said Roy Whitlock,
president of the club and director of maintenance engineering and
environmental services at Riverside Rehabilitation Institute in
Newport News.
   One club member helped in Miss Tschirn's rehabilitation and let
the group know of the young woman's dream.
   ``I understand soon after she was injured, she stated it blankly:
`I want to stand up at my wedding,''' Whitlock said.
   After a yearlong rehabilitation, Miss Tschirn graduated with her
high school class. She has regained some movement in her feet. She
works, lives in an apartment behind her parents' garage and
considers herself more independent than many people who have
suffered similar accidents.
   She also talks to children and anyone who will listen about
wearing seat belts, since she was not wearing one when the accident
occurred.
   She met her fiance a year after her accident. Thomas also was in
a car accident and used a wheelchair for three months.
   ``My fiance said, `I don't see why you're so hung up on standing
up,''' she recalled. ```I didn't meet you standing up.'''
   Miss Tschirn hopes to leave the wheelchair behind at the altar
and sit in another chair for the first part of the ceremony, then
stand up for the vows. She and Thomas will operate the stand, which
will be decorated with ribbons and lace.
   ``I'm going to get him to carry me down the aisle,'' she said.
</TEXT>
