<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Nominations     09-07 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Nominations,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Blames Bush for Administration Vacancies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell says
President Bush, not the Senate, is responsible for the 200 vacancies
still remaining in top policy-making positions in the Bush
administration.
   Bush's attempt to blame the Senate for foot-dragging is
``unwarranted and unfair,'' Mitchell said.
   In each of the 200 positions, the president has not indicated
that holdovers from the Reagan administration will be asked to stay
on, the Maine Democrat told the Senate on Wednesday. There are a
total of 432 such jobs.
   ``Thus, nearly eight months after he took office, the president
has failed to make nominations for nearly half of the full-time
positions in executive departments and independent agencies which
require Senate confirmation.
   ``Whose responsibility is that?'' Mitchell asked. ``It is
certainly not the Senate's.''
   Mitchell noted that after he met with Bush on Aug. 4 to discuss
nominations, White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said,
``The president wanted to express his deep concern that these
(nominations) were being held up for artificial reasons not related
to the candidates themselves.''
   Mitchell said that, based on a careful review of the status of
the Bush nominations to date, he is ``urging that the president
discontinue such criticism.''
   ``It is unfounded and unfair,'' Mitchell said. ``The principal
problem is in the slow pace at which nominations are being made, not
in the pace at which nominations, once made, are being processed.''
   He said there are 48 policy-making positions in government
departments that are ``totally vacant,'' with no nominations
submitted and no holdovers from the Reagan administration.
   ``Out of 14 Cabinet departments, only the Department of
Transportation has no totally vacant positions,'' Mitchell said.
``There are five totally vacant positions in the Executive Office of
the President and another 20 in major independent agencies.''
   In education, he said, there are no nominees to fill assistant
secretary positions in elementary and secondary education or in
vocational and adult education and civil rights.
   In public health, Mitchell said, there is no nominee for Surgeon
General, commissioner of aging or for administrator of the Health
Care Finance Administration.
   ``The vital 1990 Census is rapidly approaching and there is no
nominee to be director of the Census Bureau,'' Mitchell said.
``Whose responsibility is that?''
   Mitchell said the Senate has confirmed 212 Bush nominees, 90
percent of them within two months of the time the nominations was
received. He did not include nominations for U.S. ambassadors, U.S.
marshals or U.S. attorneys.
   He said a slow-motion nominating process is hurting the way the
government functions because senior Civil Service professionals ``do
not set policy for an administration.''
   ``When there are no people at the top, the professional civil
servant does the best he or she can; but policy initiatives await
the arrival of presidentially nominated personnel,'' Mitchell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
