<FIRST>r a PM-People-Bing-Annulment     09-07 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Bing-Annulment,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annulment Granted for Sir Rudolf Bing and Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Rudolf Bing's marriage has been annulled, but
his lawyer says that comes too late for the former opera impresario
to finish his life in his own home.
   State Judge Carmen Ciparick on Wednesday granted the invalidation
over the objections of Carroll Douglass, ending a 33-month union
during which attorneys for both said the pair had lost touch with
reality.
   As the case proceeded, the 87-year-old Bing, who suffers from
Alzheimer's disease, was moved from the fashionable Essex House
hotel along Central Park to a nursing home.
   ``In 1985, he came to a 30-year friend and said, `The one thing I
really want is to stay in the Essex House and die there,''' said
Bing's lawyer, Paul Goldhamer. ``But we ran out of money and time.''
   Goldhamer said hiring security and nurses to protect Bing from
Ms. Douglass took up $400,000 to $450,000 of Bing's $600,000 estate.
What's left is mostly paintings.
   ``It's truly a tragic event,'' Goldhamer said.
   The judge denied alimony or any part of Bing's estate to Ms.
Douglass, 50, who is hospitalized in a mental ward of Bellevue
Hospital, said her lawyer, Harvey Sladkus.
   Ciparick ordered Bing's estate to pay the expenses for Ms.
Douglass' hospitalization for mental problems last summer, Sladkus
said.
   Ms. Douglass' sister and brother in Washington will confer on the
next legal move, Sladkus said.
   Ms. Douglass, who had a history of mental problems, was
hospitalized in August 1988 after she ``lost touch with reality,''
he said.
   Bing's legal guardian, Paul C. Guth, was on vacation and
unavailable for comment. Bing's first marriage lasted 54 years but
ended in divorce.
   Bing and Douglass married Jan. 9, 1987, in a civil ceremony in
Arlington, Va. Attorneys for Bing, the general manager of the
Metropolitan Opera for 22 years, claimed he was mentally incompetent
and had no idea of what he was doing when he got married.
   The annulment trial began in May 1988. Almost half the couple's
marriage was spent in court.
</TEXT>
