<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0508EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     09-07 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Slightly, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the yen today, while
share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined for the third
consecutive day.
   The dollar closed at 146.87, up 0.22 yen from Wednesday's close.
The currency opened at 146.20 yen, 0.45 yen lower than the previous
day's close of 146.65 yen. But the dollar soared to 147.05 yen
during afternoon trading before easing down to the day's close.
   Currency dealers said market participants were waiting on the
sidelines on speculation that the West German central bank would
raise key interest rates to drive the dollar lower later in the day.
   They said the speculation caused the West German mark to rise
against the dollar, depressing the relative value of the U.S.
currency against other currencies, including the yen.
   ``When there is such speculation swirling around the market, it
is hard to buy the dollar though I believe the dollar is still quite
bullish,'' said a dealer with Daiichi Kangyo Bank, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The dealer also said many market participants share the view that
the dollar has been rising too fast, and ``that led to easing of the
dollar today.''
   ``Traders are keeping their eyes on central banks'
intervention,'' he said.
   But another dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar is
expected to remain bullish for some time because of the strength of
the U.S. economy.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 170.64 points Wednesday, fell another 118.75
points, or 0.35 percent, to close at 34,152.56.
   Securities dealers attributed the bearishness of the stock market
to unstable exchange rates and the weakness of the yen.
   ``Many investors are sidelined until the instability of exchange
rates settles down,'' said a dealer at Nikko Securities, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   He added that buying incentives are increasing in the market
though ``the Nikkei average is not improving yet,'' he said.
   The volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where
most major shares are listed, was estimated at a moderate 600
million shares.
</TEXT>
