<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0549EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Malaria     09-07 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaria,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Therapies Aimed at Blood Vessel Protein May Avert Malaria Complications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New therapy to block malaria infection from
harming the brain may result from a study that implicates a protein
in that problem and other serious complications of the disease,
researchers say.
   Scientists reported today that red blood cells infected with a
malaria-causing parasite stick to the protein, which is found in the
inner lining of blood vessels.
   Attachment of infected red cells to vessel walls is thought to
play an important part in producing complications of malaria, said
researcher Anthony Berendt.
   For example, it makes red cells clog some blood vessels of the
brain. The clogging is a key factor in cerebral malaria, a
complication reponsible for more than half the world's deaths from
malaria, said scientist Luis Fajardo of Stanford University Medical
School.
   Berendt said that if further work demonstrates that the protein
plays a key role in cerebral malaria, finding drugs aimed at
dislodging the red cells from the protein may prove useful.
   Berendt, of John Radcliffe Hospital in Oxford, England, and
colleagues there describe their work in the British journal Nature.
   The protein is called intercellular adhesion molecule-1, or
ICAM-1. Two other proteins, called CD36 and thrombospondin, had
previously been implicated as possible attachment sites for infected
red cells.
   But studies suggested those proteins could not account for all
cases of red cell attachment, Berendt said in a telephone interview.
That led to the work that implicates ICAM-1, and there may be still
more blood vessel proteins involved, Berendt said.
   Fajardo, a pathology professor at Stanford, said the findings
were very important.
   Fewer than 1 percent of the world's estimated 100 million to 200
million annual malaria cases are thought to progress to cerebral
malaria, but it probably kills more than 500,000 people a year in
Africa alone, he said.
   The condition can be treated with quinine, but new drugs would be
welcome because quinine does not always work and because it has
undesirable side effects, Fajardo said.
   Malaria occurs after a parasite is injected into the bloodstream
from the bite of a mosquito. The Nature paper shows that red blood
cells infected by the most dangerous species of malaria parasite,
Plasmodium falciparum, can stick to the protein ICAM-1.
   That protein is widely distributed in the inner linings of
capillaries, the tiny blood vessels where red cells can attach
themselves in malaria, researchers said.
   In the test tube, red cells infected by a parasite strain from
Brazil stuck to the ICAM-1 protein on the surface of tissue cells.
Red cells infected by a strain from Gambia did not.
   The rate of binding increased after the tissue cells were exposed
to tumor necrosis factor, a natural substance known to stimulate
production of ICAM-1.
   Fajardo said that fits in with research that found higher levels
of tumor necrosis factor in malaria patients who suffered cerebral
malaria than patients who did not.
   The British researchers are now preparing to test a range of
parasite strains to see how widespread the affinity for ICAM-1 is,
Berendt said.
   In the Nature paper, they suggested that the severity of a case
of malaria may depend on red cell affinity for various blood vessel
proteins, as determined by the infecting parasite, and the infected
person's levels of those proteins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
