<FIRST>r a PM-YugoslavLaundering     09-07 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslav Laundering,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank, Texan Guilty In Money Laundering; Consular, Bank Officials
Innocent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslavian diplomat and a bank chairman
have been cleared of conspiring to launder nearly $3.5 million
provided by undercover agents posing as mobsters, but a Texas
businessman has been found guilty.
   Hubert Cole, an admitted money launderer, testified he lied when
he told investigators that 48-year-old Bahrudin Bijedic,
Yugoslavia's consul general in Chicago, gave him consular seals,
which bar U.S. officials from opening packages, and an official
courier letter to help him transport cash to Yugoslavia.
   ``In 10 years I've represented many not guilty people, but only
four innocent men. Bijedic was one of them,'' attorney Michael C.
Goode said.
   Vinko Mir, 55, chairman of LBS Bank of New York, also was
acquitted of the conspiracy charge, but his bank, a branch of
Ljubljanska Banka of Yugoslavia was convicted and faces a $500,000
fine.
   Businessman Vjekoslav Spanjol, 42, of Plano, Texas, was convicted
too and faces a sentence of about 60 years in prison and a $4.1
million fine, Assistant U.S. Attorney Paul A. Sarmousakis said.
   Lawyer Denver G. McCarty said he would appeal Spanjol's
conviction. Vince Fuller, the bank's lawyer, could not be reached
after the verdict.
   ``I thought it was entirely possible that he'd be found not
guilty on everything. I was surprised he and the bank were found
guilty of the conspiracy because he did not have anything to do with
the bank or its officers,'' McCarty said.
   Spanjol, Bijedic, Mir and the bank branch were charged with
conspiring to launder $3.47 million by depositing the money in
Yugoslavia and wiring it back to accounts in the United States to
conceal its source.
   Spanjol, a naturalized citizen, and LBS Bank of New York were
convicted of conspiracy to obstruct the U.S. Treasury from
collecting taxes, gathering accurate information on domestic
currency transactions and obtaining information on international
cash movements.
   Spanjol was found guilty of seven other counts, including
smuggling out of the country two underwater breathing devices
restricted by the State Department. The jury acquitted him of two
related counts.
   All three men were arrested Dec. 1, 1988. Cole and Spanjol were
apprehended at Philadelphia International Airport as they tried to
ship $2 million to Yugoslavia, Customs officials said.
   Cole, 44, of Carrollton, Texas, who had faced up to 230 years in
jail and a $10.6 million fine, pleaded guilty to money laundering
charges and agreed to testify for prosecutors.
   Larry Card of Chattanooga, Tenn., who could have been sentenced
to five years in jail and fined $250,000, also pleaded guilty in the
case and testified for the government.
</TEXT>
