<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseExile     09-07 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Exile,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exiled Chinese Student Leader Emerges from Life On The Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exile's life is not what Wu'er Kaixi
wanted, but he took a leading role in China's student uprising last
spring and when the dust had settled was on his government's
most-wanted list.
   Wu'er, a student at Beijing Normal University, made a dangerous
10-day journey to escape his homeland. Now he's starting over as a
student at Harvard University, but he told The Associated Press on
Wednesday his eye is still on the battle back home.
   ``If you experience that kind of massacre it changes your life,''
said Wu'er. ``Whenever I think of my friends who were murdered in
Tiananmen Square, I feel the obligation.''
   The China Information Center here is now his focus. It's through
this hub's telephones, fax machines and computers that he works to
effect change back home.
   In June, the events in Beijing riveted the world and millions saw
Wu'er's drawn face as he stood up to Premier Li Peng and demanded a
dialogue.
   Then came the quiet morning after troops stormed the square,
killing hundreds, maybe thousands. Only a few who fled could carry
on in the wake of such force.
   He and his girlfriend navigated China's backroads for 10 days
before they finally reached the South China Sea and what seemed the
only route to go.
   ``The first step I took was into the sea, and I knew that I
wouldn't go back,'' he said. ``I didn't feel anything because it was
just after the massacre and my feelings were already frozen.''
   Those few, bloody days last spring also numbed the Chinese
people, but they did not cower, Wu'er said.
   ``This is a famous face now,'' the tall, muscular man said.
   ``But in the city and in the country, the people protected me.
Even people who I didn't know kept quiet and immediately showed
support,'' said Wu'er, who tried to find a way out of the country
from eight cities before succeeding.
   The people didn't like the government before, but dislike has
been displaced by hatred since their sons and daughters were gunned
down in June, Wu'er said.
   He and many other exiled students, their supporters and those who
remain at work underground in China, are getting the word out and
forming unions.
   ``We aren't organized officially, of course, because the
government doesn't want it,'' said Wu'er, who refused to provide
many details on the escape. ``But we can establish a voice outside
China.''
   He said that on a recent trip to Paris he helped form a group
called The Front for Democratic China as a central organization to
coordinate efforts outside of China. He said a congress would be
held later this month in Paris to set an agenda and elect a
governing board.
   China's largest newspaper recently featured Wu'er, complete with
various statements about his character _ all derisive. But the
insults don't vex him.
   ``They're paying a lot of attention to what we're doing outside.
And that means they're scared,'' said Wu'er.
   Wu'er says chance played a large part in his own place in the
spotlight.
   ``When I was a freshman (in Beijing) I loved beer and parties,
like American kids,'' he said. ``But the political and economic
situation forced me to think about the country's system...
   ``I stood in the front because I care about my self-worth,''
Wu'er, who will study English in his first semester at Harvard, said
through a translator. ``I stood in front because the government
doesn't allow ... the Chinese people to realize their own
self-worth.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
