<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ForestGlen-LoveCanal     09-07 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forest Glen-Love Canal,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>First House Boarded up at Contaminated Neighborhood</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's being called Love Canal II and
lately a trailer park where toxic contamination was discovered has
begun to resemble the infamous toxic waste site just three miles
away.
   A house at the entrance to the Forest Glen trailer park, one of
two non-trailers in the subdivision of 53 families, was the first to
be boarded up Monday. The house's owner, Dennis Bauer, has relocated
to Lewiston, about 10 miles north of Niagara Falls.
   The Bauer family was one of 23 households in Forest Glen where
traces of benzothiazole, a carcinogenic industrial chemical, were
found. The federal Environmental Protection Agency said the amounts
in the homes were so small that they are not a health concern.
   Nonetheless, the Bauers left a sofa on their front lawn with the
words ``Danger Contaminated'' spray-painted on it.
   Such displays were common 11 years ago when dioxin and other
contaminants were discovered at the Love Canal neighborhood.
Eventually, 1,030 families were evacuated from a 10-block area
around the former chemical dump site.
   Forest Glen, home to some of the people who left Love Canal, also
was built on a toxic dump.
   EPA spokesman Michael Basile said the Bauers' property will be
padlocked and that a private security force has been hired to patrol
the area.
   Despite the EPA's recommendation to leave the neighborhood, some
residents said they did not want to move away temporarily because
they were afraid their homes would be looted.
   Many homes in Love Canal were vandalized after the evacuations.
The dilapidated homes still stand as a monument to environmental
disaster, although some have been torn down as part of a plan to
revitalize the area.
   Federal officials have made no determination on the long-term
future of Forest Glen. Until residents are out, there can be no
excavations to determine the extent of the contamination, officials
said.
   As of Monday, the Federal Emergency Management Agency had taken
24 applications for temporary relocation, said spokesman Bert
Gallowing.
   Of those, six have moved off-site, eight have found new
residences and are waiting to move, and 10 others are still looking.
   Twenty-three other families are considering moving their trailers
out of the park. Six families have not announced plans and are
believed to be waiting for the federal buyout, which is expected to
take up to a year.
   Basile said once families moved, the EPA will board up their
homes to protect them from vandalism.
</TEXT>
