<DOCNO> AP890907-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0736EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia-Rebels     09-07 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Rebels Claim New Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels in northern Ethiopia say they have
taken four more towns, including a strategic government garrison, in
an offensive that began last week.
   The clandestine radio of the Tigray People's Liberation Front
said Wednesday the rebels had captured the garrison town of Weldiya
in Wollo Province, killing 103 government soldiers and capturing 26.
   The broadcast was monitored in Nairobi on the eve of scheduled
peace talks in Atlanta in the United States between the government
and another major rebel group, the Eritrean People's Liberation
Front.
   The Tigrean rebels also said they had overrun three smaller towns
in Wollo Province in three days of heavy fighting that began Aug.
31. The radio identified them as Robit, Gobiye and Dorogebir.
   The Tigrean front, newly allied with the Ethiopian People's
Democratic Movement, had earlier claimed the capture of a string of
towns along a major highway leading south toward Addis Ababa, the
capital.
   Weldiya, about 200 miles north of the capital, is an important
junction on the north-south highway, connecting it with a route
running west to Gondar Province.
   The Eritrean rebels have been fighting since 1962 for the
independence of Ethiopia's northernmost province.
   The Tigreans seek greater autonomy for their region, which is
immediately to the south of Eritrea.
   The Ethiopian People's Democratic Movement is a much smaller
group that has been active in Wollo and Gondar provinces.
</TEXT>
