<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Andre     09-07 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Andre,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developer of Duncan Hines Cake Mixes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arlee Andre, creator of the original
Duncan Hines cake mixes, has died at age 89.
   Andre, who died Monday, was a cereal chemist testing flour for
Nebraska Consolidated Mills in Omaha in 1952 when he decided to
develop a cake mix with better flavor and uniformity than the two
mixes then commercially available.
   Working after hours and on his own time, Mr. Andre researched the
best ways to make yellow cake, white cake, chocolate cake and angel
food cake.
   ``My sister and I were more or less raised on it. We were the
test subjects,'' said his son, Alan. ``He'd bring home these little
cakes, unfrosted, with little numbers on them. He'd say, `Taste them
and tell me what you think.'
   ``Of course, we weren't good critics; my sister and I were
children and liked them all.''
   When the mixes were ready to be marketed, Nebraska Consolidated
Mills paid food and drink connoisseur Duncan Hines a penny a box to
use his name. The mixes quickly became popular and were sold to
Procter &amp; Gamble in 1956.
   Andre also moved to the conglomerate and retired from P&amp;G in the
mid-1960s.
   Besides a son and daughter, survivors include his wife, Thelma,
four grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
   Services will be private.
</TEXT>
