<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     09-07 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Arrested in Sabotage of U.S. Distribution of Films</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two film makers were arrested today on
charges of sabotaging the distribution of U.S. films in South Korea,
police said.
   One of the suspects, Yoo Dong-hun, chairman of the Korean Film
Workers Association, admitted hiring others to attack theaters doing
business with a Holywood-based film distributor, Universal
International Pictures, by releasing snakes in the theaters and
attacking the buildings with firebombs, police said.
   Yoo, 48, and screenwriter Lee Jung-u, 45, were charged with
arranging the sabotage. On Monday, two film directors were arrested
on similar charges.
   Police said today they are searching for three Koreans accused of
carrying out the attacks on the theaters. Their names were not
released.
   In an unrelated development today, prosecutors indicted two Roman
Catholic priests for sending a fellow priest to escort home a South
Korean radical student who had made an illegal trip to Communist
North Korea.
   Yoo and Lee have been active in a campaign opposing Universal
International Pictures releases in South Korea. Yoo also reportedly
collected funds from movie producers to launch campaign against the
U.S. films.
   Police said Yoo arranged a firebomb attack Aug. 13 on Seoul's
Cine House. The theater was partly burned, but no injuries were
reported. The non-poisonous snakes were released into another
theater last year.
   Universal International Pictures has faced a boycott campaign by
South Korean film workers since its first film, ``Fatal
Attraction,'' was shown in September. The South Korean film industry
wants to handle the distribution of U.S. films itself, rather than
see a foreign company do it.
   A trade law adopted last year allowed U.S. companies to bypass
South Korean distributors by releasing films directly to cinemas.
   Revs. Nam Kook-hyun, 40, and Park Byong-jun, 37, were charged
with sending a fellow priest, Moon Gyu-hyon, to accompany a radical
student across the border with North Korea on Aug. 15 after her
illegal trip to the North.
   If prosecutors from the Seoul District Prosecutors' Office win
convictions for the priests, they could receive up to seven years in
prison.
   The radical student, Im Su-kyong, 20, will be formally indicted
Friday on charges of making an illegal trip to North Korea to attend
a World Youth Festival there July 1-8, prosecution officials said.
If she is found guilty, she could receive up to 10 years in prison
under the National Security Law.
   Im, a student at Seoul's Hankuk University, said her North Korean
trip was aimed at promoting unification of the divided Korean
peninsula. Her arrest touched off violent anti-government protests
by radical students in the South.
   Radicals stepped up anti-government protests to press their
demand for the release of Im, whom they described as ``the flower of
unification.''
   South Korea bans unauthorized trips to North Korea, an enemy
country since the division of the Korean peninsula in 1945. The two
Koreas fought a three-year war in the early 1950's.
</TEXT>
