<FIRST>r a PM-Drug-DeathThreat     09-07 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug-Death Threat,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Tightened After Caller Threatens to Kill Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security has been tightened around some New York
City judges following a death threat from a caller claiming to be a
member of a Colombian drug cartel, authorities said.
   The anonymous call was made at 2 a.m. Saturday to the FBI in New
York City.
   ``An anonymous call is just that. It's hard to verify or judge
the level of the threat,'' said FBI spokesman Joe Valiquette.
   Alfred Lerner, administrative judge of the Supreme Court in the
city's borough of Queens, said the caller threatened to kill a judge
in Kew Gardens, a Queens neighborhood. He said he called a meeting
in the court's Kew Gardens branch and told 25 judges about the
threat after learning of it Wednesday.
   ``I don't know if it's a crank call, but I think (the judges)
have a right to know,'' Lerner said.
   One judge, Vincent Naro, a past target of death threats, was
escorted to his car Wednesday by a police officer, New York Newsday
reported today. Extra court officers were posted in the Kew Gardens
courthouse parking lot as well.
   Other, unspecified measures have been taken to protect the 77
judges of the Queens Supreme and Criminal courts, said John Perno,
director of security at the Office of Court Administration. In New
York, Supreme Court is a trial-level court.
   ``I took the necessary measures we ordinarily take when we learn
of death threats,'' Perno said. Judges in other court branches were
also told of the call.
</TEXT>
