<FIRST>u i PM-MarcosTrial     09-07 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Trial,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Hears $810-Million Suit Against Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today began hearing an $810
million lawsuit against Ferdinand Marcos based on the former
president's tax returns.
   It is the first case against Marcos that has gone to trial in the
Philippines since he was ousted three years ago.
   In all, the government has filed 35 civil suits since in 1987 to
recover $100 billion that Marcos and 300 associates are accused of
stealing during his 24 years in power. He was forced into exile in
Hawaii after a popular-military uprising ousted him in February 1986.
   Solicitor General Frank Chavez said he expects to call as many as
20 witnesses and hopes the trial will persuade courts in Switzerland
and elsewhere to speed up proceedings to recover money Marcos
allegedly invested abroad.
   ``This is the first real, significant step toward the recovery of
ill-gotten wealth,'' Chavez said.
   In the case, being heard in the nation's anti-graft court, the
government is seeking $476 million in damages and recovery of up to
$334 million in property Marcos and his wife, Imelda, allegedly
purchased in New York.
   Government lawyers said they will argue that Marcos and his wife
owned properties worth far more than they could afford based on
assets declared in income tax returns.
   Assistant Solicitor General Romeo de la Cruz told the three-judge
panel that Marcos' presidential annual salary totaled $71,000 for
his nearly quarter-century in power. Mrs. Marcos earned $34,000
during nine years as minister of human settlements and governor of
the Metro Manila Commission, de la Cruz said.
   Eliseo Pitargue, intelligence chief of the Bureau of Internal
Revenue, testified that between 1960 and 1984, the couple declared
total assets equivalent to $657,000 at current exchange rates.
   They paid nearly $271,000 in income taxes in that time, Pitargue
said.
   Chavez said Marcos' tax records will ``establish the patently
gross and scandalously disproportionate acquisition of Mr. Marcos on
the basis of his declared wealth.''
   Marcos' lawyers, Rafael Recto and Juan David, were in the
courtroom but told reporters they are not representing the couple.
Recto said he will report to Marcos on the proceedings.
   ``This is all a big charade,'' Recto told reporters before the
proceedings adjourned until Friday. ``This case will take about 100
years more.''
   Marcos had insisted on his right to defend himself, but the court
ruled he forfeited it by ignoring subpoenas delivered to his
Honolulu home.
   President Corazon Aquino, Marcos' successor, has refused to allow
him to return, citing national security. Marcos is reported in
critical condition at a Honolulu hospital, where he has been
confined since January with heart, kidney and lung failure.
   Marcos and his wife were indicted by a U.S. federal grand jury
last year on racketeering charges for allegedly pillaging the
Philippine treasury and investing some of the money in the United
States.
   Mrs. Marcos denied the charges and is free on $5 million bail.
Marcos was temporarily separated from the case because of failing
health.
   The Marcoses have never been charged with a criminal offense in a
Philippine court because the government fears they would invoke
their constitutional right to return to face their accusers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
