<FIRST>r a PM-MBTASuit     09-07 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MBTA Suit,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>MBTA Settles Suit Over Racial Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city transit agency has agreed to pay at least
$689,000 to the estate and children of a black man who was struck
and killed by a subway train after being chased into a station by a
gang of whites in 1982.
   The settlement was reached in July and made public Wednesday by
the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority in response to a
Freedom of Information Act request by The Boston Globe.
   William F. Atkinson Jr., a 30-year-old janitor, died after
fleeing a group of white men who chased him in the city's Dorchester
section. In 1985, two men were convicted of manslaughter and three
of assault in the attack.
   The settlement stemmed from a $10 million negligence and
wrongful-death suit filed by the mothers of Atkinson's children,
ages 10 and 19.
   The suit alleged that MBTA workers neglected to notify police
immediately when Atkinson and a friend fled into the station and
failed to alert train operators that Atkinson had run onto the
tracks.
   The suit also claimed that the train that hit Atkinson was
operating without headlights.
   The MBTA also agreed to pay $138,000 to Atkinson's estate, of
which some will go to his children. The agency will also pay the
children at least $551,000 in installments for the rest of their
lives, the Globe said today.
   The children are Atkinson's sole heirs because their mothers
never married him.
   Atkinson was walking along a street around 12:30 a.m. with a
white friend, William Grady, when a group of whites began shouting
racial epithets, hurling bottles and threatening to kill the pair,
authorities said.
   The suit claimed that William Davulis, a coin changer, failed to
call police when Atkinson ran into the station and called for help.
It was not until Davulis saw Grady punched that he finally called
for help, the suit alleged.
   Davulis called police a second time after he was initially placed
on hold but left for home before police arrived, the suit said. MBTA
police arrived seven minutes later, looked around, saw no one, and
left, the Globe reported.
</TEXT>
