<FIRST>r a PM-TrainCollision     09-07 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Collision,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten Injured in Collision of Two Freight Trains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOWARDSVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two freight trains collided and derailed
early today, injuring 10 people, authorities said.
   None of the injuries appeared serious but some of those hurt were
being taken to two hospitals, said Albemarle County police Commander
Scott Hambrick.
   Three engines and 23 cars jumped the tracks and spilled coal in
the 6:20 a.m. collision 60 miles west of Richmond, said Commander
Tom Maxwell.
   Lloyd Lewis, a spokesman for CSX Transportation in Jacksonville,
Fla., said it is not known how the trains ended up on the same track.
   The eastbound train was moving down the single-track line and had
been cleared to move onto a siding when a westbound train came
around the curve and hit it, Lewis said. He said crew members of
both trains were injured.
   The eastbound train was moving slowly or standing still at the
time; the other train's speed isn't known, he said.
