<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1029EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ActressStalker     09-07 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Actress Stalker,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Opens Play As Fan Put Under Psychiatric Observation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fan who pursued Justine Bateman for
months was put under psychiatric observation for holding police at
bay outside a theater and threatening to kill himself if the actress
didn't talk to him, authorities said.
   Bateman, who played shopping-crazy Mallory Keaton in the TV
series ``Family Ties,'' was not inside at the time but went on stage
hours later for the opening of the play ``Lulu,'' in which she has
the title role of a femme fatale.
   Authorities said John Thomas Smetek, 39, of Houston, imagined he
was romantically involved with with the 23-year-old Bateman. He was
taken to Highland Hospital after his arrest Wednesday at the
Berkeley Repertory Theater.
   Smetek was booked for investigation of weapons offenses. Bail was
set at $25,000.
   ``She just hopes that he seeks the help he needs,'' said
Bateman's publicist, Cindy Guagenti.
   Smetek kept police at bay for three hours, holding a loaded gun
to his abdomen and forcing cancellation of a midday rehearsal. ``He
just wants to talk with her and indicate his love-fixation with
her,'' said Lt. Robert Peters.
   Earlier this year, police said, Smetek claimed to be a producer
and tried to speak to Bateman at the ``Family Ties'' sound stage in
Hollywood.
   He first appeared outside the Berkeley theater Friday, and
Bateman ``more or less brushed him off,'' Peters said. When she saw
him the next day, she notified police, who questioned Smetek, but
``he really hadn't committed any crimes.''
   Richard Griffoul, a spokesman for the theater, said the theater
had hired security guards and circulated Smetek's description among
employees.
   ``Justine was aware that he was pursuing her and took the
situation seriously,'' said Guagenti.
   ``It's no joke,'' said Griffoul. ``This type of thing is the
worst scenario for a person in the public eye.''
   The incident was the latest in a series of security threats to
celebrities.
   On July 18, actress Rebecca Schaeffer, who appeared in the TV
series ``My Sister Sam,'' was shot to death at the door to her Los
Angeles apartment. A 19-year-old described as an obsessed fan has
been charged.
</TEXT>
