<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TVMarti 1stLd-Writethru a0453 09-07 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Marti, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Television May `Invade' Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, By the, with 2 grafs to show the types of
programs that could be broadcast to Cuba. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Proponents
say.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is planning to use what may
be the ultimate weapon against Fidel Castro's Cuba: television.
   By the end of the year, a million or more Soviet-made TV sets are
expected to tune in six hours a day, seven days a week to
American-made news programs and the best reruns Hollywood has to
offer, courtesy of the U.S. Information Agency.
   Could programs such as ``Dynasty,'' ``Days of Our Lives'' and pro
bowling lure big Cuban audiences away from state-run TV?
   Proponents say Cubans will flock to their sets, as they
apparently did with Radio Marti, and take their first uncensored
look at the outside world in 30 years.
   But critics say TV Marti may harden anti-American attitudes in
Cuba, violate international communications laws and cause massive
headaches for Florida broadcasters who may find themselves blacked
out by TV Marti's powerful signal or who may be bludgeoned by
retaliatory broadcasts from Havana.
   President Bush supports sending TV to Cuba, as do many members of
Congress and Cuban exile groups.
   But the plan has faced some powerful opponents, including Sen.
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, and the National Association of Broadcasters.
   After three years of rancorous debate over the wisdom of such an
enterprise, the House and Senate this year voted money to begin TV
Marti testing this fall.
   But the Senate, before it appropriated $7.5 million in July for a
90-day TV Marti test, agreed to hold up funds for full operation
until the Senate Foreign Relations Committee holds hearings on
whether TV Marti would violate U.S. treaty obligations.
   The House earlier authorized $32 million for TV Marti over the
next two years, and the House and Senate measures are awaiting
resolution in conference committee.
   If the spending plan gains final congressional approval, the USIA
will begin satellite relays of Spanish-language programs from
Washington to a receiving station in Cudjoe Key, Fla. There, weather
permitting, the signals will be fed to a transmitter aboard a giant
balloon tethered two miles above the Atlantic, and thence to Cuba
some 90 miles away.
   Cubans, TV Marti backers say, are eagerly awaiting U.S.
television.
   ``My understanding is they can't wait for it to start,''
Jacqueline Tillman, executive director of the Cuban-American
National Foundation in Washington, said Wednesday.
   ``Radio Marti has, and hopefully TV Marti will as well, provide
views to the Cuban people that they are not receiving.''
   Tillman said Radio Marti has helped nurture human rights groups,
made the Cuban populace aware of the number of Cuban army casualties
in Angola, the level of oppression in Cuba, AIDS and the new era of
openness in the Soviet Union and East Bloc.
   ``All that news is frequently censored by the Cuban government
media, so the promise of TV Marti, with pictures, is very
important,'' she said.
   Cuban officials have labeled TV Marti ``anti-Cuban propaganda''
and said they will take appropriate measures against it. When Radio
Marti was launched in May 1985, Cuba briefly tried to jam the
broadcasts.
   The National Association of Broadcasters has lobbied against TV
Marti, saying it could wreak havoc on U.S. stations, which already
are subject to periodic radio blasts from enormously powerful Cuban
transmitters.
   ``The idea is technically flawed and there are no provisions to
protect U.S. broadcasters from either direct interference from TV
Marti's signal or retaliatory broadcasts from Cuba,'' NAB spokesman
Walt Wurfel said Wednesday.
   ``Cuba has demonstrated in the past it has powerful transmitters
that can cause interference to U.S. radio stations'' from Florida to
North Carolina and as far west as Des Moines, Iowa, Wurfel said.
   Some Cuban-American groups also oppose TV Marti.
   Manuel R. Gomez, president of the Cuban-American Committee Fund,
wrote recently in a New York Times op-ed piece that TV Marti
violates a 1982 treaty that stipulates that normal TV transmission
wavelengths are for domestic, national use only.
   ``The creation of TV Marti would surely be perceived by Cuba as a
hostile act,'' Gomez said. ``The Cuban community in the U.S. will
suffer the brunt of Cuba's displeasure, as we did after Radio Marti,
when Cuba virtually closed off all family visits to the island.''
</TEXT>
