<HEAD>Aoun Criticizes U.S. for Withdrawing Embassy Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Aoun criticizing U.S. for
recalling embassy staff. Pickup 3rd pvs, ``The artillery...'' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NSSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian army commander, Gen. Michel
Aoun, today said the U.S. decision to remove its diplomats from
Lebanon was based on ``half-truths, hearsay and downright black
propaganda.''
   Aoun lashed out at the United States during a news conference in
his underground bunker hours after another artillery battle between
Christian and Moslem forces left at least two people dead and seven
injured.
   The U.S. staff at the Beirut embassy was evacuated on Wednesday
amid souring relations with Aoun and a protest at the facility
during which hundreds of Christians demanded the United States press
Syria to end the fighting.
   On Saturday, the 54-year-old Maronite Catholic charged that the
United States has ``sold Lebanon to Syria'' out of fear for the
lives of eight Americans held hostage by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
groups in Lebanon.
   He compared his war against the Syrians to the American war of
independence and called on the American people to support the
Christians.
   The U.S.-trained general was clearly angered by U.S. State
Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler's remark that the 30 U.S.
diplomats were pulled out because he had threatened them with a
``good dose of Christian terrorism.''
   She said an unidentified Christian leader told diplomats they
moved in and out of the compound in the Christian sector of Beirut
``at their own risk.''
   Aoun said during the hour-long news conference that Ms.
Tutwiler's remark was ``a calculated but crude personal attack on me.
   ``It's an attack perhaps born of desperation, rather than
exasperation at the continued Lebanese resistance, and based at best
on half-truth, hearsay and downright black propaganda at which we
all know the State Department excels.''
   Lebanon's Ambassador to Washington, Abdallah Bouhabib, also
disputed the U.S. charge that American diplomats were exposed to
terrorism.
   ``We think that there was no danger whatsoever for the American
diplomats there,'' the envoy said. He appealed to Americans to
``support all the Lebanese, Moslems and Christians, in our war of
liberation'' against Syria's 40,000 troops in Lebanon who the
Christians refer to as an occupation force.
   Police said two people were killed and seven wounded in five
hours of shelling before dawn today. The fighting ended a week of
diminished fighting in the six-month confrontation between Aoun's
forces and the Syrians.
   The deaths raised the casualty toll since the fighting erupted
March 8 to at least 830 killed and 2,462 wounded, nearly all of them
civilians.
   The artillery battles began late Wednesday, 12 hours after the
American diplomats were airlifted by U.S. Navy helicopter to Cyprus,
100 miles away.
</TEXT>
