<FIRST>r a PM-AgentsShot     09-07 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agents Shot,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Informant, Three Others Arrested in Shooting of Agents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The informant who helped arrange a Border
Patrol sting aimed at smuggling of illegal aliens was arrested on
suspicion of murder after the bust went awry. One federal agent was
slain and his partner wounded.
   Four people in all were arrested in the shooting in a convenience
store parking lot early Wednesday.
   Agent Keith Connelly, 42, an 18-year Border Patrol veteran, died
of a gunshot wound to the chest. His partner, Ted Jordan, also shot
in the chest, was downgraded from serious to critical condition
today.
   Connelly and Jordan had arranged through the informant, an
illegal alien farmhand, to meet a group of smugglers at the store,
said J. William Carter, chief Border Patrol agent. He said the
agents posed as employers offering to pay about $500 for the alien
and were about to make arrests when they were shot.
   The agents had met the informant Saturday, and he did not tell
them the smugglers would be armed, Carter said. After the shooting,
the informant fled.
   Authorities could not immediately say what his role was in the
shootings.
   ``At this time I have no idea whether or not it was a setup,''
Carter said.
   Arrested on suspicion of murder and other, unspecified, charges
were Lorenzo Macias Arreola, 41, Florentino Nunez Mujica, 31, and
Rosura Rodriguez, 22, all of Los Angeles, and Albert Serrano
Saldana, 18, of Costa Mesa, Calif.
   Authorities have not identified which one was the informant.
Police Capt. Pat Rhames said Rodriguez apparently was not involved
directly in the shootings.
   One of the downed agents fired before backup agents arrived and
began shooting, Carter said. It was not known if any suspects were
shot, but one was bleeding, said Sgt. Jerry Dyer, head of the SWAT
team that sealed off the area.
   Two suspects sped off in a station wagon and two others ran in
opposite directions, Dyer said. The car was abandoned a few blocks
away. Police arrested the first suspect within an hour of the
shooting, and the final suspect was dragged out of a yard around
7:20 a.m., police said.
