<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-BushRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0451 09-07 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Goes on the Road to Promote Drug Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New throughout from Bush speeches in Baltimore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today praised ``the courage and
determination'' of the government of Colombia for extraditing an
accused major drug trafficker to the United States and warned
against letting critics of his anti-narcotics strategy ``lose the
war.''
   Bush, addressing the annual convention of the American Legion,
appealed to the veterans to rally behind his anti-drug and
anti-crime measures to help ``free our country from the fear of
drugs and crime.''
   The president, recalling a now-famous campaign gaffe he made ast
last year's Legion convention, also jokingly told the veterans to
``remember Pearl Harbor.'' Bush shocked the convention on Sept. 7,
1988, by saying it was Pearl Harbor Day. The day actuall is Dec. 7.
   Bush said the extradition Wednesday of Eduardo Martinez Romero,
indicted in Atlanta on charges of laundering money for the Medellin
drug cartel, ``sends a strong signal of the courage and
determination of President Barco and the Colombian government to
deal with this scourge which drugs are inflicting on all of us.''
   He said his $7.9 billion anti-drug package, unveiled in a speech
to the nation Tuesday night, ``will require the bravery and
sacrifice that Americans have shown before and must again.''
   ``As veterans, you know how battles are often fought, house by
house, block by block. Well, we'll win this battle the same way.
We're going to win win it kid by kid, neighborhood by
neighborhood,'' said the president.
   Democrats have charged the Bush drug plan is underfunded and
inadequate to meet the menace.
   To them, Bush replied, ``Some, incredibly, say it's not enough.
This from the very people who oppose the death penalty. It's that
kind of thinking that's lost too many battles.
   ``So let's not let these critics lose the war,'' said Bush. ``I
ask you to support our crime plan and also the other parts of our
drug strategy.''
   Bush, who entered the convention hall wearing his American Legion
Post 77 cap from his hometown of Houston, also attacked the
House-passed defense authorization bill and commended the Legion's
support of his call for a constitutional amendment to protect the
flag.
   Legion officials presented him with petitions signed by a million
people in support of a constitutional amendment.
   He said the House-passed $295 billion defense budget ``is totally
unacceptable to the commander-in-chief of the United States armed
forces.''
   He charged that the House version, now headed for compromising
with a Senate defense bill, would ``strip money from programs
crucial'' to modernizing strategic weapons, including the mobile
Midgetman missile and putting the MX missile on rail cars.
   Recalling his campaign gaffe, Bush said, ``Today surprisingly is
Sept. 7. Can you believe it? And I'm determined not to repeat the
mistake I made exactly one year ago when I referred to this as Pearl
Harbor Day. ... As long as I live I'll remember the gasp from the
audience.''
   From the convention. the president went to nearby Fort McHenry
for a ceremony marking the 175th anniversary of the Battle of
Baltimore in the War of 1812 against the British, which inspired
Francis Scott Key to write ``The Star-Spangled Banner.''
   Standing before a 90-foot white flagpole, Bush called it ``one of
America's most hallowed shrines.'' He said Baltimore ``stopped a
British invasion and preserved our independence'' in ``one of the
greatest chapters in the American experience.''
   The speeches in the Baltimore area kicked off a series of
out-of-town appearances to drum up support for the anti-drug
strategy. On Friday he heads to New Orleans to deliver the same
message.
   Although the drug plan doesn't call for direct use of U.S.
troops, it proposes sending some drug offenders to military-style
boot camps. In addition, the administration is seriously considering
using National Guard forces for marijuana eradication, said drug
policy director William J. Bennett.
   Bush, in a series of appearances Wednesday in behalf of his
program, struck back at Democrats who attacked his program.
   While apologizing for getting ``down into the trenches of
domestic politics,'' he told an audience that included a group of
Latin American ambassadors: ``I couldn't help but notice that the
minute I finished speaking, there was the predictable response by
some that we haven't done enough.''
   On Capitol Hill, some Democrats pushed the case for raising taxes
to finance an all-out fight against narcotics with Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., declaring: ``Unless the president supports the
tax increases that will be necessary to fight this war, the drug
dealers are going to win.''
   House Speaker Thomas Foley, D-Wash., said that ``without the
administration's support, the idea of raising taxes is futile.''
   Bush has rejected new taxes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
