<FIRST>r i PM-SoccerViolence 1stLd-Writethru   09-07 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soccer Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0493,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Hooligans Hustled Out of Sweden</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Thatcher quote, ferry refusing passage
to some Britons, raises news report of attack near train station. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish police hustled hundreds of
English soccer hooligans out of the country today after they
ransacked shops and scuffled with rowdy Swedish youths.
   Police said 102 Britons and 106 Swedes were arrested before and
after Wednesday's World Cup qualifying match, which ended in a 0-0
draw.
   Duty officer Lennart Norden said 78 people spent the night in
jail.
   Newspapers ran a picture of two youths, one with a raised club in
his hand, kicking a man outside a Stockholm train station. Dozens of
people looked on.
   A few Britons and Swedes may be charged with assault and
vandalism, but nearly all the foreigners have been freed and given
48 hours to leave Sweden, said Superintendent Kurt Nilsson.
   In London, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher called the fans'
behavior ``a disgrace to Britain,'' and her government asked soccer
officials to cancel a visit by the national team to the Netherlands
in December.
   ``I am always horrified if there is any difficulty with football
fans abroad,'' she said.
   Scandinavian Seaways said today it refused passage to about 20
Britons, fearing violence. It bought back return tickets from one
group and volunteered to pay for 10 people to find another way home.
   ``We didn't want them on board,'' said a spokesman.
   The shipping line said it confiscated passports of another 30
passengers, and threatened to turn over the documents to British
police if there was any problem at sea.
   About 600 policemen at the Rasunda Stadium in suburban Stockholm
kept the British fans isolated in a standing terrace during the
game. Dozens of visitors were escorted directly from the stadium to
trains for the west coast ports of Goteborg and Helsingborg for the
return ferry to Britain.
   Swedes and Britons clashed later in town, but no serious injuries
were reported. The trouble ``was less than we expected,'' said
police Superintendent Sture Hoglund. One newspaper headline read:
``Police Win the Match.''
   Earlier, about 100 England supporters, mostly teen-agers,
rampaged through downtown Stockholm, throwing bottles at police
vehicles, knocking down passers-by and vandalizing shops.
   One large group of youngsters entered the Ahlens department
store, overturning flower pots and goods displays. Some looting also
was reported, Norden said.
   ``No more,'' wrote sports commentator Stefan Thylin in the
Aftonbladet daily. ``This problem seems insoluble. England must be
shut out of the European soccer community.''
   The hooliganism could effect a decision by the European soccer
clubs' governing body, UEFA, to lift a ban against English clubs
playing in Europe. The ban was imposed after England supporters were
blamed for a riot that triggered a stampede in Belgium, killing 39
spectators. The ban does not apply to the national team.
   On Monday a British fan died when he jumped off a ferry into the
North Sea. Under the influence of drugs, he panicked when companions
sprayed him with a fire extinguisher.
   Fears of hooliganism prompted the British Football Association to
ask its Swedish counterpart to cut back ticket sales in Britain.
About 1,000 visitors attended the match at Rasunda, which was filled
to its 38,500-seat capacity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
