<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-US     09-07 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-US,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Son Rules Out Relations with United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of the late Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini today ruled out relations between Iran and the United
States and said Iran's new president, Hashemi Rafsanjani, is
undoubtedly anti-American.
   Ahmad Khomeini, 43, appeared to be trying to rally radicals
against conciliatory moves toward the West expected from Rafsanjani,
who is associated with the so-called pragmatist camp in postwar Iran.
   Hatred of the United States, referred to in Iran as the ``Great
Satan,'' is strong among radicals who favor maintaining
revolutionary Islamic fervor.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Khomeini as saying:
``You know well the higher authorities of the country and our dear
president. If our president is not anti-American, who in Iran is?''
He spoke at a meeting with families of soldiers who died in the
eight-year Persian Gulf war.
   Khomeini added that Rafsanjani ``is not a person to take even one
step outside the path of the imam, and against his guidance,'' the
radio reported.
   Iranians regarded Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini as a supreme
spiritual leader, or imam. Before his death on June 3, he preached a
staunchly anti-American doctrine that ruled out any ties with
Washington.
   His son's description of Rafsanjani's anti-American credentials
would seem to make any friendly gesture toward the United States
more difficult.
   Rafsanjani, elected July 28, is known to want to shed Iran's
radical image abroad, to end Tehran's international isolation, and
to attract foreign investment and technology to rebuild the
country's war-battered economy.
   Rafsanjani recently won parliamentary approval for a 22-man
Cabinet consisting largely of technocrats, many Western-educated,
and his administration is making positive gestures to ease strains
with some foes.
   Earlier this week, Iran's deputy foreign minister, Ali Mohammad
Besharati, said 16 Western hostages, including eight Americans,
being held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem groups could be
freed if Washington releases billions of dollars in frozen Iranian
assets. Washington has made the release of the hostages a condition
for improving ties with Iran.
   The younger Khomeini used to act as a spokesman for his father
and was expected to become part of the senior leadership when his
father died.
   But he has no official role and is considered more of a symbol
for the hard-line elements with which he has allied himself.
</TEXT>
