<FIRST>r e AM-WKD--Pei     09-07 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WKD--Pei,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Designer Calls Symphony Hall One of ``Great Buildings''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Also moved as BC advance, b0366 Sept. 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: Dallas Symphony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ANDREA WEISGERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center is I.M.
Pei's first concert hall _ a once-in-a-century opportunity, and the
world famous architect knows he may never have a chance to do it
again.
   ``There aren't that many concert halls built in this world,'' the
72-year-old designer said.
   But would he do another?
   ``I tell you, you know, never say never, `No, I don't know,' but
I don't think I would be seeking it as much as I once would, because
I have done it.''
   Pei, whose buildings include the John F. Kennedy Library in
Boston, the East Wing of the National Gallery of Art and the new
Louvre in Paris, speaks lovingly of the new Dallas symphony hall and
the opportunity it presented to him.
   ``I would have to say that this is one of the great buildings
that I have had the fortune'' to design, he said. He received a $10
million commission for the Meyerson Center in 1982.
   Pei likes the feel of the 2,065-seat music chamber. It is more
vertical than horizontal, and he says it lends intimacy to the room.
   The public areas outside the music chamber presented the greatest
design challenge for Pei. The lobby area curves around the music
chamber in a series of pieces of circles, overlooked by glass that
curves and sweeps the area. ``I haven't done a work that has had
such a complex geometry,'' he said.
   Ieoh Ming Pei was born in China. His creations fuse environment
with structure.
   He attributes his rise in architectural circles to his first big
break in 1969 _ the commission for the Kennedy Library. Pei was not
well-known at the time, and the decision to bypass other masters for
him was so surprising that Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis felt it
necessary to explain the decision.
   From there, he received commissions for the Christian Science
Church Center and the John Hancock Tower in Boston, and the East
Building of the National Gallery of Art in Washington.
   With the addition of the symphony hall, there are six Pei
buildings in the Dallas area _ the ARCO Tower, One Dallas Centre,
City Hall, the Allied Bank Tower and the Field Research Center for
Mobil Oil Co. Only Boston and nearby Cambridge have more Pei
structures: 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
