<SECOND>AM-Greece-Motorcycles,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Orders Confiscation of Dangerous Drivers' Bikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor concerned about motorcycle
riders doing wheelies through city streets has ordered police to
confiscate motorcycles of riders arrested for dangerous driving,
newspapers reported Thursday.
   The motorcycles will be regarded as ``instruments used in the
committing of a crime,'' prosecutor Christos Dakouris was quoted as
saying. A court will decide whether to return the vehicles or keep
them.
   In a bid to cut down on noise pollution in 1985, traffic police
began to confiscate noisy motorcycles. Irate riders alleged some
officers confiscated parked bikes on suspicion that if they were on
the road, they would have been noisy.
   The latest moves have already drawn fire from the nation's
estimated 196,674 motorcyclists.
   ``These decisions are absurd,'' Yannis Efraimidis, president of
the Greek Motorcycle Club, told the Athens daily Proti. Six-time
Greek motorcycle champion Dimitris Papandreou questioned the
legality of the decision.
   A spokesman for the traffic department said officers had not
received the prosecutor's order to confiscate motorcycles, but Proti
reported that the first victim of the order was arrested Wednesday
for racing in the city and that his motorcycle would be held at
least until his trial in January.
