<SECOND>AM-Peru-Drugs,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peru's Garcia Wants European Help for Bush Anti-Drug Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alan Garcia of Peru on Thursday urged
Western Europe to join the fight against drugs to bolster President
Bush's new initiative.
   Garcia, whose country is a major producer of cocaine, called
Bush's plan ``serious'' but said it is incomplete without support
from members of the European Economic Community.
   One element of Bush's plan would offer $261 million in aid to
military and police forces in Colombia, Bolivia and Peru where
cocaine is produced.
   ``The (drug) problem involves the entire international community
and not only the producing nations and the United States,'' Garcia
told a news conference. ``I believe that the dialogue that has begun
is incomplete without an active participation by the European
Economic Community.''
   Garcia stopped briefly in Rome for meetings with Pope John Paul
II and Italian political leaders en route home from the summit of
non-aligned nations in Yugoslavia.
   Garcia met with the pope for 30 minutes at his summer residence
in the Alban Hills south of Rome. The Vatican listed the meeting as
private and released no details.
   Earlier, Garcia called on Italian President Francesco Cossiga and
met with Socialist leader Bettino Craxi.
   Craxi said after the meeting that the fight against drugs can be
effective only if it includes a crackdown on places of production.
``It's an international problem, not only American,'' he said.
