<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Drugs     09-07 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Drugs,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Indicts 44 People in Italy-US Drug Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REGGIO CALABRIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge indicted 44 people Thursday
on charges of involvement in a Mafia drug ring, including a Roman
Catholic priest who lived in New York, the Italian news agency ANSA
reported.
   The indictments came as part of an investigation that resulted in
more than 200 arrests in the United States and Italy in the spring
of 1988 in connection with the ring, which smuggled heroin to the
United States in exchange for cocaine.
   Investigating Magistrate Enzo Macri of the Reggio Calabria
criminal court, who issued the indictments, said Reggio Calabria, in
southern Italy, ``represented between 1986 and 1988 the terminal,
for departure and arrival, for a colossal exchange of heroin and
cocaine between Italy and the United States.''
   A Mafia-style organization known as the 'ndrangheta operates in
the Reggio Calabria area, and its members were believed to have run
the drug operation.
   FBI officials announced the breakup of the ring in April 1988.
   The priest was identified as the Rev. Lorenzo Zorza. Authorities
said Zorza and another man headed a company that sold artwork and
archaeological pieces. The profits were allegedly used to buy drugs,
ANSA said.
   Zorza, 48, a U.S. citizen, was arrested in Bologna in April 1988
and is also wanted by federal authorities in New York on drug
charges.
   The breakdown of charges in the indictment was not given by ANSA.
There was no answer Thursday afternoon at the judicial offices in
Reggio Calabria, and Macri's home number was not listed.
   Macri decided not to indict 14 other people, citing lack of
evidence, ANSA said.
   Also Thursday, police in Milan said they seized 57 pounds of
cocaine in the luggage of a Venezuelan merchant marine officer at
Milan's international airport.
   Police said the cocaine, worth $20 million, was found during
routine checks of passengers at Malpensa airport Wednesday.
</TEXT>
