<FIRST>r w AM-WaldheimReport     09-07 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waldheim Report,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Report To Contradict Howe Finding On Waldheim's Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British investigation of Kurt Waldheim's
World War II actions contradicts Deputy Prime Minister Geoffrey
Howe's finding that the Austrian president's military unit did not
torture British commandos, a Jewish organization said Thursday.
   Howe told Parliament in 1986, when he was foreign secretary, that
four British commandos captured in Nazi-occupied Greece were held by
the German Gestapo secret police rather than by Waldheim's
Wehrmacht, or armed forces, unit.
   The new British Defense Ministry report ordered by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher includes German war records which show the
commandos were transferred to Waldheim's unit in the Greek town of
Salonika, said the World Jewish Congress.
   The Defense Ministry said only that it will release its report on
the investigation in a few weeks.
   The WJC, which was instrumental in the 1986 campaign to expose
Waldheim's past as a Nazi officer, said it had been informed about
the contents of the British report and supplied some of the
documents on which the report is based.
   Records show Waldheim's duties as an intelligence officer
included prisoner interrogation, the WJC said.
   In written testimony to the U.S. Justice Department, Waldheim
contended there were no interrogations at his unit's headquarters.
Nevertheless, in 1987 the Justice Department placed Waldheim on a
list of people barred from the United States after finding he
participated in the execution of hostages and mistreatment of Allied
prisoners.
   Howe wrote British Member of Parliament Greville Janner in 1986
that his own investigation had determined the four commandos were
held in a Gestapo jail. But the Defense Ministry study says there
was no Gestapo jail in Salonika and the men were not interrogated by
the Gestapo, the WJC said.
   According to the report, the British prisoners ``suffered ill
treatment'' at the hands of Wermacht personnel working at the
detention center, the WJC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
