<FIRST>r a PM-RacialAttack     09-07 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Attack,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Judge Assigned to Racial Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The normal random rotation of judges was bypassed
and a black judge assigned to the case of a black man slain Aug. 23
by a gang of whites in Brooklyn's Bensonhurst section, a court
spokeswoman said today.
   Justice Thaddeus Owens, 70, will take over the murder case on
Sept. 18, spokeswoman Mary de Bourbon said.
   Owens, an Arkansas native who has said an uncle was the victim of
a lynch mob, is one of three blacks among the 42 state Supreme Court
justices in Brooklyn.
   The New York Post, which first reported the story today, said
court officials bypassed normal procedures _ in which judges are
randomly picked from a list _ to get an experienced and able judge
for what will be a difficult trial.
   Seven whites have been arrested in the attack on 16-year-old
Yusuf Hawkins. Police said he was ambushed and shot by a gang of
about 30 whites, many of them carrying baseball bats and clubs.
   The Post quoted Sol Wachtler, chief judge of the Court of
Appeals, as saying, ``Neither race nor gender was a factor in this
decision. Excellence was the sole criterion used in this case.''
Wachtler oversees administration of the court.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, I appointed a capable and experienced
judge and not a black judge to handle this case,'' Matthew Crosson,
a deputy chief court administrator, told the newspaper. ``The judge
who I designated happens to be black and the fact that he is black
will not affect the case.''
   On Wednesdsay, 18-year-old Joseph Fama, the alleged gunman, was
indicted on murder charges, as were two other young men earlier. The
grand jury found Fama ``shot four times at close range and struck
Yusuf Hawkins twice in the chest,'' said Assistant District Attorney
Bruce McIntyre.
   Police said Hawkins and three friends were attacked after
entering the mostly white neighborhood to buy a used car.
   Chief of Detectives Robert Colangelo said more arrests are likely.
</TEXT>
