<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Poland     09-07 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Poland,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Want Aid, Experts Sent to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the world's industrial
democracies should send economic, business and labor experts to
Poland to help that nation's new non-communist government establish
a free economy, Sen. Pete Domenici said Thursday.
   The New Mexico Republican explained his proposal as other
lawmakers urged the Bush administration to expand the modest package
of aid it has earmarked for Poland as a critical signal of political
support.
   Domenici said the team of experts he envisions would make a
complete but speedy survey of Poland's largely state-controlled
economy and recommend basic changes needed to spur investment and
free enterprise.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas said many of the
Polish leaders he spoke with when he visited Warsaw last month asked
for just such help.
   ``Poland's leaders, including its communist leaders, are wide
open to new American investment,'' said Dole.
   Dole said the Bush administration is considering ways to expand
the $100 million aid package the president announced in Warsaw
earlier this summer.
   ``I am convinced we can take some additional steps at no cost and
perhaps also find some additional resources within existing budgets
and programs,'' Dole said.
   He said although Poland needs long-term help, especially to ease
the strain caused by payments on its $39 billion foreign debt,
short-term aid is essential.
   ``There cannot be a long-term approach unless Poland's government
makes it through the short term,'' Dole said. ``That's where an
immediate American signal of support can be critical.''
   ``We in the United States, and our allies in Western Europe and
Japan, have a big security, political and economic stake in what
happens in Poland,'' Dole said.
   ``If Solidarity remains in power and succeeds in governing, the
threat of war in Central Europe will go down, democratization in
Hungary, elsewhere in Eastern Europe and even in the Soviet Union
itself will get a big boost, and the prospects for expanded private
investment in and trade with Poland will grow,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., urged support for his
three-step plan to send U.S. assistance to Poland.
   Simon introduced legislation Wednesday which would postpone
interest payments on Poland's $2.8 billion debt to U.S. banks for
three years and defer half of the interest payments due in the
following two years.
   The proposal also calls for establishment of an investment fund
to distribute $300 million for development projects in Poland for
each of three years. It would also call for spending $25 million to
help Poland modernize its telephone system.
</TEXT>
