<FIRST>u a PM-HurricaneGabrielle 2ndLd-Writethru a0511 09-07 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hurricane Gabrielle, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0511,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gabrielle Veers Away From U.S. Mainland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with noon positions, wind speed dropping
to 105 mph. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge but weaker Hurricane Gabrielle should skirt
Bermuda sometime after midnight with high winds and big ocean
swells, but the East Coast will get little more than heavy surf,
forecasters said today.
   Forecasters said it appeared the storm center would pass 200 to
300 miles east of Bermuda, far enough away for the island to escape
destructive tropical storm-force winds. Swells of more than 20 feet
were reported in Bermuda this morning.
   ``They'll get some showers, some winds and definitely some surf
problems,'' Bob Sheets, director of the National Hurricane Center,
said Wednesday night.
   Gabrielle's top sustained winds dropped from a high of 135 mph to
105 mph as it swirled north on a path far from the United States,
but the storm was so large that swells of five to 13 feet were
recorded more than 1,500 miles away, from Florida to New England.
   ``We have a very large wind field around this hurricane,'' Sheets
said.
   Winds 39 mph or higher _ a speed that forecasters define as
tropical storm-force _ stretched 250 miles to the west and 300 miles
to the east as Gabrielle curved north in the mid-Atlantic.
   At noon EDT, Gabrielle's center was located near 29.9 degrees
north latitude and 60.0 degrees west longitude, or about 320 miles
east-southeast of Bermuda. It was heading north at 15 mph.
   Gabrielle is the largest and most powerful hurricane of the
season, rating just below last year's Hurricane Gilbert, which
ravaged the Caribbean with 155 mph winds.
   Far to the north of Gabrielle, Felix maintained its status as a
minimal hurricane, with winds of 75 mph. The storm was drifting
slowly out in the Atlantic and was no threat to land, forecasters
said.
   At noon EDT, Felix's center was near 39.5 degree north latitude
and 48.0 degrees west longitude, or about 900 miles west of the
Azores. It was drifting north at 7 mph.
   Felix is the sixth and Gabrielle the seventh named storm of the
1989 Atlantic hurricane season. Storms are named when their winds
reach 39 mph and are classified as hurricanes when they grow to 74
mph.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
