<SECOND>AM-BRF--Train Collision,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Suffer Minor Injuries in Collision of Two Freight Trains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOWARDSVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two freight trains collided head-on
early Thursday near the James River, injuring nine people and
spilling 100 gallons of diesel fuel, authorities said.
   Three engines and 23 cars of the two CSX trains were derailed.
But three tanker cars carrying hazardous material were untouched,
police said.
   Albemarle County police commander Scott Hambrick said four cars,
one carrying coal, dumped their loads onto Virginia 626, and one was
leaking a white powder identified as borax, which is not hazardous.
One engine leaked about 100 gallons of diesel fuel which was dammed
by firefighters, Hambrick said.
   ``We have no idea why the trains ended up on the same track,'' he
said.
   Lloyd Lewis, a spokesman for CSX Transportation in Jacksonville,
Fla., said one train was heading west from Richmond and the other
was heading east from Clifton Forge.
   Lewis said all of the injured were from the train crews, and all
were hospitalized in good condition.
