<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Violence, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0544,1031</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Day Violence Widespread, Police Accused of Brutality</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 7th pvs, `Police Maj...' to UPDATE with
police updating their death count. Pickup 8th pvs, `The independent...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police marched through townships
firing shotguns and tear gas to break up rallies by people
protesting the segregated national elections, and at least 25 people
were killed, activists said today.
   Media reports and a church monitoring group said at least 100
people were injured in more than 20 townships, and one police
officer said other officers caused the unrest by indiscriminately
beating and whipping blacks.
   Essa Moosa and Associates, a Cape Town law firm, said 25 people
died Wednesday night and early today in seven black and mixed-race
townships outside the city.
   More violence broke out this afternoon, with white riot squads
firing shot guns and tear gas at crowds of dancing and chanting
young people in the Lavender Hill township near Cape Town, a
journalist on the scene said. There was no word on casualties.
   ``They (police) got out of the van and ran down to the road where
the students were coming and started firing. There was a lot of tear
gas,'' said the journalist, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu said earlier today that 23
people had been killed during election day violence, adding: ``We
expect the numbers of the dead to grow.''
   Police Maj. Reg Crewe in Pretoria said at least seven people
``but certainly not as many as 23'' died in violence in the Cape
Town area Wednesday night. He said the circumstances were being
investigated.
   A later police statement said 12 deaths occurred in the Cape Town
area: seven during violence associated with a feud between factions
in the black township of Khayelitsha, and five during mob violence
of unknown origin in three mixed-race townships. Police said more
than 50 people were arrested.
   The independent South African Press Association described the
area outside Cape Town as ``a war zone ... as residents danced
around dozens of burning barricades blocking streets in the area and
police fired repeatedly at groups of youths.''
   One local newspaper, Grassroots, said it had confirmed 15 bodies
were in a local mortuary.
   Acting President F.W. de Klerk's governing National Party
narrowly retained its majority in Wednesday's parliamentary
elections, which excluded the black majority.
   An anti-apartheid activist, the Rev. Allan Boesak, said de
Klerk's presidency ``now sits in a pool of blood.''
   ``People who begin a new term of office with a massacre ... have
no right to be in government,'' he said.
   The National Party has ruled South Africa for 41 years.
   The Western Province Council of Churches said at least 100 people
were injured, including children.
   Groote Schuur Hospital in Cape Town said 40 people were admitted
Wednesday night with birdshot injuries. Gatesville Medical Center
said it treated at least 20 people hit by birdshot, including a
4-year-old. Tyberberg Hospital reported 20 admissions for ammunition
wounds.
   Police reported 200 instances of unrest nationwide from Wednesday
through today, including rock throwing, arson and illegal
gatherings, police said.
   Police said they used shotguns, rubber bullets, whips and tear
gas to disperse placard-carrying marchers as well as people throwing
stones. In at least two instances, police said they whipped and
arrested demonstrators who sat down when they were told to disperse.
   Police said seven officers around the country, including four
near Cape Town, suffered minor injuries when they were hit by rocks
and bottles.
   On Wednesday, journalists saw five white policemen flanked by a
yellow armored vehicle walking through the mixed-race township of
Manenberg outside Cape Town. They said the officers slowly raised
their shotguns and tear gas rifles and fired straight ahead and down
side streets as they marched along.
   A crowd of mixed-race youths, men and women had set fire to
burning barricades of tree branches, newspaper and mattresses at
each end of the street.
   They were dancing and talking in the street, but scattered behind
fences and into houses when the armored vehicle rolled over the
first barricade. One or two youths threw rocks toward the police,
but hit nothing.
   A mixed-race police lieutenant in the Mitchell's Plain area of
Cape Town said Wednesday night that police riot squads were ``the
cause of the riots'' in that area on Tuesday.
   Lt. Gregory Rockman, 30, said a white riot-squad major threatened
to detain him under emergency regulations when he tried to stop
officers from hitting bystanders as well as students holding a
placard demonstration.
   ``They just stormed and hit them whenever they felt like doing
that _ they hit them like mad,'' Rockman said.
   He said four officers joined to beat a woman waiting for a bus
with whips.
   ``She was jumping up and down. Then she ran and they chased after
her,'' Rockman. ``One of them even fell and then got up again and
chased her, hitting her. Their was an elderly man (who) collapsed
because of the beating.''
   As the local crime prevention officer, Rockman said he had tried
to defuse trouble by telling the students they could ``do their
thing'' and then disperse in 20 minutes.
   He said he took one riot squad out of view of the students, but
that another squad repeatedly charged into ``the normal curious
crowds,'' including shoppers.
   ``They were just hitting people. They couldn't care if they were
innocent bystanders or not,'' Rockman said. ``They were running
after them even when they were fleeing, hitting them.
   ``It seemed to me that they were enjoying themselves, feasting on
the people. `You could just see the killer instinct in their eyes.''
   Cape Town police Maj. Gen. Phillipus Fourie confirmed that
Rockman had been summoned to his office Wednesday to discuss police
matters but he would not comment further.
   Tutu said that Rockman could face retaliation, but that he was
``going to be given very wide recognition in the black community''
for his willingness to describe police action.
</TEXT>
