<FIRST>r i AM-NATOExercises     09-07 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO Exercises,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Opens Annual Fall Exercises For 205,000 troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arms Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO on Thursday began its annual fall
maneuvers, which this year involve 205,000 troops in 16 land, air
and sea exercises throughout Western Europe.
   NATO's Allied Command Europe said its Autumn Forge maneuvers
began with the arrival of a U.S. Air Force C-130 Hercules transport
plane from West Germany's Rhein-Main Air Base to participate in
``Armada Exchange,'' the first of the fall maneuvers.
   U.S. Gen. John Galvin, NATO's top military commander in Europe,
said in a statement that military maneuvers remain necessary despite
the warming in East-West relations in recent years.
   ``There is probably no need to remind anybody that while we can
be hopeful about the success of arms control negotiations, there is
still a requirement for national and collective security,'' Galvin
said in the statement issued by Allied Command Europe headquarters
in southern Belgium.
   ``Our potential adversaries are still quite big and
unpredictable.''
   In ``Armada Exchange,'' 2,500 Allied Mobile Force troops from
Belgium, West Germany, Luxembourg, Britain and the United States
join 1,500 Italian soldiers and air forces for a land and air
exercise in northeastern Italy.
   The multinational force is a rapid-deployment unit for use on the
NATO flanks. It is to be deployed in times of crises before the
outbreak of war, when the key aim is to deter an attack.
</TEXT>
