<FIRST>u a PM-BakkerTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0462 09-07 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bakker Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0462,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Resumes After Judge Rules Bakker Competent</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CH1,4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with this morning's testimony.
PICKS UP 14th graf pvs, `Nelson said...'; DELETES last graf to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL raised nearly $17 million in one week
during 1986, but its Heritage Grand Hotel was almost constantly
short of cash, the jury in Jim Bakker's fraud trial was told today.
   The testimony came after a day after the judge pronounced the TV
evangelist competent to stand trial. A government psychiatrist had
testified that Bakker suffered a ``panic attack'' last week but is
not going crazy.
   Delores Jones, who worked in PTL's cash management office,
testified this morning that during the week of May 31, 1986, the
ministry collected $13,000 from passing the plate at Sunday services
and $7,000 from the TV audience of ``The Jim and Tammy Show.''
   ``It was sometimes more, sometimes less,'' she said when asked
whether the $20,000 in cash collections for the week were unusual.
   Ms. Jones said the rest of the $17 million ``would have to be the
Lifetime Silver 1000 Account,'' one of several ``lifetime
partnership'' programs that offered $1,000 contributors three
nights' free lodging each year for life.
   Prosecutors say Bakker and other PTL executives diverted to their
own use more than $4 million of the $158 million raised by
partnerships from 1984 to 1987. If convicted on all counts, Bakker
could receive 120 years in prison and more than $5 million in fines.
   William Maybrey, general manager of Heritage Grand Hotel in
1984-85, testified today that the management contract with Brock
Hotel Corp. required that half the 500 rooms be set aside for
lifetime partners. Brock employed Maybrey to run the hotel.
   He said PTL had agreed to keep a $300,000 balance in an operating
account for the hotel, but he warned Bakker in two memos in 1985
that the account was at least $195,000 short of the requirement.
Brock had to pay employees out of its own funds at one point because
of the shortages, Maybrey testified.
   ``It was difficult to balance the level of services with the cash
flow problems we were experiencing,'' said Maybrey.
   Last week, U.S. District Judge Robert Potter committed Bakker to
a federal prison for psychiatric evaluation after his lawyers
reported he was hallucinating and cowering under a couch. After a
competency hearing Wednesday out of sight of the jury, Potter
released Bakker.
   ``He is not going crazy,'' Dr. Sally Johnson, head of the
psychiatric team at the Federal Correctional Institution in Butner,
told the judge. ``He has no hidden mental illness. The stress that
he's feeling is normal.''
   Ms. Johnson said she didn't think Bakker had faked his breakdown.
She said Bakker told her that journalists at the courthouse took on
the form of frightening animals.
   In Wednesday's testimony, former fund-raiser Carol Price broke
into tears when she described trying to discourage an elderly woman
from purchasing a $1,000 lifetime partnership. She said she was
fired for complaining about PTL policy.
   ``I told her that selling a burial policy to buy a lifetime
partnership was not a good idea,'' Ms. Price said Wednesday.
   Former PTL Vice President Steve Nelson, whose fainting episode on
the stand last week was cited by doctors as triggering Bakker's
breakdown, returned to testify Wednesday.
   Nelson said he had gone to Bakker and former PTL Vice President
Richard Dortch with concerns over the number of ``lifetime
partnerships'' sold at the 500-room Heritage Grand Hotel.
   ``I told them we had problems getting people in there,'' he said.
``I told them we could not sell more memberships.''
   Ms. Price testified that workers were encouraged to sell as many
partnerships as they could, regardless of whether the hotel could
accommodate them.
   Ms. Price, who was in charge of handling partner relations, said
she took her concerns to Bakker on several occasions. She said that
when she and 10 members of her staff were fired in 1985, she asked
Nelson, her boss at the time, why she was let go.
   ``He leaned back in his chair and said, `That's the price you pay
for knowing too much and not keeping your mouth shut,''' she said,
crying. ``Ten people lost their jobs because my conscience wouldn't
let me keep my mouth shut. I carry that with me to this day.''
   Bakker, who said he was suffering from the flu, appeared more
alert during Wednesday's testimony. He smiled, chatted with
attorneys and reviewed documents.
   He showed little emotion during the morning competency hearing,
sometimes hanging his head and staring at the floor.
   Bakker, who resigned from the PTL ministry in 1987 in a
sex-and-money scandal, went on trial Aug. 28.
   Prosecutors contend Bakker oversold the partnerships and used
nearly $4 million in ministry funds to live in high style.
</TEXT>
