<FIRST>r a PM-Nuclear-Free     09-07 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear-Free,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Fights Oakland Ordinance Barring Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is suing to overturn
an Oakland ordinance barring ``nuclear weapons work'' in the city.
   The ordinance _ one of the few such nuclear-free ordinances not
considered symbolic among about 160 in the country _
unconstitutionally interferes with national defense, the Justice
Department said in a lawsuit filed Wednesday in federal court.
   The ordinance could force two federal installations employing
2,170 people to leave Oakland, the department said.
   They are the Naval Supply Center, which supplies Pacific Fleet
ships with components for nuclear weapons, and a Department of
Energy operations office overseeing weapons research at the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory east of Oakland.
   But Steve Bloom, primary author of the ballot initiative, said
the measure approved by voters in November was drafted to exclude
the Naval Supply Center, where more than 2,000 people work.
   And City Attorney Jayne Williams said the ban on nuclear weapons
work covered such activities as ``creating nuclear weapons in their
offices,'' and should not apply to an administrative office like the
DOE's.
   The lawsuit said the Constitution gives the federal government
exclusive authority over defense. The lawsuit also said the Atomic
Energy Act gives the federal government sole authority over nuclear
weapons and nuclear energy.
   The ballot initiative's sponsors countered that local communities
also have rights.
   ``We should be able to exercise the full power of local
governments to protect our health and safety and to direct policy
about what happens in our city jurisdictions,'' said Madge Strong of
the Nuclear-Free Oakland Coalition.
   Bloom added that the First Amendment should take precedence.
   ``The people of an entire city are saying, we don't want this
going on. The federal government is saying, you have no right to say
that. That ceases to be democracy,'' Bloom said.
   Williams, the city attorney, called Oakland's nuclear-free
ordinance one of the broadest in the country. Among other things, it
bans nuclear weapons work in the city in two years.
   Williams said she believed it was the first such ordinance the
federal government has challenged. A conservative legal group filed
a federal lawsuit challenging it four months ago.
</TEXT>
