<HEAD>Marcos Hospital Bill Paid; Wife Unsure of Source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone paid Ferdinand Marcos' $500,000 hospital
bill, but his wife said she was unsure exactly how the payment was
arranged.
   Eugene Tiwanak, a spokesman for St. Francis Medical Center,
confirmed Wednesday the bill had been paid in full.
   Marcos' basic intensive-care needs cost about $2,000 a day. The
former Philippine president has been hospitalized since Jan. 15 for
treatment of heart, lung and kidney ailments. He remained in very
critical condition Thursday.
   Imelda Marcos said the money might have come from loans from
friends and supporters and from assets not frozen by the courts.
   Tiwanak said the Marcoses at first were not paying their bills
and officials approached the family when the bills reached $300,000.
   In March, Mrs. Marcos asked the U.S. government to cover the
hospital costs, saying she and her husband had been brought to this
country against their will.
   Mrs. Marcos said the U.S. government never responded to that
request.
   The money paid to the hospital does not include an estimated
$250,000 owed to Marcos' doctors.
