<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Kathleen Kaufman won't have to ask her
husband how his day at work went for a while: She's a juror in a
malpractice case over which he is presiding.
   ``Yes, I'm your wife,'' Mrs. Kaufman responded Wednesday when
Wayne County Circuit Judge Charles Kaufman asked if she was related
to anyone in the courtroom.
   Mrs. Kaufman was among prospective jurors selected randomly from
lists of licensed drivers. Neither attorney struck her name from the
list, so she was seated on the jury.
   ``I didn't really know what to do with her,'' said Euel Kinsey,
the attorney representing a man suing over a wrist injury. ``But as
the judge handled the questioning, it developed that she could be
fair and impartial. It was cute, him asking her questions he already
knew the answers to.''
   ``She seemed like a nice and conscientious lady,'' defense
attorney Kenneth M. Mattson said.
   ``She'll be wonderful. She's very fair,'' the judge allowed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Final touches are being put on Lincoln's
first trashy video, but the producer isn't worried about legal
ramifications.
   In fact, Doug Boyd of the Citizen Information Center, is making
this video with the blessings of the League of Women Voters and the
Economic Development Department.
   And ``Give Trash a Second Chance'' gets only an R rating _ four
Rs, that is: reduce, reuse, recycle and recover.
   The intent of the video is to educate people about the the city's
goal of reducing the amount of trash going to its new landfill by 40
percent and to change waste disposal habits.
   ``You can't make a video and expect the problem to be solved. But
it's a part of the process, a valuable, important resource,'' Boyd
said.
   The video, which features the ``Garbage'' song by Pete Seeger,
begins with shots of people overstuffing trash cans. It includes a
shot of deep piles of garbage bags strung out for 20 miles to depict
the amount of trash the city sends to the landfill each year.
   City recycling coordinator Gene Hanlon said a follow-up recycling
``how-to'' video is in the works, funded by the $2,000 or so
remaining from the initial $5,000 grant from the League of Women
Voters.
