<FIRST>r a AM-MissAmerica-Predictions     09-07 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miss America-Predictions,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecaster Stops Predicting Winner Of Miss America Pageant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judging system of the Miss America
Pageant has changed so much that a retired statistics professor has
stopped his tradition of predicting who the new Miss America will be.
   George L. Miller of Bellevue, Wash., who retired in 1984 from
Northern Illinois University, says his statistical model was thrown
off balance by the decreasing emphasis on swimsuits and additional
emphasis on brains.
   ``The interview counts for 30 percent this year, and I can't get
any information related to the interviews,'' said Miller. ``The
swimsuit counts only for 15 percent this year. They've downgraded
swimsuits so much that it took care of poor old George.''
   Each year, Miller, 66, compiled statistics on every Miss America
contestant and past winners, tallying up a composite to set odds on
woman might win. His first year he correctly predicted Cheryl
Prewitt would be crowned Miss America 1980. He then named four more
winners over the next nine years.
   But in the past few years, his statistical odds have failed. He
gave little hope to the past two winners, saying a Tahitian dancer
and a violinist had little chance of capturing the crown. They did,
and the dancer _ Miss America 1988 Kaye Lani Rae Rafko _ turned out
to be Miller's favorite so far.
   Miller used various statistics to devise his predictions,
including height, weight, hair and eye color, academic major and
talent. He was forced to stop using bust, waist and hip measurements
after the pageant stopped releasing those figures three years ago.
   Despite the changes, he said, ``in some ways, they're improving
the pageant.''
   ``They're getting better people. They seem brighter and come from
better schools.''
   Last year's winner, Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson, attends Stanford
University and hopes to go to law school. This year's winner is to
be crowned Sept. 16.
   Pageant officials were never pleased at Miller's uninvited annual
prediction. Leonard Horn, director of the Miss America Pageant, was
not disappointed to learn Miller would not pick a winner this year.
   ``The fact that he's decided not to do it proves these young
women are individuals with varying degrees of talents and positive
characters,'' Horn said.
   Miller said he will switch from beauty queens to baseball. ``Some
people may think I'm backsliding, but some may think I'm moving
forward,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
