<DOCNO> AP890907-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Crash     09-07 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Crash,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Winds, Pilot's Decision to Take Off, Caused Cuban Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a jetliner that crashed in Havana
and killed 170 people took off in severe winds against the control
tower's advice, Cuban news reports said Thursday.
   The Soviet-made Cubana de Aviacion jet crashed into a suburb off
the end of the runway Sunday. All but one of the 126 people on board
died, and 45 people on the ground were killed.
   Gen. Rogelio Acevedo, head of the Cuban government commission
investigating the Sunday crash, said winds up to 30 mph near the end
of the Jose Marti airport runway in Havana were believed to be the
basic cause of the crash, the Cuban government news agency Prensa
Latina said.
   The tower advised the pilot, Capt. Armando Oliveros, to wait
before leaving, and the commission thinks his decision to take off
was in error, the agency quoted Acevedo as saying.
   Luigi Capalbo, 22, of Parma, Italy, was the only survivor on the
Ilyushin 62. Doctors at Hermanos Ameijeiras Hospital were treating
him for head injuries, burns over 65 percent of his body and a
broken left leg.
   Acevedo, who is president of the Civil Aeronautics Institute,
said the pilot, faced with winds of 28 to 30 mph and heavy rain,
reduced the angle of the wing flaps apparently to gain speed, but
wind drove the plane down.
   A tail wheel struck the runway and the right wing hit an antenna
at the end of the runway. The plane then lifted slightly, clearing a
concrete median on a major street, and plunged into homes, he said.
Two square blocks were destroyed.
   No indication was found of mechanical problems on the 7-month-old
plane, which had been flown 1,300 hours, he said.
   Oliveros, 51, had been flying 29 years and instructed other
pilots, the news agency said.
   Builders of the plane arrived early Thursday from the Soviet
Union to aid Cuban and Italian teams in the investigation. One of
their tasks will be to analyze data on the three flight recorders
that were recovered.
</TEXT>
