<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HomingPets     09-07 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homing Pets,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>County Considering Microchip IDs for Pets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEATON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Du Page County's Animal Control
Department wants every dog or cat to have a chip in its shoulder.
   Daniel Boyle said he would ask the County Board to approve an
ordinance requiring that microchip IDs be implanted in all animals
that bite someone and all pets reclaimed or adopted from the
county's animal shelter.
   Boyle said he would also try to persuade pet owners and
veterinarians to voluntarily implant the chips in all dogs and cats
to help identify them.
   ``This is going to be, essentially, the ultimate ID,'' Boyle said
Wednesday. ``Since the dog can't talk, maybe his chip can talk for
him.''
   If approved, the county would register the ID numbers of all the
microchipped pets.
   The chips are manfuactured by a California company, American
Veterinary Indentification Devices Inc.
   Hannis Stoddard, a veterinarian and chief executive officer of
the company, said the chips have been implanted in 5,000 prize
hunting falcons owned by a sheik of the United Arab Emirates.
   ``It's the only unalterable ID ... that can be used safely and
humanely for animals, and it does not scar or disfigure them,''
Stoddard said.
   The microchip, about the size of a grain of rice, is injected via
a syringe into the fatty tissue above the shoulder or hip of a dog
or cat. The number on the microchip can be read by a handheld
scanner.
   Boyle said a microchip injection by a veterinarian would cost $20
to $25.
</TEXT>
