<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Court-Shoreham     09-07 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Court-Shoreham,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Judge Allows Bush Administration to Enter Shoreham Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge today ruled that the Bush
administration _ the most powerful opponent to Gov. Mario Cuomo's
plan to tear down the Shoreham nuclear plant _ may enter the state
court fight against the agreement.
   Supreme Court Justice F. Warren Travers ruled that the federal
Department of Energy was an ``interested party'' through its
ownership of the Brookhaven National Laboratory on Long Island.
   There was no immediate word from the Cuomo administration on
whether it will appeal.
   Cuomo has sought to prevent the $5.5 billion plant on Long Island
from operating because of concern over whether the region can be
safely evacuated.
   Under a deal negotiated by Cuomo and the Long Island Lighting
Co., the state will buy the plant for $1 and have it dismantled. In
return, LILCO gets at least a decade's worth of annual rate
increases of about 10 percent. Its customers already pay among the
highest electric rates in the nation.
   If the deal goes through, and it has already been approved by the
required state agencies and LILCO stockholders, it will be the first
time a completed nuclear plant was torn down without having gone
into commercial operation.
   In his ruling, Travers noted that Brookhaven lies on 5,000 acres
of federal land and that the DOE intends to purchase 41,000 megawatt
hours of electricity from the Long Island Lighting Co. this year at
a cost of more than $3 million.
   ``Here, where DOE is a landowner and user of power provided by
LILCO, the court, in its discretion determines that DOE should be
allowed to and is granted permission to intervene,'' said Travers.
   Last week, state lawyers argued that DOE intervention would be
``superfluous'' and that interested parties were all represented in
a lawsuit filed against the Shoreham deal by the conservative
Atlantic Legal Foundation.
   The lawsuit before Travers argues, among other things, that Cuomo
usurped the power of the Legislature in negotiating the Shoreham
deal and that there should have been a state environmental impact
statement.
   Travers has yet to rule on the merits of those arguments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
