<UNK>Mother Teresa Admitted to Hospital</UNK>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa, who won the Nobel Peace
Prize for her work with the poor and destitute, has been admitted to
the intensive care unit of a Calcutta hospital with a heart ailment,
doctors said Thursday.
   She was admitted to a private hosptial Tuesday with high fever
and an irregular heartbeat, but her condition is stable, said Dr. A.
Bardhan, a cardiologist who treated the 79-year-old nun.
   Mother Teresa, who was given the 1979 Nobel Peace prize, became
ill Sunday night, said an aide who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   She attended mass Monday but was moved to hospital when her
condition deteriorated Tuesday, the aide said.
   The Roman Catholic nun, revered in India as a living saint, was
born in Albania. She founded the Missionaries of Charity, an order
of 3,000 nuns in 87 countries, in 1950.
 
