<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--TelephoneVandalism     09-07 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Telephone Vandalism,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telephone Cable Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEWATER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New England Telephone Co. cable was
cut early Thursday, knocking out service to tens of thousands of
customers in Massachsuetts and Rhode Island.
   The company said three fiber optic lines were cut in a
Bridgewater manhole about 2:30 a.m., but spokeswoman Claire
Silvestri said the company was not pointing blame.
   ``Let's just say that the rural location of the manhole and the
selection of the cables in the manhole seems to indicate that the
person, or persons, chose the location carefully and knew what to do
to disrupt service,'' she said.
   The Communication Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 2222 have been striking
against NET parent company NYNEX Corp. for about six weeks, but
neither union has advocated vandalism.
   The vandalism disrupted toll call service from Boston to the
region's communities and calls between Boston and Rhode Island.
Silvestri also said that customers in most communities also had
difficutly reaching an operator.
   The company offered a $50,000 reward for information leading to
the conviction of the vandals.
</TEXT>
