<SECOND>PM-Iowa-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0469,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailor's Family Rejects Navy Conclusion in Iowa Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with family reaction to report. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iowa Inquiry, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clayton Hartwig's family today rejected the
Navy's conclusion that the gunner's mate probably caused the
explosion that killed 47 sailors on the USS Iowa by shoving a
detonator between gunpowder bags.
   ``I never believed it right from the start,'' Kathy Kubicina,
Hartwig's sister, said outside her father's home following a
two-hour briefing by Navy officers this morning. ``I didn't really
hear anything I didn't hear before.''
   The family attorney, Kraig Brusnahan, said Hartwig's relatives
want a congressional investigation into the Navy probe of the April
19 blast aboard the battleship and repeated leaks to the news media
from investigators.
   ``The Navy is kind of investigating itself and clearing itself,''
said Brusnahan.
   Hartwig's father, Earl V. Hartwig, a Navy veteran, also said he
didn't believe the Navy conclusion. ``I think there was a powder
explosion _ accidental _ that caused the explosion,'' Hartwig said.
   The family was briefed at Hartwig's home by a three-officer team
led by Capt. Douglas J. Katz.
   ``This is probably one of the hardest things I've ever done in my
entire life,'' said Katz, who left the home a half hour before the
Pentagon released the report on the April 19 disaster off Puerto
Rico.
   The report said the exact cause of the explosion, the worst naval
disaster since the Vietnam War, cannot be pinpointed since the
sailors close enough to see what was going on, including Hartwig,
were all killed in the fiery blast.
   However, Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, presenting the conclusions
in Washington, said there was much ``circumstantial information''
pointing to Hartwig.
   He cited an FBI psychological profile of Hartwig ``with the
opinion that he took his own life and hoped it looked like an
accident.''
   Navy investigators had been examining the possibility that
suicide or murder was involved in the explosion.
</TEXT>
