<FIRST>r w AM-Frank-Prostitute     09-07 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frank-Prostitute,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank Defends Voiding Tickets Incurred by Aide Who Was Prostitute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Barney Frank said Thursday he used his
congressional immunity to void parking tickets incurred by a
personal aide who was also a male prostitute, but only when the
assistant had used Frank's car for official business.
   Frank, D-Mass., said he allowed the aide, Stephen L. Gobie, to
use his car for official business and also gave him authorization to
drive it when the congressman was out of town.
   The lawmaker had said earlier that he hired Gobie in July 1985 as
his housekeeper and driver, paying him from personal funds, and
fired him in August 1987.
   Frank, an acknowledged homosexual who has asked that his
situation with Gobie be investigated by the House ethics committee,
issued a statement on the parking tickets after a story on the
subject appeared in Thursday's Washington Times.
   ``Part of Mr. Gobie's uties was the use of my car on official
business and access to my car when I was away from Washington,''
Frank's statement said. ``There are some occasions when tickets were
issued even though the car was being used on official business. I
did ask that such tickets be waived. At all other times, it was my
policy to pay for tickets incurred.''
   Frank branded as ``lies'' Gobie's assertion to the Times that the
lawmaker had knowingly intervened to waive tickets the aide received
while using Frank's car to keep appointments for illicit sex.
   Gobie told the Times he used the car to transport prostitutes and
even to have sex. He previously said he operated an escort service
from Frank's Capitol Hill apartment.
   ``He knew what I was doing,'' said Gobie. ``I used to drive that
car around all the time.''
   Gobie told the Times he always left Frank's official
congressional plate on the dashboard when he used the car. He said
Frank's car was ticketed about 50 times over a year-and-a-half.
   Frank has said he paid Gobie $80 for sex after answering a
classified ad in a Washington gay newspaper in the spring of 1985.
   The representative said he then hired Gobie as his housekeeper
and driver, hoping to change his ways, but fired him when he found
out Gobie was using Frank's apartment to operate a prostitution ring.
   In Thursday's statement, Frank said, ``These and all other issues
are rightfully before the House ethics committee at my request and
will be dealt with in detail.''
</TEXT>
