<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1435EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan-Defector     09-07 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-Defector,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Pilot Says He Defected Because of Military Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese air force pilot who flew a MiG-19
jet to Taiwan said Thursday he defected because of his contempt for
the Communist government after its suppression of a movement for
democracy.
   Lt. Chiang Wen-hao, 24, told reporters he sympathizes with the
soldiers who carried out the crackdown in June, saying they had to
follow government orders.
   ``I don't want to dedicate my blood and my life to a Communist
regime that the people spit on in contempt,'' said Chiang.
   For the defection, Taiwain will pay him 206 pounds of gold worth
about $880,000. Taiwan has a sliding scale of gold rewards for
Chinese military defectors, calculated on the type of aircraft they
bring out.
   Chiang flew his Soviet-built fighter to the Nationalist-held
island of Quemoy on Wednesday from Longxi airport in China's
southern Fujian province, just over a mile away. The flight took 14
minutes.
   He was brought to Taipei on Thursday for a news conference and
told reporters he had planned to defect for two years but was
spurred to action by the June crackdown on the student-led democracy
movement at Tiananmen Square in Beijing.
   After taking off, Chiang said he kept the fighter low to escape
pursuing aircraft, but the Chinese air force apparently did not
notice he had left.
   ``I was so nervous that I didn't know if anyone followed me,'' he
said. ``I could still hear the air base's communications when I
landed at Quemoy airport.''
   Chiang said he left his parents, a sister, and his grandmother
behind.
   In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing said
``the press reports about the plane are under investigation by the
departments concerned.''
   Chiang defended the Chinese military, which fired on thousands of
residents in Beijing on June 3-4.
   ``The military stood beside the people and supported the
pro-democracy movement, but they had to carry out orders from
authorities,'' he said. ``They executed orders against their own
will. I sympathize with the soldiers. They were but the tools to
execute the orders of the Chinese Communist Party.''
   China says about 300 people died in the street clashes, including
unspecified ``dozens'' of security personnel and more than 200
civilians. Western security sources say the death toll may have been
3,000.
   Four women from the opposition Democratic Progressive Party
draped a banner outside the conference room protesting Chiang's
entry to Taiwan. They said the government should not welcome
communists while barring many Taiwanese political dissidents from
returning home.
   The last Chinese pilot to defect to Taiwan, Liu Chih-yuan, 30,
also flew a MiG-19 when he fled in 1987. The Nationalist government
rewarded him with 412 pounds of gold then valued at about $3
million. Liu, now a member of Taiwan's air force, was at the news
conference to show support for Chiang.
   Last year, gold rewards were cut by more than 50 percent after
China abolished a similar practice of rewarding defectors from
Taiwan.
   Officials said 14 Chinese military personnel have defected to
Taiwan since 1949, when the Nationalists fled to this island after
losing a civil war to the Communist forces on mainland China.
   China regards Taiwan as a renegade province and the two
technically still are at war.
   More than a dozen Nationalist air force officers have sought
asylum in China since 1949. The most recent Nationalist defection
was in February when Lt. Col. Lin Xianshun parachuted to safety as
his F-5E jet crashed in a rice paddy in Guangdong province.
</TEXT>
