<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>General in Charge of Dispersing Protest Removed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet general who reportedly ordered an army
assault that killed 19 demonstrators in the Georgian city of Tbilisi
in April has been removed from his post, officials said Thursday.
   Col. Gen. Igor Rodionov, who was head of the Transcaucasian
Military District, was replaced by Col. Gen. Valery O. Patrikeyev,
said an editor at the official Gruzinform news agency in Tbilisi,
the capital of the Georgian republic.
   Spokesman Vyacheslav Kirillov of the Soviet Defense Ministry's
International Relations Department confirmed that Rodionov had been
removed.
   Neither had any information on Patrikeyev.
   Nationalists have accused Rodionov of ordering soldiers armed
with shovels and irritating gas to attack a crowd on Tbilisi's
Rustavelli Prospekt the night of April 9.
   The protest was a demonstration for more autonomy for the
republic. Nineteen people were killed in the assault and another
young man was shot for violating a curfew that was imposed later.
   Rodionov was chosen a representative to the national Congress of
People's Deputies parliament in March, and he staunchly defended
himself during debate on the assault at the congress' first session.
   Rodionov said the protest turned into a ``pure orgy, with
anti-Soviet slogans ... appeals to overturn the government, appeals
to exterminate communists.''
   A Georgian commission accused the military of a ``planned mass
massacre.''
   The removal of Rodionov also was noted in a dispatch by the Tass
news agency in a report on Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze's
visit to Georgia.
   Tass said Shevardnadze told Georgian party officials they had
made progress in mending ethnic relations since April but that it
still was the most difficult problem they face.
   The foreign minister, who used to be the Communist Party chief in
Georgia, said, ``It's as if much appears quiet on the outside, but
on the inside everything is boiling, and the situation continues to
be explosive.''
