<FIRST>r w AM-Hungary-Trade     09-07 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Trade,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes to Reward Hungary's Economic Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, eager to reward Hungary for its
steps toward economic openness and human rights, voted Thursday to
grant the Warsaw Pact nation a three-year extension of preferential
trade status.
   The 221-169 vote, over the objection of President Bush, sent the
matter to the Senate.
   The bill would grant an extension through July 4, 1992, of the
most-favored-nation trading status Hungary currently enjoys on a
year-to-year basis. Sponsors of the bill said it was time to reward
Hungary's moves toward a more Western-style market economy and
relatively open emigration policies.
   ``For 25 years they have fought the communists, and they have
turned that country around, and we have not done a damn thing to
help them,'' said Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., chairman of the Ways and
Means trade subcommittee.
   The original measure would have provided a five-year extension,
but that was scaled back in a compromise with opponents, primarily
conservative Republicans, who argued the gesture infringes on Bush's
right to conduct foreign policy and diminishes pressure on Hungary
to keep the reforms going.
   ``Let us remember that Hungary remains a member in good standing
of the Warsaw Pact,'' said Rep. Gerry Solomon, R-N.Y., speaking
against the provision.
   ``This bill is an embarrassment to the people of Hungary who have
been fighting for their freedom. They want the pressure kept on
their government to allow them to live where they want to live, work
where they want to work, move where they want to move,'' he said.
   ``This is a fairly delicate time,'' said Rep. Richard T. Schulze,
R-Pa., who helped work out the three-year compromise. ``I don't
think we should let the emotional euphoria (over Hungarian reform)
carry us into a policy we might regret.''
   The five-year version of the bill had been rejected by the House
in June when it failed to muster the two-thirds majority needed
under the expedited floor procedure used to bring it before the
chamber.
   At the time, opponents argued that Bush was about to travel to
Eastern Europe, including Budapest, and planned to annouce his own
rewards for Hungary. During his trip, Bush declared ``the Iron
Curtain has begun to part'' and promised new trade benefits and a
$25 million grant to spur free enterprise.
   Bush said he would be inclined to grant permanent
most-favored-nation status, which offers the best tariff rates
available, if Hungary adopts a liberalized emigration law now under
consideration.
   Current law bars most-favored-nation status to communist
countries with restrictive emigration policies. Since the ban was
imposed in 1974, three nations have been granted waivers: Hungary,
Romania and China.
   ``The president of the United States went over there and put his
Good Housekeeping seal of approval on it,'' argued Rep. Larry Smith,
D-Fla., speaking for the bill. ``This is a country that has proven
over and over again that it wants to be free, open and democratic.''
</TEXT>
