<FIRST>u a PM-EthiopianTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0532 09-07 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopian Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Peace Talks Open at Carter Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with talks under way, comments
from participants. PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `An estimated ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the government of Ethiopia and
an Eritrean rebel group began preliminary talks at the Carter
Presidential Center today in an effort to end the war that has raged
between the two since 1961.
   Former President Jimmy Carter, acting as an observer at the
closed-door talks, said the two sides agreed that no statements on
the progress of the negotiations will be made until the open-ended
sessions are complete.
   Delegations from the government and the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front appeared with Carter at a news conference after
arriving at the center.
   Alamin Mohamed Saiyed, head of the EPLF negotiating team, said
through an interpreter that his people want a ``just and peaceful
solution'' to the war.
   ``We realize that the path to peace is tortuous and requires
patience and time. The Eritrean case cannot be resolved either by
evading it or by cover-ups,'' he said. ``It cannot also be solved by
running away from the truth or by playing some tricks.''
   Ashegre Yigletu, head of the government delegation, said, ``We
would like to affirm that the delegation ... is prepared to conduct
these talks tirelessly and with the utmost patience, and in a new
spirit of broad-mindedness.''
   Carter said he did not know how long the talks would last. He
said the first order of business was an agenda.
   The former president stressed that the talks here are preliminary
and that it would take further negotiations, with the top leaders of
Ethiopia and the EPLF participating, to produce concrete results.
   ``Both sides have limits with how far they want to go in
Atlanta,'' he said.
   An estimated 1 million people have died in the 28 years that the
Eritrean People's Liberation Front has been fighting for
independence.
   Eritrea, a former Italian colony, is a province of Ethiopia and
contains the troubled East African nation's only direct access to
the Red Sea.
   The Carter Center, which houses the presidential library, a
museum, a think tank and foundations working for peace and public
health, is trying to fill a gap by acting as go-between in the
dispute. U.N. intervention is limited to disputes between nations.
   ``These are very intransigent, difficult, dividing issues that
have never been addressed in a substantive way before,'' Carter said
recently. ``Of course my hope is, my expectation is, that we'll go
from there to fairly sustained talks that might bring about a
cease-fire.''
   During his presidency, Carter served as a go-between in the Camp
David talks that led to an accord between Israel and Egypt.
   The Atlanta Constitution reported today that Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak has been asked by both sides to serve as mediator if
the Atlanta talks lead to further negotiations. Mubarak succeeded
Anwar Sadat, who took part in the Camp David accords.
   Exactly when such long-term talks on Ethiopia would be held and
who would oversee them are matters the delegations hope to decide in
Atlanta, Carter has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
