<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American actor Mickey Rourke is only in films
to make money _ at least that's what he told an Italian interviewer.
   ``Until four years ago I still was an idealist, certain that to
be a good actor one must know acting ... now I know it's not that
way,'' he told Milan's Corriere della Sera newspaper.
   ``To be a star you must butter up the right people. They will get
this from me any time they pay me enough,'' he was quoted Thursday
as saying.
   Rourke, at the showing of his ``Johnny Handsome'' at the Venice
Film Festival, said he came ``just for business, for commercial
reasons.''
   The actor, whose relations with the media are often tense, had a
brief and stormy news conference Wednesday. Some Italian
commentators called him capricious and nasty.
   Rourke starred in `` 9{ Weeks,'' ``Barfly,'' and ``The Pope of
Greenwich Village.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Miss America will be selected
next week without a vote from actor-muscleman Arnold Schwarzenegger.
   Schwarzenegger withdrew from the judging because his wife, TV
reporter Maria Shriver, plans to report on the contest for NBC,
pageant director Leonard Horn said Thursday.
   ``She assured me that her post was unbudgeable and she felt there
was a conflict of interest,'' Horn said.
   Horn said he learned of the problem only last week, though Ms.
Shriver knew several months ago she was doing a piece on the Sept.
16 pageant for NBC's new show ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow.'' The
pageant will be on NBC.
   ``We saw no conflict, but she does,'' he said.
   Ms. Shriver's spokesman at NBC, Paul Reader, said she was
traveling and unavailable for comment.
   The judges who will choose Miss America from 10 finalists include
developer Donald Trump, entertainer Merv Griffin, former baseball
player Mike Schmidt, psychologist Joyce Brothers, actresses Phylicia
Rashad and Debbie Allen, and entertainment writer Claudia Cohen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles prodded American businesses in
Britain on Thursday to contribute more to a trust that helps young
people set up their own businesses.
   ``I need your help,'' Charles, the heir to the British throne,
told a luncheon meeting of the American Chamber of Commerce.
   The Prince's Youth Business Trust was launched on his 40th
birthday last November. With a goal of $60 million, donations have
reached $42 million, with U.S. contributions accounting for $1.5
million.
   The trust provides seed money and professional advice to help
young people, particularly from Britain's economically depressed
inner cities, set up their own businesses.
   ``What I am trying to do is invest in this nation's future and as
you, on the whole, have operations in this country, you do to a
certain extent have a stake in that as well,'' Charles said.
  
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel Wheels hit the Steel City, but it was the
fans who stole the show as the Rolling Stones rolled through a
2{-hour show that crossed several generations of rock 'n' roll
lovers.
   ``Hey, Pittsburgh, it's been a long time,'' guitarist Keith
Richards said Wednesday night as 63,000 jammed Three Rivers Stadium
for the hard rockers' first Pittsburgh concert since 1972.
   Mick Jagger praised the crowd for its dancing-in-the-aisles
enthusiasm and often stopped singing to let the fans take over.
   ``You're a rowdy, rowdy, rowdy, rowdy crowd, Pittsburgh,'' Jagger
said after a full-tilt version of the 1978 hit ``Miss You.''
   Teens danced to the band's latest single, ``Mixed Emotions,''
then watched bemusedly as their parents swayed to songs they didn't
recognize, such as ``Play With Fire'' and ``Little Red Rooster.''
   But all sang along to ``Honky Tonk Woman,'' ``Brown Sugar'' and
``You Can't Always Get What You Want,'' whch have become anthems to
fans decades apart in age.
   ``My mother wanted to come as bad as I did,'' said Brian
Growwood, 15, of Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Tom Jones will pay child support for a
14-month-old boy the entertainer fathered during a 1987 visit to New
York, said attorneys who reached a tentative settlement Thursday.
   But the settlement failed to assuage the feelings of the child's
mother, 27-year-old Katherine Berkery, who waged a bitter paternity
fight against Jones. Manhattan Family Court Judge Judith Sheindlin
ruled July 27 that the Welsh singer was the father of Jonathan Jones
Berkery.
   ``I think he's a disgusting human being,'' said Ms. Berkery after
the agreement was reached during a private negotiating session in
Family Court.
   Although no support figure was announced under terms of the
agreement, Ms. Berkery's lawyer, Raoul Felder, was reportedly
seeking $3,800 a month. Ms. Berkery said she was ``very happy with
what I'm going to get.''
   Alton Abramowitz, the attorney for Jones, said the agreement
still needs the singer's approval. Jones did not yet know the
details of the plan, Abramowitz said.
   During the paternity fight, attorneys for Jones argued Ms.
Berkery was a prostitute who lied about her background. Jones, who
has never seen the child, did not attend the hearings.
   Ms. Berkery said Jones fathered the child when they spent two
nights together in October 1987. The boy was born June 27, 1988.
