<HEAD>Armored Car Holdup Leaves One Dead, Two Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with police saying gunmen fled on bicycles,
truck driver not hurt. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two holdup men shot and killed an armored
car guard and seriously wounded two other men today in the Bank of
America headquarters building, police said. Witnesses said the
gunmen fled on 10-speed bicycles.
   ``It looks like a well-planned, well-orchestrated robbery,'' said
Deputy Chief Larry Gurnett.
   It was not immediately known what, if anything, was taken.
   Police said it appeared the two robbers, in ski masks and
baseball caps, followed a pair of Brink's Inc. guards into the
55-story building in the city's financial district and for some
reason opened fire outside the indoor entrance to a Bank of America
branch on the office tower's ground floor.
   A third man, drawn to the scene by the gunfire, was wounded in
the mouth, said police Officer David Ambrose. He said police
received the first call at about 9:55 a.m.
   Ambrose said it also was not immediately clear if the Brink's
truck was there to pick up or drop off cash. The truck's driver
remained with the vehicle as required by Brink's policy and was not
injured, authorities said.
   Witnesses told police the holdup men fled on bicycles.
   ``We're trying to seal off as much as we can here and have an
opportunity to arrest these people,'' Ambrose said.
   A spokeswoman at San Francisco General Hospital said the dead
guard had gunshot wounds in the face and the back of the head. The
other guard was shot above the left eyebrow but was conscious, the
spokeswoman said.
   The third victim was listed in stable condition.
