<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1522EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush Bjt   09-07 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Defense Bill `Totally Unacceptable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush denounced a House-passed defense
bill as ``totally unacceptable to the commander in chief'' on
Thursday and accused the chamber of holding the defense budget
hostage to $20 billion in ``unneeded programs.''
   Bush, in a speech to the American Legion that mixed defense and
anti-drug themes, also praised Wednesday's decision by Colombian
president Virgilio Barco to extradite a major drug figure to the
United States.
   The extradition of Eduardo Martinez Romero to face U.S. drug
money-laundering charges ``sends a strong signal of the courage and
determination of President Barco and the Colombian government to
deal with the scourge which drugs are inflicting on all of us,''
Bush said.
   Declaring ``Remember Pearl Harbor,'' Bush also poked fun at his
1988 campaign gaffe _ to the same group one year ago _ confusing
Pearl Harbor Day.
   ``Today, surprisingly, is Sept. 7. Can you believe it? And I'm
determined not to repeat the mistake I made exactly one year ago
when I referred to this as Pearl Harbor Day.''
   A year ago, Bush, a World War II combat veteran, told the
American Legion convention in Louisville, Ky.: ``I wonder how many
Americans remember that today is Pearl Harbor Day.'' The Japanese
air attack on the U.S. naval base in Hawaii occurred Dec. 7, 1941.
   The president, moving from drugs to defense, said Americans
deserve protection from both ``the fear of war abroad (and) the fear
of drugs and crime at home.''
   But he claimed that the national defense was threatened by the
House version of a defense spending bill for the fiscal year that
begins Oct. 1. A House-Senate conference committee begins work on a
compromise version Friday.
   While suggesting he could live with the Senate-passed bill, which
preserves most of the administration's programs, Bush declared:
``The House version is totally unacceptable to the commander in
chief of the United States armed forces.''
   Congressional negotiators must reconcile rival versions of the
legislation to authorize $295 billion in Pentagon spending and $10
billion for defense programs in the Energy Department.
   The House refused to fully fund either of the two types of mobile
intercontinental ballistic missiles Bush wants. It chopped in half,
to $502 million from $1.1 billion, Bush's request for the rail-based
multiple-warhead MX; and it deleted all funds for the single-warhead
Midgetman.
   The House bill ``contains unneeded programs costing nearly $20
billion from 1990 to 1994, holding our defense budget hostage to
projects that will strip money from programs crucial to strategic
modernization,'' Bush said.
   ``Fellow veterans, real peace is not an accident, so let us
modernize our strategic forces and thus encourage arms control,''
Bush said.
   The president, a longtime American Legion member, wore a cap from
his home post _ Post 77 in Houston _ at the beginning and end of his
appearance, although removing it for the speech.
   On drugs, Bush said his $7.9 billion anti-drug package, unveiled
in a speech to the nation Tuesday, ``will require the bravery and
sacrifice that Americans have shown before and must again.''
   ``As veterans, you know how battles are often fought, house by
house, block by block. Well, we'll win this battle the same way.
We're going to win win it kid by kid, neighborhood by
neighborhood,'' he said.
   To critics of the plan, Bush said: ``Some, incredibly, say it's
not enough. This from the very people who oppose the death penalty.
It's that kind of thinking that's lost too many battles.
   ``So let's not let these critics lose the war,'' he added. ``I
ask you to support our crime plan and also the other parts of our
drug strategy.''
   Afterwards, Bush attended a ceremony at nearby Fort McHenry
marking the 175th anniversary of the War of 1812 battle against the
British that inspired Francis Scott Key to write ``The Star-Spangled
Banner.''
   Standing before a 90-foot white flagpole, Bush called the fort
``one of America's most hallowed shrines'' and said its small force
of soliders had ``stopped a British invasion and preserved our
independence.''
   While Bush used his appearance before the American Legion to
promote his drug plan and criticize the House's defense bill, one
Republican lawmaker suggested using money for the Pentagon's B-2
stealth bomber to fund the anti-drug effort.
   Rep. John G. Rowland of Connecticut said he will introduce
legislation next week to cancel all procurement money authorized by
the House for the stealth bomber in fiscal 1990 and transfer the
funds to Bush's anti-drug program.
   The House, in approving its version of the defense bill last
month, authorized procurement of two stealth bombers, which at a
cost of $530 million apiece are considered the most expensive planes
in history.
</TEXT>
