<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PoisonMushrooms     09-07 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poison Mushrooms,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Ill, One Critically After Eating Poisonous Wild Mushrooms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man remained in critical condition
Thursday after he and three other people ate what experts described
as the deadliest species of wild mushroom.
   ``It's the worst outbreak of amanita mushroom poisoning in at
least 20 years,'' said Dr. Samuel Hall, medical director of the
Minnesota Poison Control Center.
   The victims ate the amanita phalloides in two incidents Friday,
one near Siren, Wis., and the other by Gull Lake north of Brainerd.
All were taken to St. Paul-Ramsey Medical Center.
   An unidentified 52-year-old man from Isanti was in critical
condition. He had picked mushrooms Friday evening near Siren and
cooked them into a creamed soup-like mixture that he shared with a
friend, Sandy Barton, 32, of Blaine. The man ate about two bowls of
the mushroom mixture; Barton ate just a little, and she was released
from the hospital Tuesday.
   Hall said the man had liver failure.
   Daniel Padrnos, 59, and his wife Yvonne, 52, who own the Gull
Lake Four Seasons Resort just north of Brainerd, were the other
victims. Padrnos was discharged from the hospital Wednesday; his
wife remained in the hospital and was improving steadily.
   The cases prompted health and plant experts to issue warnings
about eating mushrooms picked in the wild. Mushrooms have flourished
in the recent cool, wet weather and will be plentiful through early
October, said Neil Anderson, a plant pathologist at the University
of Minnesota.
   Only those who have been trained should pick mushrooms, Anderson
and Hall said. Amanita phalloides and its relatives resemble the
edible field mushroom.
   Padrnos said he had some doubts about the safety of the mushrooms
as he sliced them into a frying pan. ``They didn't seem just
right,'' he said. ``So I fried them for a long time, 15 minutes.
Dumb me, I didn't throw them out.''
   Padrnos said he and his wife scooped the fried mushrooms onto
pork chops and ate them.
   The last recorded amanita death in Minnesota occurred in 1960,
but there have been several non-fatal cases since then, Anderson
said.
   Amanita phalloides contain amatoxin, a deadly poison that keeps
recycling through the body, damaging the liver and sometimes the
kidneys. Hall said there is no antidote for the toxin.
</TEXT>
