<FIRST>r i AM-IraqiBlast     09-07 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraqi Blast,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Says Explosion Killed 19, Not Hundreds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iraqi Embassy said Thursday that 19 people died
in an explosion at a fuel depot outside Baghdad, contradicting
reports by British media and Kurdish dissidents that at least 700
people died and that the site was a top-secret missile plant.
   The embassy said 19 firefighters and civil defense workers
fighting a fire at a depot containing ``highly flammable gasoline
materials'' were killed when a passing truck packed with explosives
detonated.
   In a statement, the embassy said all the casualties were Iraqi
nationals, and that a small number of workers suffered minor cuts
when the explosion shattered the windows of passing buses. The fire
was put out in a few hours, it said.
   The embassy said the truck was en route to a dam under
construction in northern Iraq and its explosives were ``for use in
engineering projects.''
   An official of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, an outlawed
Kurdish movement fighting the Baghdad government, quoted sources in
Iraq on Wednesday as saying 700 bodies had been recovered. The
official spoke on condition of anonymity.
   London's Independent newspaper, quoting unidentified diplomats
and Middle East sources, also reported at least 700 people were
killed, including Egyptian engineers helping the Iraqis develop a
new ballistic missile.
   The embassy denied that a modified version of Argentina's
medium-range Condor-2 surface-to-surface missile known as the
Badr-2000 was being developed ``between Iraq and any other country
including Argentina,'' as news reports had said.
   ``Iraq has already proved being self-sufficient in its
technological capabilities, and it has produced middle-range
missiles by developing a technology that is not yet available to
Argentina itself,'' the statement said.
   The embassy gave no further details about the facility between
Al-Hillah and Ad-Diwaniyeh, about 40 miles south of Baghdad, which
dissidents described as a top-secret missile plant. An embassy
employee who answered telephone calls said the embassy was closed
and no officials were available for comment.
</TEXT>
