<FIRST>r w AM-SovietJews     09-07 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Jews,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Says Quarter-Million Soviets May Seek Entry In 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department estimated Thursday that up
to 250,000 Soviet citizens will apply for admission to the United
States in 1990.
   ``We are seeking ways to fairly and equitably respond to the
expansion in demand,'' spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said.
   About half the applicants are Jews. Armenians comprise another
large category, as do Pentecostal Christians.
   The spokeswoman denied published reports that because of the
heavy flow some Soviet Jews would be declared ineligible. This would
have the effect of diverting many of them to Israel.
   The United States was instrumental in persuading the Soviet Union
to lower is immigration barriers. The rising exodus is a mark of
success, Ms. Tutwiler said, and ``we welcome it.''
   Most Jews who leave the Soviet Union have permits to go to
Israel. But the vast majority opt for the United States once they
reach Vienna.
   A U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
U.S. Embassy in Moscow was receiving 10,000 applications a month
from Soviet Jews for admission into the United States. Another
10,000 a month were applying through the Dutch Embassy for
emigration to Israel, he said.
   ``The rate is going straight up,'' he said.
   The Bush administration is pondering how to handle the situation,
with a decision expected within a week or two.
   ``The administration is definitely not proposing to bar Soviet
Jews from emigrating to the United States,'' Ms. Tutwiler said. ``We
are not propsoing rules to make any Soviet Jews ineligible.''
   Known to be under consideration is the addition of dozens of U.S.
workers to the U.S. Embassy in Moscow to handle the applications.
   The State Department also is considering a six-month waiiting
period for Soviet Jews who do not have close relatives in the United
States.
   ``We are seeking ways to fairly and equitably respond to the
explosion in demand because of our successful efforts in pressing
the Soviets to open emigration,`` Ms. Tutwiler said.
   She estimated that applications will be received from up to
100,000 Soviet nationals in the fiscal year that ends Sept. 30.
   ``In fiscal year 1990,'' she said, ``we expect that the number of
Soviet applicants could increase to around a quarter of a million.''
</TEXT>
