<DOCNO> AP890907-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1932EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineSupply     09-07 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Supply,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Shipments Dry Up in Wake of Colombia Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Martinez, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flood of drugs into the United States has dried
up since Colombia's latest round of violence began, raising the
price of cocaine and shrinking the size of crack rocks, authorities
said Thursday.
   But they warn the sudden drop in trafficking may be temporary,
and could simply be the work of middlemen trying to drive up the
price.
   The Miami-based Seventh Coast Guard District, which has accounted
for 97 percent of the more than 10,000 pounds of cocaine intercepted
by the entire service this year, has seen import activity suddenly
grind to a halt, said Lt. Cmdr Jeff Karonis.
   ``We're still carrying out the same operations as we were, but
the boats aren't coming out, and the air drops aren't happening _
the targets just aren't there.''
   Pat O'Brien, outgoing head of the U.S. Customs Service in Miami,
said agents from his district, by far the busiest in the nation, had
been tracking three to five air drops a week prior to the Colombian
crackdown.
   ``That has now come to a standstill,'' he said. ``There was only
one right after the violence started, and we weren't even able to
confirm that.''
   The only recent major cocaine haul _ 800 pounds on a freighter in
Tampa on Saturday _ had been loaded and shipped before the violence
began.
   Undercover agents trying to make cocaine buys have been put off
for two to three weeks, and even though that period is about up,
there are still no shipments ready, he said. The summer months have
traditionally been the traffickers' busiest.
   In addition, money-laundering activity tracked by Customs is
sputtering _ traffickers are still moving wire transfers for old
cocaine shipments, but there are few new payments.
   The Drug Enforcement Administration has also spotted the change,
but agents there aren't sure if it marks a true disruption.
   ``Yes, there appears to be a slowdown of drug activity out of
South America, a fluctuation in distribution, and a rise in the
wholesale price of cocaine,'' said Miami DEA spokesman John
Fernandes. ``But we don't know if that's because of what's happening
in Colombia, or if entrepreneurs are trying to take advantage of
what's happening to raise the price.''
   Fernandes said the price of large cocaine shipments in the last
two weeks has increased from $11,000-$15,000 a kilogram to
$18,000-$19,000, with individual kilogram sales reaching as high as
$23,000.
   The scarcity is being felt on the street as well, says Metro-Dade
police Cmdr. Steve Rothlein, head of the county narcotics bureau.
Street prices for a kilogram of cocaine have shot up about $7,000,
he said.
   ``Crack, on the other hand continues to sell for $10 dollar a
rock _ but some of the rocks are getting smaller,'' said Rothlein.
   O'Brien attributes the disruption in part to the confiscation of
planes used to carry cocaine from processing plants in southern
Colombia to coastal staging areas.
   The heads of the cartels are also having difficulties trying to
control their operations while on the run, he said. But how long the
situation lasts depends on whether the Colombian government can keep
up the pressure.
   Fernandes warns that the cocaine business is cyclical, just like
any other commodity operation.
   ``There have been slowdowns before,'' he said. ``Slowdowns at
different intervals ... are normal for the narcotics-trafficking
business.''
   He said other traffickers wait in the wings to replace anyone
arrested or extradited, and planes and boats can be bought again
quickly when the pressure is off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2038EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NewspaperFuture     09-07 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspaper Future,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Star Co. Studies Whether to Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kansas City Star Co. said it has
begun a study to determine whether the morning and evening
newspapers should be merged.
   Publisher James H. Hale said in a letter to employees Thursday
that no decision has been reached and no deadline set for deciding
whether to merge the The Kansas City Star with The Kansas City
Times. The study began several weeks ago.
   ``For years there have been consistent rumors that publication of
the afternoon paper would cease,'' the notice said. ``These rumors
have been unsettling to our employees, readers and advertisers. The
time has come to provide a definitive answer.''
   The Star publishes weekday afternoons and Sunday morning. The
Times publishes Monday through Saturday morning.
   The Star reported Thursday that some employees speculated after
the letter was posted that the study would concern itself with ways
to accomplish a merger rather than to determine the viability of The
Star. Hale said that speculation was false.
   Hale, who became publisher in 1977 shortly after the company was
acquired by Capital Cities Communications Inc., said one of the
first questions he was asked was how long Capital Cities would
continue to publish the afternoon newspaper. He said Thursday that
he did not have the answer then and does not have the answer now.
The study will determine that, he said.
   ``I always said I didn't want to be here when that happened,''
Hale said. ``Nobody wants to preside over the death of a great
newspaper, especially me.''
   According to the 1989 edition of the Editor &amp; Publisher Yearbook,
the Times has a daily circulation of 281,886. The Star's circulation
was listed at 184,882 daily and 408,916 on Sundays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
