<FIRST>r w AM-AbortionRights     09-07 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Rights,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion-Rights Backers Announce Rallies Around Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abortion-rights coalition of women's groups
and religious, labor, business and advocacy organizations on
Thursday announced plans for rallies in the nation's capital and in
cities across the country this fall to kick off a nationwide
political organizing effort.
   Under the banner ``Mobilize for Women's Lives,'' the groups said
they will use the Nov. 12 rallies and other events in the states to
register supporters to vote, to enlist their help in political
organizing and to boost the campaigns of abortion-rights candidates.
   ``We will make it the political issue of 1989, 1990, 1992, and we
will change the legislative halls of this country so that we have
pro-choice legislators everywhere in the majority,'' said Molly
Yard, president of the National Organization for Women.
   Organizers said the coalition was formed before the Supreme
Court's July 3 decision giving states broad powers to regulate
abortions. NOW had wanted to stage a Washington rally this fall to
protest the court ruling, but other groups wanted more state and
community involvement in the demonstration.
   Abortion-rights groups brought hundreds of thousands of people to
the nation's capital in April for one of the largest marches in
recent years in the capital and the largest abortion-rights
demonstration ever. Police estimated the crowd at 300,000;
organizers said their numbers reached 600,000.
   Coalition leaders declined to estimate how many people they
believe will participate in the Nov. 12 events, but Yard said she
expected it would be in the millions.
   Organizers said the Washington rally is intended to demonstrate
the unity and strength of the movement, while the events in the
states will be designed to recruit volunteers for political
campaigning and abortion-rights education efforts.
   ``This will mark the 51-week countdown to the 1990 elections,''
said Kate Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion
Rights Action League.
   The groups will be signing up volunteers to ring doorbells, raise
money, write letters and get out the vote at election time in their
state and community, organizers said.
   Among the groups in the coalition are the American Civil
Liberties Union, American Jewish Congress, Americans for Religious
Liberty, Catholics for a Free Choice, Coalition of Labor Union
Women, National Black Women's Health Project, National Federation of
Business and Professional Women's Clubs, People for the American
Way, Planned Parenthood Federation of America, Physicians for
Reproductive Health, Women's Legal Defense Fund and YWCA of the USA.
</TEXT>
