<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1610EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SpySwap 1stLd-Writethru a0633 09-07 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spy Swap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine-Nation Spy Swap Being Negotiated, Newspaper Claims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to add denials from Israel, Norway and lawyer. CORRECTS
spelling of Natan Sharansky. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national newspaper said Thursday that
a nine-nation spy swap is being negotiated by the East German lawyer
who arranged the 1986 release of Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky.
   The Bonn-based daily Die Welt gave no source for its information
but said lawyer Wolfgang Vogel was on a secret mission to Israel
over the weekend to work out the deal.
   Die Welt said the mass release of convicted spies would likely
free two agents from Israel convicted of spying for the KGB, as well
as prisoners in the Soviet Union, the United States, East Germany,
Britain, South Africa, Norway, Iraq and West Germany.
   West German government sources refused comment on the newspaper
report, which said the spy swap was planned some time in the fall.
In Washington, the State Department also refused comment.
   Israel and Norway denied the report.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said: ``From time to time
there are articles like this. It is certain that we are interested
in exchanges of prisoners and hostages, but we have no information
on what was printed. No one has spoken to us on this and Israel was
not involved in this story.''
   Arne Strand, a spokesman for Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem
Brundtland, said ``The government is completely unaware of any such
spy swap.'' Die Welt said Vogel refused to discuss the reported deal
when asked by the newspaper for details.
   The 63-year-old East Berlin lawyer has arranged other spy swaps
in the past, including the 1986 exchange that allowed Sharansky to
emigrate to Israel.
   The newspaper said Shabtai Kalmanovich, sentenced to nine years
in an Israeli prison for his conviction of spying for the Soviet
KGB, was one of the prisoners being considered for release. It also
named a Professor Glinberg, without giving his first name, who Die
Welt said was an expert on chemical warfare. The man referred to is
believed to be Marcus Klingberg, sentenced in 1983 to 18 years
imprisonment in Israel for spying for the Soviets.
   Die Welt said the Soviets were also seeking the release of Dieter
and Ruth Gerhardt from South Africa. Dieter Gerhardt, a former
admiral, is serving a life sentence while his Swiss-born wife is
serving a 10-year term. They were arrested in 1981, the paper said.
   Norway is involved through the case of former government official
Arne Treholt, who was convicted of spying for the Soviet Union and
Iraq and sentenced to 20 years in jail, the newspaper said. He was
arrested in 1984.
   But Treholt's lawyer, Arne Haugestad, ridiculed the report.
``This is nothing but a cock-and-bull story,'' NTB state news agency
quoted Haugestad as saying.
   East Germany's secret service was hoping to win the release of
Reinhard and Sonja Schulze, a couple arrested in Britain, according
to Die Welt.
   The East Germans also reportedly wanted the release of an agent
captured in West Germany and were in return ready to release a
number of Western agents caught in East Germany, Die Welt said.
   Die Welt did not specify any agents convicted in the United
States or U.S. agents serving sentences abroad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
