<FIRST>r w AM-SenateSigner     09-07 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate Signer,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Allows Sign Language Interpreter on Floor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Disabilities Act</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sign-language interpreter was allowed to work
on the Senate floor for the first time Thursday, translating the
debate on proposed legislation to protect the disabled.
   Jean Lindquist, an employee of Gallaudet University for the deaf,
sat at the side of the presiding officer's podium while senators
debated amendments to the Americans With Disabilities Act.
   Ms. Lindquist was later relieved by Mary Owens, of the Senate
Special Services section of the Sergeant-at-Arms office. Other
interpreters were to take turns as well.
   Their interpretation could be seen from the gallery and on the
C-Span television service, which broadcasts Senate proceedings.
   The legislation would guarantee a full range of employment and
equal access rights to the nation's 43 million disabled. The bill
contains a provision guaranteeing special telephone service for the
hearing and speech impaired.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, obtained
unanimous consent from fellow senators to allow the interpreters on
the floor.
