<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2040EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     09-07 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraqis Ready To Swap POWs Unconditionally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Iraqi official said Thursday his
country is ready for a comprehensive, unconditional exchange of
prisoners-of-war with Iran.
   A former Iranian official still close to the government declared
there has never been a better time for reaching a full peace
settlement with Iraq.
   Speaking at the summit of the non-aligned movement in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, Iraqi Deputy Premier Taha Yassin Ramadan said his
country was prepared for a full exchange of all POWs with Iran,
regardless of the lack of progress on other issues in the peace
talks.
   His remarks were carried by the Iraqi News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia.
   Talks on implementing U.N. Resolution 598, which halted the war
Aug. 20, 1988, began five days after the cease-fire. But the talks
stalled almost immediately and have been deadlocked since. The last
round of talks, held in Geneva in April, broke down in an
acrimonious stalemate.
   The deadlocked peace talks have left an estimated 100,000 men
held by both sides languishing in POW camps.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted
Mohammad Javad Larijani, a former deputy foreign minister close to
newly elected President Hashemi Rafsanjani, as writing that ``There
has never been such a good chance of attaining peace as there is
now. One should appreciate such chances.''
   Larijani, whose remarks quoted by IRNA were carried in the daily
Ettelaat, said that was partly because the Iraqis were desperate to
rebuild their war-shattered economy.
   No new peace talks between Iran and Iraq are scheduled.
   The Iraqis insist on direct talks with the Iranians without U.N.
mediation, but Iran has refused.
   After the last round of talks broke down, the Iraqis proposed
exchanging POWs. The Iranians refused, insisting that the full U.N.
peace resolution must be implemented step by step.
   The resolution calls for withdrawal of troops to internationally
recognized boundaries, the exchange of POWs, and dredging of the
Shatt-Al-Arab waterway, which is shared by both sides according to a
1975 agreement but which is cluttered with war debris.
   The talks have been stalled over Iran's insistence that Iraqi
troops withdraw from some 385 square miles of its territory before
the talks can continue.
   But the Iraqis reject the 1975 Algiers Treaty which drew the
border in the middle of the Shatt-Al-Arab. They insist that the
border must be redrawn along the Iranian bank of the Shatt to
include all of the waterway in Iraqi territory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
