<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Dubcek     09-07 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Dubcek,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubcek for First Time Said to Sign Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, Czechoslovakia's leader
when the nation embraced its ill-fated reforms of 1968, has for the
first time signed a document criticizing the government, a human
rights organization said Thursday.
   Dubcek and 32 other Slovaks signed an appeal to President Gustav
Husak, the man who succeeded Dubcek as leader of the Communist Party
in 1969, to drop charges against two Slovak dissidents arrested Aug.
14, the Vienna-based International Helsinki Federation said.
   The two men, Jan Carnogursky and Miroslav Kusy, originally were
charged with incitement, but the charge was later changed to the
more serious offense of activity against the state, which carries a
penalty of three to 10 years in prison, the Helsinki Federation said
in a statement.
   Carnogursky and Kusy were among four people who signed an appeal
to Slovaks to lay flowers at public monuments on Aug. 21 in memory
of those killed when Soviet-led Warsaw Pact tanks invaded in 1968 to
crush the reforms led by Dubcek.
   No date was given of the signing of the appeal by the former
Communist Party leader, who has lived in Bratislava since he was
expelled from the party in June 1970.
