<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Jordan     09-07 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Jordan,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attackers Fire Rockets Into Israel From Jordan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers fired several rockets Thursday from
Jordan into Israel, and a news report said a PLO faction claimed
responsibility. The government demanded that Jordan do a better job
of policing its border.
   There were no casualties in the attacks, but Israelis living
along the border expressed concern that the generally quiet boundary
might be changing into a line of confrontation.
   Jordanian officials said at least one rocket fell on their side
of the border and that they were checking the source of the firing.
   Israel radio reported that a Syrian-backed Marxist faction of the
PLO, the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, claimed
responsibility for the attack in a statement released to Radio Monte
Carlo.
   ``We still do not think that Jordan's policy of ensuring the
security and quiet of the border between us has changed,'' Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir said on Israeli television's Arabic language
service. ``But all the incidents that have occured lately require
caution and alertness.''
   When asked what Jordan should do following the raid, Shamir said:
``First of all, they must prevent this. This is their
responsibility.''
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens echoed Shamir's comments in an
interview on Israel television.
   ``It is certain that the Jordanian government is responsible for
every terrorist act whose source is Jordanian territory,'' Arens
said. ``We are asking the government of Jordan to take action ... to
prevent such acts in the future.''
   Shamir said the attack could be the result of recent Jordanian
moves at a rapprochement with the PLO.
   ``It could be that as a result of some improvement in ties
between the government of Jordan and the PLO, the PLO men were given
more freedom to act in Jordan and this (attack) could be the
result,'' Shamir said.
   The rocket attack was the second incident in a week and the fifth
this year across a normally quiet border.
   The other attack was Saturday when an infiltrator shot and killed
one Israeli soldier and fatally wounded another.
   Israeli newspapers have reported that the army asked farmers who
live along the border to carry weapons when they go to their fields.
   Menachem Regev, secretary of a collective farm near where the
rockets fell, said on army radio there was concern about the growing
number of incidents, which were the most frequent since a four year
war of attrition that started in 1969.
   ``It's like we're returning to the situation of 20 years ago,''
Regev said.
   Jordan does not permit cross border attacks and expelled
Palestinian guerrillas in a 1970-71 civil war, sharply reducing such
attempts.
   But some radical Syrian-based Palestinian groups have
occassionally tried to use Jordan as a launching pad for raids.
</TEXT>
