<DOCNO> AP890907-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     09-07 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Romania,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trip by Romanian Official Canceled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday that a
visit by Romania's defense minister has been canceled, an apparent
result of the deteriorating relations between the Warsaw Pact allies.
   ``Ilie Ceausescu, Romanian deputy minister of national defense,
is not to visit Hungary, in spite of preliminary plans,'' the
official MTI news agency quoted Hungarian Defense Minister Col. Gen.
Ferenc Karpati as saying.
   Ceausescu is the brother of Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu.
   MTI did not say which nation canceled the visit. A date for it
was never announced. Hungarian officials had been criticized for
weeks over the planned visit.
   Reporting on the cancellation, the government daily Magyar Hirlap
said Karpati told reporters that ``Hungarian youth is opposed to the
visit of the Romanian general.''
   The Warsaw Pact countries are seriously split over the plight of
1.7 million ethnic Hungarians in Romania.
   Romania claims no wrongdoing, but Hungary says Romanian citizens
face discrimination and has given 18,000 of them asylum during the
past two years. The actions flout an agreement obliging Hungary to
return Romanian citizens fleeing over the countries' border.
   The two nations also have disputed control of Transylvania, which
is under control of Romania.
   The bitterness between the Soviet bloc countries also stems from
changing politics.
   Under Ceausescu's undisputed one-man leadership, Romania's
Communist Party prohibits dissent. Hungary, meanwhile, has moved
toward reform and next year plans to hold the nation's first free
elections since the Communists consolidated power more than 40 years
ago.
   Ilie Ceausescu's planned visit first was announced in the July 14
issue of Nephadsereg, Hungary's military weekly.
   Hungary's fledgling political opposition parties and some senior
Communist officials immediatey criticized the plan.
   Central Committee member Matyas Szueros, the speaker of
Parliament, said he found it ``incomprehensible.'' He accused the
Romanian leadership of an ``official political campaign'' to
persecute the Hungarian minority and said bilateral relationships
had ``hit bottom.''
   He also called Ceausescu's leadership an example of ``degenerate
socialism,'' and called for Transylvanian autonomy.
   Tensions even have caused senior Hungarian officials to express
concern about Romania's defense policies.
   Foreign Minister Gyula Horn told reporters in July it would be
``irresponsible'' to ignore signals from Romania, referring to
claims by Bucharest that it was capable of manufacturing nuclear
weapons and was thinking of acquiring mid-range missiles.
</TEXT>
