<FIRST>r w AM-StudentLoans     09-07 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Student Loans,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Allows Federal Agencies to Repay Some Student Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the hope of luring talented young
professionals into public service, a House panel approved a bill
Thursday to allow federal agencies to repay outstanding student
loans of some employees.
   On a voice vote, a subcommittee sent to the full Post Office and
Civil Service Committee the legislation, which authorizes a federal
agency to repay up to $6,000 of an employee's federal student loan
debt in any calender year. The measure also would give agencies the
flexibility to pay or reimburse employees for degree training in
certain occupations.
   The Subcommittee on Civil Service also passed on a voice vote a
bill to prevent the Department of Housing and Urban Development and
other agencies from stacking performance review boards with
political appointees. It merely clarifies sections of the Civil
Service Reform Act by requiring agencies to have a majority of
career appointees on review boards when making performance award
recommendations.
   The subcommittee chairman, Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., said
HUD's present policy ``not only circumvents the spirit of the Civil
Service Reform Act, but also undermines the very goal of a
performance award system.
   ``Instead of instituting a system which motivates and awards
individuals for successful performance, HUD's policy threatens to
politicize and void the award process,'' he said.
   The full committee chairman, Rep. William D. Ford, D-Mich.,
introduced the student loan bill.
   Subcommittee members passed the measure with little fanfare or
discussion because Sikorski offered an amendment that addressed most
of the problems raised by the administration during a July hearing.
   Under the amended bill, an agency may repay a total of $40,000 of
an employee's student loan indebtedness. Employees cannot be
reimbursed for any loan payments made before the job began and must
agree in writing, before receiving the benefit, to remain at the
agency for a specified period, not less than three years.
   In selecting workers for the program, an agency is required in
the bill to follow ``merit principles taking into consideration the
need to maintain a balanced workforce representative of the racial,
female-to-male ratio and ethnic makeup of our society.''
</TEXT>
