<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1701EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AcidRain     09-07 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Acid Rain,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine States Want All to Share Cleanup Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers representing nine states demanded
Thursday that the entire country share the cost of cleaning up their
states' acid rain emissions, but colleagues said states that foul
the air should foot the bill.
   ``The country owes some help to those asked to do more,'' said
Rep. Philip Sharp, D-Ind., who is chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce energy and power subcommittee and represents one of the
coal-producing states that contribute to acid rain.
   ``We are talking about economic justice for the country,'' Sharp
said at a hearing of the subcommittee.
   The regional conflict, which has been festering for years,
erupted anew with added urgency because President Bush and lawmakers
from both parties are pushing for a new clean air bill. The question
of who pays to clean up acid rain that is fouling lakes and killing
trees would have to be resolved before such a bill is passed.
   Lawmakers from the nine states say their electric utilities
produce 50 percent of the nation's acid rain pollution, but would
have to finance some 67 percent of the cleanup under Bush's plan and
other bills. The extra cost would likely be passed on to consumer
and business electric bills in those states.
   That idea is vigorously opposed by miners who produce high-sulfur
coal that is burned exensively in the nine states: Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Indiana, West Virginia, Illinois, Kentucky, Missouri,
Tennessee and Georgia.
   United Mine Workers of America President Richard L. Trumka told
the hearing up to 30,000 miners could be thrown out of work by the
year 2000 unless other regions share the costs. Utilities would
simply adopt the cheapest solution, he said, and switch to other
fuels rather than installing expensive pollution-reducing equipment.
   Sharp said it ``galls us'' that the nine states would pay ``more
than our fair share.''
   But Rep. Carlos J. Moorhead, R-Calif., said other states have
already paid to clean up their air. ``The other 41 states have
cleaned up their act'' and customers are financing anti-pollution
efforts with higher utility bills. ``The nine states have the
cheapest rates,'' he said.
   ``California has had to do away with all our coal-fired plants''
and adopted technology that includes expensive solar energy and wind
machines, he said, asking why the 41 states ``should pay for states
that have not cleaned up their act.''
   Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., argued that states such as
Florida ``went to the expense, they went to the trouble. Now you're
saying we should bear part of the cost.''
   The Bush plan calls for reducing sulfur dioxide emissions by five
million tons by 1995 and by 10 million tons by 2000.
   The cleanup burden in the first phase would fall entirely on 107
utilities burning high-sulfur coal in 20 states. But after 1995,
utilities that exceed their cleanup requirements could trade credits
with other utilities and with other industries.
   Sulfur dioxide, and nitrogen oxide _ which has its own reduction
schedule _ are the main components that form an acid in the
atmosphere and destroy trees and lakes thousands of miles from the
emissions. Refineries and smelting plants emit these pollutants
also, although certain coal-burning utilities are the main culprits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
