<FIRST>r a AM-Medfly     09-07 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medfly,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medfly Quarantine in Effect, Spraying Begins Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture officials plan to begin
an air attack on the Mediterranean fruit fly Friday night, seven
years after similar sprayings in the area wiped out an invasion of
the voracious insects.
   Only 16 medflies have been found so far, but those were enough
for federal and state officials Thursday to seek a quarantine of
fruit from a 60-square-mile area in Santa Clara County, southeast of
San Francisco. The quarantine from San Jose to Palo Alto is
voluntary until the filing becomes official next week.
   Gov. George Deukmejian declared a state of emergency Wednesday,
letting authorities spray the pesticide malathion without issuing an
environmental impact report that could take months to prepare.
   At 9 p.m. Friday, if the weather is good, two helicopters are
scheduled to begin five hours of aerial spraying in a $2 million
battle against a bug that is capable of causing up to $50 million
damage locally to tomatoes, apples, pears, grapes and other produce.
   Millions of sterile medflies will be released in 10 days in a
further attempt to stop the spread of the pests.
   In 1980-82, the state sprayed 1,400 square miles in eight
counties to wipe out a medfly infestation. That war cost $100
million to fight and cost California growers another $100 million in
lost sales.
   Medflies started showing up in traps Monday, and state officials
Wednesday completed a ground spraying of malathion on a
200-square-yard area around a peach tree where the larvae were
breeding.
   Agriculture officials, who are checking 1,700 traps in an
81-square-mile area, warned residents to cover their cars and remain
indoors during the aerial spraying on trees and lawns.
   The quarantine, the officials said, is necessary to prevent
widespread infestation.
   ``It has to be emphasized that the reason the quarantine kept
expanding last time is people kept ignoring our warnings about
moving fruit out of that zone,'' said Greg Van Wassenhove, the
county agricultural commissioner.
   Statewide agriculture is a $16 billion per year industry. Last
year, Santa Clara County's agricultural production was worth $142.5
million, with $94.3 million of the total in fruits, nuts, vegetables
and nursery crops that are among the 250 crops that the medfly
devours.
   Gera Curry, spokeswoman for the state Department of Food and
Agriculture, said harvesters, truckers, processors and sales people
also would be hurt by a medfly infestation because every $1 in
agricultural sales produces $3 in the general economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
