<FIRST>r w AM-HealthInsurance     09-07 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Insurance,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says Most Favor National Health Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans think employers should provide
health insurance for their workers, and more than half favor
national health insurance, according to a survey released Thursday.
   But the survey conducted for the Employee Benefit Research
Institute also suggests that Americans undervalue their insurance
benefits, the institute said.
   The survey found that 80 percent of those polled believe
employers should be required to provide health insurance to their
full-time workers.
   Fifty-four percent said the federal government should insure all
Americans, according to the survey.
   However, few would be willing to bear the full cost of benefits.
   About half of those without health insurance said they would be
willing to pay less than $600 annually for coverage, while those
favoring national health insurance said they would be willing to
pay, on average, $664 per year, for that coverage.
   The average cost of individual coverage is $1,056 and for a
family, $2,700, according to the institute.
   ``Everybody is desperately searching for a silver spoon,'' said
Dallas Salisbury, president of the private, nonprofit, nonpartisan
public policy research organization.
   Salisbury said the survey results show that most Americans don't
know what health insurance costs, and that most workers who are
insured through their employer do not consider these benefits to be
part of their compensation.
   Seven out of eight of those surveyed opposed taxing health
insurance benefits received from employers. But of the bulk who
favored requiring employers to provide health insurance, 73 percent
said they would still back that requirement even if benefits were
taxed.
   The survey also asked whether respondents would rather have cash
that would be taxed or the equivalent amount in health insurance
benefits that would be taxed. When the amount was $1,000, 53 percent
opted for health insurance benefits and 40 percent for cash. When
the amount was $2,000, 49 percent took health insurance and 44
percent went for cash.
   Of the 1,000 adults surveyed by telephone during the last week in
June, nine out of 10 said they had health insurance. Of the 10
percent who did not, more than one-third said it was because they
couldn't afford it, 14 percent said they were between jobs and 10
percent said they saw no need for it.
   The survey was conducted by the Gallup Organization Inc. The
margin of error was plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
