<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Ethiopia     09-07 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Ethiopia,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remaining Cuban Soldiers to Return from Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban soldiers will begin returning Saturday
from Ethiopia under an agreement between the two countries, the
Cuban government news agency Prensa Latina said Thursday.
   A communique from the Revolutionary Armed Forces Ministry said
the decision to withdraw the troops was taken after ``the conditions
of aggression and threats from abroad that made necessary our
presence in that heroic land ... changed.''
   Cuban military advisers and other specialists were sent to
Marxist Ethiopia in April 1977 and later were joined by combat units
who helped defeat Somali rebels and troops in 1978. Those troops _
which at one point reached 20,000 _ were withdrawn and a small
contingent was left behind as protection, according to the
communique in the Communist Party newspaper Granma.
   The dispatch did not say how many Cuban troops remain in Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
