<FIRST>r a AM-TuckerResigns     09-07 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tucker Resigns,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. Senate President Resigns, Pleads Guilty, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate President Larry Tucker resigned
Thursday after his guilty plea to a felony charge was disclosed in
federal court, becoming West Virginia's latest state official to
leave in disgrace this summer.
   Earlier Thursday, a defense lawyer told U.S. District Judge John
T. Copenhaver Jr. that Tucker has agreed to plead guilty to
extortion on a charge that he accepted $10,000 from racetrack
officials seeking favorable legislation.
   ``I just made a stupid mistake,'' he told WSAZ-TV in Charleston.
   The announcement came just before opening arguments in the U.S.
District Court trial of Tucker's predecessor as senate president,
Marshall County Democrat Dan Tonkovich. Tonkovich is charged with
three counts of extortion, two counts of attempted extortion and one
count of racketeering.
   Tucker, also a Democrat, is listed as a defense witness for
Tonkovich, who is accused of soliciting money from groups that had
legislation pending before the Senate.
   Tonkovich's lawyer, James Lees, told Copenhaver he was unaware of
Tucker signing an agreement to plead guilty when he placed the
Senate president on his list of defense witnesses.
   Among other West Virginia Democratic officials who have resigned
or pleaded guilty this summer are Attorney General Charlie Brown,
who resigned as part of an agreement in which a grand jury
investigation of him was halted; state Treasurer A. James Manchin,
who resigned to halt his removal trial in the state Senate on 17
impeachment counts; and state Sen. Si Boettner, who pleaded guilty
to a felony income tax charge and resigned.
   Tonkovich's former top aide, Bob Cain, recently pleaded guilty to
a federal tax charge.
   Federal prosecutors had previously filed documents alleging that
Tonkovich supported legislation in 1987 favorable to Tri-State
Greyhound Park in Cross Lanes in exchange for $10,000 from track
co-owner Bill Ellis. At the time, Tucker was Senate Judiciary
chairman and Tonkovich was Senate president.
   Ellis could not be reached for comment Thursday, but he
previously denied any wrongdoing.
   Tucker, 54, told WSAZ he accepted $10,000 from race track
lobbyist Sam D'Annunzio, then unsuccessfully tried to return it to
him. He said D'Annunzio refused to accept the money.
   D'Annunzio eventually cooperated with federal prosecutors in
their investigation of the Legislature, and he committed suicide in
December 1988.
   Senate Clerk Darrell Holmes said Tucker submitted a one-sentence
letter of resignation Thursday afternoon.
   Tucker, a two-term senator, was elected president in 1989 after
Tonkovich gave up his Senate seat for an unsuccessful campaign for
the Democratic nomination for governor.
   Under legislative rules, Senate President Pro-Tem Tony Whitlow
will serve as acting president until a replacement is elected by the
full Senate, Holmes said.
   The state constitution requires the governor to call a special
session of the Senate within 10 days so a new president can be
elected, Holmes said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
