<FIRST>u w AM-US-Hungary-Poland     09-07 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Hungary-Poland,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Asks Congress for First Installment in Aid to Hungary and Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush asked Congress on Thursday for
the downpayment on a $150 million aid package for Poland and
Hungary, and the White House said it might increase the amount if
more economic and political reforms are adopted by those countries.
   For the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, Bush requested $33.5
million.
   ``We'll always be looking for opportunties to increase that aid
but we believe certain economic reforms and political reforms are
necessary as a link with any real increases in aid, so we have some
assurances that it is, indeed, revitalizing the Polish economy,''
said White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   He said Bush wrote to congressional leaders and asked for rapid
approval of his request.
   In addition to the economic aid, the administration is preparing
a $58 million package of food aid for Poland that is expected to be
ready around Oct. 1. Fitzwater said, ``We want to get all the food
aid in there we can.''
   Bush announced the $150 million package during his July trip to
Poland and Hungary. Some members of Congress have urged the
administration to expand the package to reward the installation of
Solidarity member Tadeusz Mazowiecki as prime minister of Poland.
   The president discussed the package, along with other subjects,
with Republican members of Congress during a meeting at the White
House.
   Senate Minority Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., who earlier had
recommended a higher figure, said, ``I think he's doing what he
should do in providing the leadership, working with the Western
alliance.''
   Dole said ``the bottom line is ... it's primarily the
responsibility of Poland.''
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., said he recommended to Bush that
he name a task force of American businessmen, labor leaders and
others to work with Poland's government to identify the reforms it
should adopt ``to get from a communist economic base to a more
productive base.''
   Fitzwater said the idea is being considered.
   In July, Bush said he would provide Poland with $100 million to
spur private enterprise and $15 million for environmental projects.
Hungary is to receive $25 million for entrepreneurial projects and
$5 million for environmental projects. Bush also requested $5
million to promote organized labor.
