<FIRST>r w AM-CommonCause-FEC     09-07 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Common Cause-FEC,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Accuses Election Watchdog of Willful Inaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Common Cause accused the Federal Election
Commission Thursday of falling down on its job of policing federal
campaign finance laws, claiming the FEC's ``seemingly willful
refusal to act'' has encouraged illegal practices.
   The self-styled citizens lobby said the problems are so pervasive
``the best, albeit drastic, remedy may be to abolish the FEC
altogether and to create a new election law enforcement agency.''
   ``The FEC in recent years increasingly has abdicated its most
basic responsibility _ to enforce the law,'' Common Cause said in a
report.
   Fred Eiland, a spokesman for the election commission, said he
wasn't certain whether the agency would issue a response. Common
Cause is an enduring critic of the FEC and has sued the agency
frequently.
   The failure to enforce the federal campaign finance laws
``springs both from the structural defects Congress created in the
agency and from the recalcitrance of the commissioners themselves,''
the study said. ``Congress virtually has ignored the FEC's failure
to enforce the law.''
   Under laws passed after the Watergate scandals in the early
1970s, the FEC is charged with administering public funding of
presidential campaigns, policing public disclosure, interpreting
laws pertaining to presidential and congressional elections,
investigating alleged violations and undertaking enforcement actions.
   Common Cause spotlighted so-called ``soft money'' practices in
which contributions from corporations, labor unions and invididuals
are channeled to state and political party organizations.
   The study said that in 1988 the presidential campaigns of George
Bush and Michael Dukakis ``together raised up to $50 million in soft
money contributions from corporations, labor unions and individuals
in donations as large as $100,000, money that is strictly prohibited
in federal elections campaigns.''
   ``Although this occurred in full public view, the FEC took no
action to stop it, in spite of a federal court decision ordering the
agency to issue new soft money rules.''
   The study said, ``by its inaction, the FEC virtually issued an
invitation to presidential campaigns to continue violating the law,
an invitation which both presidential campaigns seized upon.''
   Common Cause said such inaction discourages voluntary compliance
with the law, encourages non-compliance ``to the point where the
integrity of the presidential campaign finance system, in particular
is now at risk.''
   The advocacy group praised the FEC for performing well in the
areas of public disclosure of campaign records and administering the
distributions of public funds.
</TEXT>
