<FIRST>u w AM-StarWars-Quayle     09-07 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Star Wars-Quayle,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Quayle In Step On SDI: Fitzwater</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Thursday there was no difference of opinion between President Bush
and Vice President Dan Quayle on the Strategic Defense Initiative.
   The spokesman also said that former President Reagan had not
exaggerated the potential ability of SDI to defend against incoming
nuclear missiles.
   The Los Angeles Times published an interview with Quayle on
Thursday in which the vice president suggested that Reagan had
resorted to ``political jargon'' in his original, 1983 sales pitch
for a multi-billion-dollar research effort aimed at creating a
space-based defense shield.
   Quayle said Reagan, in launching his SDI initiative, ``talked
about this impenetrable shield that was going to be completely leak
proof.''
   ``I believe that in the semantics of let's say political jargon,
that that was acceptable. But it clearly was stretching the
capability of a strategic defense system,'' said the vice president.
   Fitzwater said Quayle's comments reflected ``the fact that we
have been able to winnow the objectives of the program to ... fit
more definable kinds of objectives.''
   He said there was ``no difference'' between Bush and Quayle on
SDI.
   Quayle was ``just saying there was some strange language
associated with some of the discussion of it,'' said Fitzwater.
``But he believes in it.''
   Referring to Quayle's ``political jargon'' phrase, Fitzwater
added, ``The only thing we have different today is two inflammatory
words.''
   Fitzwater said Bush still has not given up the goal of perfecting
a space shield against all incoming nuclear missiles.
   ``That's kind of the goal that you keep working for,'' said
Fitzwater.
   The ``ultimate goal,'' he added, remains ``a space shield that
protects against the intercontinental ballistic missiles.''
   Quayle, an early, ardent advocate of SDI, said in the interview
that the on-going research effort on SDI has been ``clearly
rethought,'' with emphasis on an approach called ``Brilliant
Pebbles'' that would rely on clusters of mini-missiles to track and
knock out incoming rockets.
   ``We have redefined Star Wars and put it into missions,
requirements, doctrine and strategy much differently than we did in
the early 1980s,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle said the new emphasis could help protect the United States
against an accidental launch or a limited nuclear attack ``rather
than an all-out, bolt-out-of-the-blue attack'' by the Soviets.
   The administration's request for $4.9 billion for SDI research
for fiscal 1990 is under attack on Capitol Hill, where the House
wants to cut $1.8 billion from the program.
</TEXT>
