<SECOND>AM-Israel-Arabs,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arabs Claim Graveyard Bulldozed to Improve View for Villas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERZLIYA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Arabs demanded an investigation
Thursday of claims that a century-old Moslem graveyard was bulldozed
so adjacent villas would have a better view of the Mediterranean.
   ``The municipality does nothing when a graveyard is criminally
desecrated and the bones of the dead are crushed by bulldozers of
people who have no morals,'' said a statement released by Moslem
leaders who gathered at the site near Herzliya, a coastal town eight
miles north of Tel Aviv.
   Moslem clerics and three Arab members of the Israeli parliament
said the city sent the machines to change a pipe in the graveyard,
then the workers hauled away hundreds of cubic yards of earth to
give the villas a better view, the newspaper Yediot Ahronot reported.
   Israel radio quoted Mayor Eli Landau as saying the bulldozers did
not enter the graveyard, but that the city would investigate. It
quoted him as saying the incident was an ``attempt to create
friction between Arabs and Jews.''
   Yediot Ahronot quoted Parliament member Rafi Edri, who owns a
house in the area, as saying no graves were violated.
   ``If there was any desecration of a graveyard, I'd be the first
to scream,'' the independent paper quoted him as saying. It said the
Labor Party legislator joined neighbors in helping pay for the
earthmoving work.
