<FIRST>u w AM-US-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0717 09-07 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evacuated Envoy Hopes to Return to Beirut Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Subs 12th graf, ``I view, to CORRECT Aoun's first name to Michel,
sted Miichel.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador to Lebanon, John McCarthy,
said Thursday he hopes to be able to return to Beirut ``as soon as
the situation is calm again.''
   McCarthy and 29 members of the U.S. Embassy staff were evacuated
from Beirut Wednesday after a Christian commander in the embattled
city had voiced threatening remarks.
   McCarthy spoke briefly with reporters when he arrived at Dulles
International Airport on a flight from Frankfurt, West Germany.
   ``Any embassy has to rely on the host government authorities to
provide protection,'' he said. ``When we felt that that wasn't being
provided any more, we had to leave.''
   Asked whether the United States was washing its hands of Beirut,
McCarthy replied:
   ``Never. We're very interested in what's happening in Lebanon. We
have a strong attachment to the Lebanese people.''
   The ambassador was asked whether the evacuation of him and the
embassy staff would have any impact on efforts to free Western
hostages believed held in Beirut.
   McCarthy said that while the U.S. Embassy was located in
Christian East Beirut, the hostages are believed to be held captive
in Moslem West Beirut. Movements of Americans assigned to the
embassy had been restricted to East Beirut.
   For that reason, he said, ``our absence from Beirut will
unfortunately not really impact significantly on what we know about
the hostages.''
   The envoy was met at the airport was met by his wife, Marija, and
their 11-year-old daughter, Julia.
   Earlier Thursday, the State Department renewed its allegation
that a Christian commander in Lebanon had threatened to take 20
Americans hostage.
   ``I view it as a threat,'' spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said
of General Michel Aoun's remark to the French newspaper Figaro that
taking hostages was evidently the way to get U.S. attention.
   Aoun had complained in the interview that the United States was
not paying enough attention to the war in his country between
Christians and Moslems backed by Syria.
   In reply, Ms. Tutwiler said the Bush administration had taken an
active role in seeking a settlement.
   She said President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III
had called for a cease-fire and U.S. ambassadors and government
officials in the Middle East were working toward that end.
   ``I think we have been engaged,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
</TEXT>
