<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-WVaElection 1stLd-Writethru a0591 09-07 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WVa Election, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0591,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Changes Election Could Be Referendum on Governor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Leading the ..., to restore dropped first reference
to Agriculture Commissioner Cleve Benedict.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents vote Saturday on three
proposed changes to state government in a special election that
could serve as a referendum on Gov. Gaston Capterton's first eight
months in office.
   Caperton, a Democrat, could win broad, new powers if two of the
measures pass.
   One amendment eliminates three statewide elected offices _
secretary of state, treasurer and agriculture commissioner _ and
places their duties under the governor's control. The second gives
the governor control of the state primary and secondary education
system, taking it away from the largely independent state Board of
Education. The third gives cities and counties the ability to merge
or choose new forms of government.
   Leading the campaign against the first amendment are two of the
officeholders _ Secretary of State Ken Hechler, a Democrat, and
Agriculture Commissioner Cleve Benedict, a Republican.
   ``This is a much larger issue than party loyalty,'' Benedict
said. ``This is a very fundamental choice on who we, Ken Hechler and
I, trust to exercise power _ whether we trust citizens at the ballot
box, or whether we trust the political elite.''
   Hechler and Benedict, both former congressmen, say they aren't
campaigning just to save their jobs; the amendment wouldn't take
effect until their terms end in 1992.
   ``I'm just a temporary occupant,'' said Hechler. ``It belongs to
the people, and future generations ought to continue to have the
right to choose whoever they want.''
   The third official, Treasurer Thomas Loehr, supports Caperton's
plan. Caperton appointed Loehr to the post in July after two-term
Treasurer A. James Manchin resigned rather than face trial in the
state Senate over the loss of $279 million from an investment fund
his office supervised.
   Caperton contends he can save $3 million a year by assigning the
officeholders' duties to other officials.
   ``This is not a turf war,'' Caperton said in his weekly radio
address last weekend. ``It's an economic battle.''
   He said critics who accuse him of a power grab are distorting the
issue.
   Saturday's election comes at a time of widespread trouble in West
Virginia politics. In addition to Manchin's resignation, Attorney
General Charlie Brown resigned Aug. 21 to halt a grand jury
investigation of his campaign financial records and allegations that
he lied under oath.
   Former state Senate President Dan Tonkovich went on trial
Thursday on federal extortion and racketeering charges. Three
others, include the former Senate majority leader, pleaded guilty to
lesser charges in exchange for their testimony for the government.
   Supporters and opponents say the special election for 868,802
registered voters could turn into a referendum on Caperton's first
eight months in office.
   Caperton, a millionaire businessman, won a landslide victory last
November over Republican incumbent Arch Moore. One of his first acts
was to push through the largest tax increase in state history, $392
million, despite a campaign promise not to raise taxes.
   ``There's a lot of anger out there about the tax increase, a lot
of anger about politics of the past, about broken promises,''
Benedict said. ``Those are all probably going to be factors in the
outcome.''
   Former Gov. Cecil Underwood, who is supporting the amendments,
agreed that Caperton's job performance will be a factor.
   ``Constitutional revision should never be a referendum on the
incumbent,'' Underwood said. ``At the same time, it is almost
impossible to keep that element out of the issue.''
   A statewide survey conducted Aug. 19-23 for The Associated Press,
the Charleston Daily Mail and WSAZ-TV showed that two-thirds of the
registered voters surveyed knew little about the amendments, but a
majority said they would vote against the two measures that would
give the governor more power.
   The secretary of state's office maintains records regarding
corporations and supervises state election laws. The Agriculture
Department regulates farming and provides assistance to farmers and
gardeners. The treasurer's office handles state investments and
maintains the state's bank deposits.
   If voters approve the amendment, the remaining elected statewide
jobs will be governor, attorney general and auditor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
