<DOCNO> AP890907-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1857EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Iowa-Vulnerability     09-07 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa-Vulnerability,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Says Suicidal Behavior All But Impossible to Guard Against</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iowa Inquiry Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy admirals said Thursday it would be
virtually impossible to guard against the type of suicidal behavior
they believe caused the explosion that killed 47 sailors aboard that
USS Iowa last April 19.
   A Navy report said ``circumstantial evidence'' indicated Gunner's
Mate Clayton M. Hartwig, who was closest to the breech in the middle
gun of turret No. 2, dropped a detonator between bags of gun powder
being loaded during firing exercises off Puerto Rico.
   ``As with any catastrophe, the immediate impulse is to take every
possible step to prevent a recurrence,'' wrote Adm. Carlisle A.H.
Trost, the chief of Naval Operations and the top officer in the Navy.
   But Trost said, ``it is virtually impossible to have established
procedures to absolutely preclude disastrous results of such an
individual choice.''
   Documents released with the report show Hartwig was depressed
over the collapse of a close friendship, and one letter from Hartwig
11 days before the explosion eulogized sailors who died in action
and said, ``I could become one of those little white headstones in
Arlington National Cemetery.''
   The report said Hartwig ``was emotionally capable of committing
suicide, probably with the intent of killing others also.''
   The report used the words ``repugnant'' and ``incredulous'' to
describe the idea that ``an intentional human act'' sparked the
blast, but concluded that Hartwig was ``the principle suspect.''
   ``We don't know the motivation,'' said Adm. Leon Edney, the vice
chief of naval operations.
   Edney told a Pentagon press conference the Navy did not plan to
change its psychological screening procedures.
   ``We didn't see anything that required a drastic change,'' he
said.
   Hartwig's allegedly suicidal character only became apparent after
interviews with his acquaintances and family over the course of the
four-month investigation, Edney said.
   ``He was a clean-cut sailor. He didn't smoke. He didn't drink. He
didn't carouse on leave. ... He wasn't a troublemaker,'' said Edney.
   The investigation also uncovered lax procedures aboard the Iowa,
the report said, and the Navy announced immediate steps to correct
them.
   The circumstances of the explosion are muddied by ``a number of
major administrative and supervisory discrepancies on board the USS
Iowa, as well as substantial and serious failures by senior USS Iowa
personnel to properly discharge their responsibilities,'' Adm.
Powell F. Carter, commander of the Atlantic Fleet, said in a letter
released with the report.
   But, Carter wrote, ``exhaustive testing and evaluation has
virtually ruled out any of these discrepancies as directly causing
the deaths of the 47 crewmembers in Turret 2.''
   ``Nevertheless, the number and egregriousness o the discrepancies
create an impression of laxity and disregard that will cloud the
investigations in the minds of non-experts for the immediate
future,'' Carter wrote.
   Among the problems cited in the report were a failure to fully
train sailors in the gun turret on firing procedures.
   To prevent a repeat, ``all battleship weapons departments are to
be inspected and deficiencies corrected prior to authorizing full
unrestricted use of 16-inch gun systems,'' the report said.
   Rear Adm. Richard D. Milligan, who led the investigation,
concluded after numerous tests none of the irregularities could have
sparked the blast.
   He began to investigate the possbibility that the explosion was
intentional after receiving a letter from Hartwig's sister, Kathy
Kubicina, saying Hartwig meant to change the beneficary of a
$100,000 accident death insurance policy to his parents from another
sailor aboard the Iowa, Kendall Truitt.
   Truitt was once a close personal friend of Hartwig, but the
friendship had cooled after Truitt became involved with a woman,
Milligan said.
   Although Milligan said he found no evidence that Hartwig was a
homosexual, documents released with the report show investigators
were examining possible ``homosexual activity'' and ``Hartwig's
alleged homosexuality.''
</TEXT>
