<HEAD>Into A Tunnel And Out Of Prison _ For The Fourth Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police once again are hunting for Zbigniew
Najmrodzki who made his fourth prison break through a tunnel dug
under the penitentiary courtyard, PAP news agency said Thursday.
   Najmrodzki, 35, was awaiting trial for assault and burglary in
Gliwice, southern Poland, when he escaped on Saturday, PAP said.
   It said he was taking a routine half-hour walk in the prison
courtyard when he disappeared underground into the camouflaged
entrance to a tunnel running 18 feet under the prison wall to a
nearby school.
   Najmrodzki's accomplices had even installed electric lighting in
the tunnel, the report said, adding that the tunnel led to a
schoolroom and from there he disappeared into heavy street traffic.
   Najmrodzki ``never quite got used to the idea of serving his
prison terms,'' PAP said.
   It said hefirst escaped in 1978 while being transported in a
military convoy; escaped from a court while on trial in 1980, and
knocked down a guard and walked out of a police station dressed in
police uniform in 1985.
   He was caught each time, but the agency gave no details as to how.
