<FIRST>r a AM-JenretteReleased     09-07 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jenrette Released,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Released from Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. John Jenrette was released from
jail Thursday after serving a 30-day sentence for stealing a necktie
and shoes from a suburban Washington discount store, his attorney
said.
   ``He was released in a normal procedure. He will begin performing
community service soon,'' said attorney Stephen Merril.
   Jenrette, 53, was sentenced to the jail time and 200 hours of
community service last month on convictionm of two counts of petty
larceny for shoplifting at a Marshall's discount department store in
nearby Tyson's Corner last Dec. 7.
   The former South Carolina Democratic congressman also was placed
on on two year's probation and ordered to continue psychiatric and
alcoholism treatments.
   At his sentencing, Jenrette said he was sorry, and didn't know
why he stole the items. ``I can only say that I'll never be back.
Why I let this happen, I don't know,'' he said.
   Jenrette also said the conviction dashed his hopes of regaining
his licenswe to practice law.
   Jenrette, a member of Congress from 1975 to 1980, served 13
months in prison after his conviction on bribery and conspiracy
charges in the ABSCAM congressional sting operation of the 1970s. In
that case, FBI agents posing as oil-rich sheiks offered bribes to
members of Congress.
   As Jenrette is still on probation in that case, he will likely
face a hearing before a federal probation board to assess the latest
conviction, Merril said. But no hearing has been scheduled, he added.
</TEXT>
