<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-US     09-07 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southern Command Accuses Panama of Jamming Radio, TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUARRY HEIGHTS, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Southern Command on
Thursday accused Panama's Defense Forces of jamming English-language
radio and television broadcasts aimed at the American military based
in Panama.
   It said in a communique that the jamming ``could potentially
thwart U.S. Forces' Canal defense missions or endanger military and
civilian personnel if it prevented the reception of emergency
Command advisories.''
   Repeated telephone calls to Defense Forces spokesmen for comment
were unavailing.
   Jamming occurs when there are news reports about Panama or
related stories, a Southern Command official said.
   The Command's TV station Southern Command Network carries local,
national and international news and programs for the U.S. forces and
their dependents in Panama. The signal is beamed from a hill in the
former U.S. Canal Zone and can be received up to 50 miles away.
   No opposition news media are allowed in Panama.
   The Southern Command encompasses 10 military installations where
nearly 14,000 soldiers and their dependents are based.
   Under terms of the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties, the bases may
remain until the end of 1999, when Panama takes full responsibility
for operation and defense of the waterway.
   Panamanian-U.S. relations have been tense since two U.S. grand
juries indicted Pnama's leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega on drug
trafficking charges in February 1988.
   The Southern Command also complained of jamming of its TV
programs before and after the May 7 presidential election.
   At the time, the Panamanian government denied it was jamming the
broadcasts.
   International observers said the opposition won the election,
which Noriega had annulled.
   As Defense Forces chief, he is the most powerful man in Panama.
   Hundreds of university students staged a brief anti-government
protest Thursday by forming a human chain on campus, but no
incidents occurred. They were protesting the arrest of three
students during disturbances last month.
</TEXT>
