<FIRST>u i AM-EEC-EastBlocAid     09-07 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-East Bloc Aid,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Nations Will Hold 2nd Meeting on Aid to Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of two dozen Western nations
will hold a conference Sept. 26 on ways to provide badly needed
economic aid to Poland and Hungary, the European Community said
Thursday.
   More than 100 officials met last month at the 12-nation trading
bloc's Brussels headquarters for an initial assessment of the need
and of aid available for the two reform-minded communist nations.
   A spokesman for the European Community, who demanded anonymity,
said the conference would consider aid programs already begun and
that another high-level meeting may be scheduled for later this year.
   President Bush and leaders of other affluent democracies asked
during their annual economic summit in July that the EC coordinate
economic aid for Poland and Hungary.
   Western nations want to encourage the trend toward economic and
political reform in both countries.
   The European Community said it began emergency shipments of beef
to Poland this week and half the total of 10,000 tons was expected
to arrive next week. It is part of a $120 million food aid package
for Poland agreed to in July by agriculture ministers of the 12
Common Market countries.
   Poland is being given the food under an arrangement that allows
the government to sell it to consumers and use the money to improve
private agriculture.
   According to the spokesman, a delegation from the trading bloc
will visit Poland and Hungary soon for further discussions. In
Warsaw, the officials are expected to sign a recently completed
agreement on expanding trade and cooperation between Poland and the
European Community over five years.
   At last month's meeting on Poland and Hungary, the United States
pledged to send Poland $50 million worth of food from surplus stocks.
   In July, President Wojciech Jaruzelski said Poland needed 685,000
tons of beef, pork, powdered milk, butter, oils, wheat, corn, rice
and sugar in the next few months. He said it would need at least 3.7
million tons of food next year and again in 1991.
</TEXT>
