<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0737 09-07 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0737,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate OKs Mass-Mail Money Transfer to Drug-Treatment Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf: ``The Senate,'' to UPDATE with final vote on
overall appropriations bill; ADDS 2 grafs with list of senators voting
against measure and not voting; SUBS 12th graf: ``Bradley and,'' to list
not voting senators on the amendment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, forced to choose between preserving
its members' mass-mailing privileges and approving aid for drug
rehabilitation programs, voted overwhelmingly Thursday to give $45
million to help addicted pregnant women, mothers and infants.
   Faced with a recorded vote on whether to slash money for
unsolicited mailings, the Senate decided 83-8 to approve the
amendment, which was attached to a $2 billion legislative-expense
budget for fiscal 1990.
   It was the first such assistance measure acted upon by either
chamber since President Bush announced his $7.9 billion anti-drug
abuse campaign Tuesday.
   Republicans, led by Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., proposed the
measure Wednesday. It was aimed at transferring to drug treatment
programs a large sum of money from the account legislators use for
their mailings.
   The Senate gave the overall legislative appropriations bill final
passage on an 81-9 vote late Thursday. The measure will have to be
reconciled with a $1.6 billion House-passed version.
   The Senate measure virtually eliminates district-wide mailings
used often by senators and representatives to keep their names
before their constituents, but allows them to continue answering
individual queries.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., told colleagues the bulk of the money
used for mass mailings is spent by senators seeking to bolster their
chances for re-election. He said that was wrong.
   ``We're approaching some $70 million a year on mass mailings to
the public that have not been solicited ... figures show a much
higher percentage of the mass mailings are by those who are up for
re-election,'' he said.
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, led the opposition, saying
mass-mailed newsletters were indispensable tools of communication
with his constituents.
   But Wilson said, ``This is an opportunity for Congress to do
something about something we have talked about,'' he said. ``So,
let's begin to break the habit and let's begin to help those who
need help.''
   Also voting against the amendment were Sens. Bill Bradley,
D-N.J.; Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.; Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii; Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn.; Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii; Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y. and Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   Bradley and Simon are the only two of the eight who are up for
re-election next year. Nine senators did not vote: Brock Adams,
D-Wash., William Armstrong, R-Colo., Max Baucus, D-Mont., Conrad
Burns, R-Mont., James McClure, R-Idaho, Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska,
William Roth, R-Del., Terry Sanford, D-N.C., and James Sasser,
D-Tenn.
   The money would go to a program started in 1988 that provides
treatment to drug-addicted pregnant women, mothers and infants,
focusing on crack. Wilson said 400,000 babies are born annually to
mothers who use drugs.
   Without Wilson's amendment, the legislative spending bill would
have limited congressional spending on mail next year to $80
million: $48 million for the House, which has 435 members, and $32
million for the 100-member Senate.
   The Wilson amendment slashes the total for both chambers from $80
billion to $35 million. The bulk of that money would be used to
cover a shortfall in mailing expenses for the current budget year,
which ends Sept. 30, leaving little mass-mailing money for fiscal
1990, which starts Oct. 1.
   The House-passed bill seeks to allocate $124.7 million for all
congressional mailing privileges in the new budget year.
   The nine senators voting against the overall $2 billion measure
were: William Armstrong, R-Colo.; Kent Conrad, D-S.D.; Alan Dixon,
D-Ill.; Jake Garn, R-Utah; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Connie Mack, R-Fla.;
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.; Steve Symms, R-Idaho; Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.
   Not voting were Brock Adams, D-Wash., Max Baucus, D-Mont., Conrad
Burns, R-Mont., John Glenn, D-Ohio, Trent Lott, R-Miss., Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, William Roth, R-Del.,
Terry Sanford, D-N.C., and James Sasser, D-Tenn.
</TEXT>
