<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-07 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heat Warms South, Rain Heavy in Iowa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Summer warmth and humidity prevailed Thursday across the Gulf
Coast states and from the southern Plains to the Great Lakes, while
heavy rains drenched parts of Iowa.
   Scattered showers and thundstorms hit Florida, southeast Georgia,
parts of Louisiana and coastal Texas, as well as Iowa, eastern South
Dakota and southern Minnesota. There were also a few showers in the
central Appalachians.
   In southwest Iowa, thunderstorms brought 5-6 inches of rain
Thursday morning to parts of southern Adams and northern Taylor
counties. Some small streams overflowed in the area and streets were
flooded in Corning.
   Wind gusts reached 44 mph around Yankton, S.D., as thunderstorms
dumped heavy rain.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included almost 2 inches at Brunswick, Ga., and more than half an
inch in Iowa at Spencer, Des Moines and Sioux City.
   A cold front extended from the upper Mississippi Valley across
the central Plains to the Great Basin area. Cool autumnlike weather
settled into the northern Rockies and northern high Plains under a
high pressure ridge that extended from western Canada to Montana.
   Sunshine prevailed Thursday afternoon from the Rockies to the
West Coast, while partly cloudy skies dominated the East.
   Hurricane Gabrielle continued to move northward, well to the east
of Bermuda. Heavy surf advisories continue from North Carolina to
New York.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Winnemucca, Nev., to 102 degrees at Imperial, Calif. The
low in the nation Thursday morning was 27 degrees at Truckee,
Calif., and Butte, Mont.
   Friday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
Michigan and northern Ohio across the upper half of the Mississippi
Valley to the northern and central Great Plains; showers and
thunderstorms scattered across the southern Plains, the lower
Mississippi Valley and Florida; rainshowers in the northern Rockies,
and western sections of New York and Pennsylvania.
   Predicted high temperatures were in the 60s along portions of the
California coast, and from the northern Rockies across North Dakota
to northwest Minnesota; 50s in some locations in western Montana and
northwest Wyoming; 90s from Florida across the Gulf coastal states,
the lower Tennessee, lower Ohio and middle Mississippi valleys, the
southern Plains and southern New Mexico to interior valleys of
California and southwest Oregon; near 100 degrees in the Big Bend
area of southwest Texas, and between 100 and 110 degrees in the
desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs will be in the 70s and 80s.
</TEXT>
