<FIRST>r a AM-RacialAttack     09-07 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Judge Named to Brooklyn Racial Attack Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sevens whites accused of killing a black
teen-ager in the mostly white Bensonhurst district will be tried
before a black judge whose assignment bypassed the usual selection
process, court officials said Thursday.
   Justice Thaddeus Owens, 70, was selected by a panel of judges and
court administrators last week because of his experience and his
ability to handle cases receiving a lot of publicity, said Matthew
T. Crosson, chief administrator of the state court system.
   Owens' race played no part in the selection, Crosson said.
   Owens was named solely because of his judicial excellence, Court
of Appeals Chief Judge Sol Wachtler, who oversees court
administration, told the New York Post, which first reported the
selection in its Thursday editions.
   The judge had no comment on his appointment or on the case, his
clerk said.
   Lawyers for the young white men charged in the Aug. 23 attack
greeted the announcement with mixed reactions.
   The attorney for the accused shooter said he might file a motion
to block it. David DePetris, who represents 18-year-old Joseph Fama,
said he objected ``not because of the judge that was selected but
because it may violate my client's rights.''
   Fama, who is being held without bail in the Brooklyn House of
Detention, has been charged with murder in the attack and is
suspected of firing the shots that killed 16-year-old Yusuf Hawkins.
   Hawkins and three of his friends had gone to the mostly white
Brooklyn neighborhood to look at a used car when they were set upon
by a gang of some 30 bat-carrying whites, the police said.
   Seven young white men who allegedly took part in the attack have
been arrested and the police say they expect to pick up other
suspects.
   Michael L. Santangelo, the lawyer for 21-year-old Charles
Stressler, labeled the selection ``indiscreet, insensitive and
illegal.''
   However, Albert C. Aronne, lawyer for 19-year-old Joseph Serrano,
praised the selection, as did Mathew J. Mari, the attorney for
18-year-old Steven Curreri.
   ``I've known Thaddeus Owens for a number of years and have tried
a number of cases before him. He is a good man and a good judge,''
Aronne said. ``He's tough and we need someone tough who calls it the
way he sees it.''
   Judges usually are selected at random or specialize in certain
types of cases. But for trials expected to generate high interest or
controversy, court officials frequently handpick whomever they
believe most suited to handle the case, Crosson said.
</TEXT>
