<HEAD>Police Arrest Neighbor After Rape Victim Writes His Name in Blood</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with suspect arrested. Picks up
6th graf pvs, `The woman's ...; INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, `She
then ..., to UPDATE with quote from detective.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-year-old woman who was raped, beaten, stabbed
and left to die in a crawl space of her burning home used her blood
to scrawl the attacker's name on a wall, and police Thursday
arrested her next-door neighbor. The woman, described by police as
``very, very brave,'' also cut her way out of the burning house with
the knife that stabbed her and scaled a six-foot wall to escape,
police said.
   She was in fair condition Thursday after undergoing surgery at
Denver General Hospital to repair sliced tendons in her right wrist.
   ``She's alert and awake ... but still is very frightened because
this person is still at large as far as I know,'' said Lisa Duchon,
a hospital spokeswoman.
   Donnie E. Russell, 18, who has lived next door to the victim for
about two years, was arrested at a truck stop in Oklahoma City at
4:20 p.m. MDT, said Oklahoma City police Sgt. Don Matthews.
   ``We got a teletype from the Oklahoma City police saying that
Donnie Russell had told them he was wanted for rape, arson and
attempted murder in Denver,'' said Denver Detective Christine Wallis.
   Matthews said police in Oklahoma City had gotten an anonymous
phone call that Russell would be coming through the city trying to
contact relatives.
   Wallis said extradition procedures would be started Friday.
   The woman's ordeal began Wednesday morning when she let Russell
into her home to use a telephone, police said.
   She was robbed of jewelry and money and raped in the basement,
Wallis said. She was beaten about the head with a hammer, stabbed in
the arm and hand and left in the crawl space, which had been closed
off with furniture. Her home then was set afire.
   The woman managed to write, ``Donnie, next door,'' in blood on
the wall before she kicked her way out of the crawl space, Wallis
said.
   She then used the foot-long knife that she had been stabbed with
to break the basement window and then scaled a 6-foot fence in her
backyard, screaming for help, police said.
   ``She is a very brave, gutsy woman,'' Wallis said Thursday after
interviewing the victim in her hospital room. ``She at one point
feigned unconsciousness and grabbed the knife from him.''
   The residents in the middle-class northeast Denver neighborhood
didn't know whether she was in trouble or looking for it. ``People
didn't want to get involved,'' Wallis said.
   But one woman, who asked not to be identified, telephoned police
after hearing the victim scream, ``Help me. Somebody help me.''
   ``I looked out the window to make sure it wasn't some kids
playing around. I saw her climbing over the fence with a knife in
her hand. I went and called the police,'' the neighbor said.
   ``She was disheveled, beat up, bloody, half-dressed. She looked
crazy. Now that I've heard what happened, I guess I would be crazy,
too,'' the neighbor said.
   After the incident, Wallis left her business card in Russell's
front door and he called her later in the day. He promised to go to
police headquarters and answer questions, but never arrived, she
said.
   He lives with an uncle, and Wallis said both the uncle and the
victim's husband were shocked to learn that he was a suspect in the
attack.
