<FIRST>r a AM-People-LaToya     09-07 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-La Toya,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pop Singing Star Denies She Married Manager, Blames Possible Imposter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer La Toya Jackson denied Thursday that she
married her manager in a quiet civil ceremony here, saying an
imposter had signed her name to Washoe County court wedding
documents.
   ``It could have been an imposter,'' Ms. Jackson said in a
telephone interview with The Associated Press. ``It's totally untrue
that I got married. I'm not ready for marriage yet. I'm too involved
in my career right now.''
   Washoe County Clerk Judi Bailey on Thursday produced marriage
license No. D044127 purchased Tuesday by La Toya Jackson, 33, and
Jack Gordon, 50, and said the couple went through a legal wedding
ceremony that night.
   ``They had to show their driver's licenses and tell the clerk all
kinds of information in order to prove who they were,'' Ms. Bailey
said. ``They even had to know their mothers' maiden name and where
she was born. And where their father was born.
   ``She got married right here in the Washoe County Commission
chambers. When they say `I do' before a witness and the deputy
marriage commissioner then they're married.''
   Ms. Jackson had been in the gambling city to perform a concert at
Bally's Reno that is scheduled to be televised later on pay
television, and which kicked off her world tour produced by Gordon.
   ``I was surprised when I heard about it,'' Ms. Jackson said. ``I
have no idea why someone would say that.''
   According to Washoe County Court documents, it was the second
marriage for Gordon, a Springfield, Ill., native who was divorced in
1982, and the first marriage for Ms. Jackson, a native of Gary, Ind.
   Ms. Jackson said her relationship with Gordon is ``strictly
professional.''
   ``He's a great man but not a person I'd settle down with,'' she
said.
   Ms. Jackson moved out of her parents' home in May after an
apparent rift developed between her and her family because of her
relationship with Gordon, a former carnival operator and Las Vegas
businessman.
   The rift is only one of several that has reportedly kept Ms.
Jackson at odds with her family in the past year.
   She posed nude in the January issue of Playboy which ran a
12-page spread on the sister of pop recording star Michael Jackson.
   And her family has reportedly been trying to get her to tone down
an alleged ``tell-all'' autobiography scheduled to be published next
year.
</TEXT>
