<FIRST>u a AM-DrugAgentSlain     09-07 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brother-In-Law Of Former Mexican President Indicted On Perjury Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother-in-law of Mexico's former
president was indicted on perjury charges Thursday, nearly a month
after he was taken into custody for questioning as a material
witness in the slaying of a U.S. drug agent.
   Ruben Zuno Arce, 59, was accused in the indictment of lying when
he told a federal grand jury in Los Angeles that he did not know two
alleged Mexican drug figures charged in the killing of DEA agent
Enrique Camarena.
   In his grand jury testimony, he apparently denied knowing Rafael
Caro Quintero and Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo.
   Zuno, a prominent Mexican businessman, was arrested Aug. 9 in San
Antonio by U.S. immigration officials and brought to Los Angeles to
testify as a material witness in the 1985 killing of Camarena.
   But a judge Tuesday found that Zuno was not a material witness
and ordered him released. The order, however, was blocked by U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service officials on grounds that
Zuno is an alleged drug trafficker.
   Zuno, brother of the wife of former Mexican President Luis
Echeverria, was taken back to San Antonio, where he was being held
on an immigration warrant.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Manuel Medrano denied the indictment was
an attempt to keep Zuno in the United States.
   ``The indictment speaks for itself. ... He was indicted because
he lied under oath,'' said Medrano.
   Zuno's attorney, Edward Medvene, could not immediately be reached
for comment in a telephone call made to his office after business
hours.
   In the past, Medvene has contended his client is not a drug
trafficker but a legitimate businessman and that the U.S. government
has illegally detained him.
   Medvene has said Zuno merely had the misfortune of having a house
that was sold to Caro, a reputed drug who allegedly masterminded
Camerena's murder in that house.
   Camarena and his pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar, were killed after
the agent led a series of raids on marijuana plantations allegedly
operated by Caro.
   Camarena's body was found March 5, 1985, on a ranch 65 miles
southeast of Guadalajara. He had been tortured before his death.
   Zuno testified before a grand jury last month, and authorities
had wanted him to testify in the upcoming trial of Juan Jose Bernabe
Ramirez, a former Mexican state police officer charged in Camarena's
killing.
   Three people have been convicted in the case, and six others,
aside from Bernabe, are under indictment.
   Caro is being held in Mexico City, awaiting trial.
</TEXT>
