<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     09-07 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Offer to Suspend Sabotage Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvador's leftist rebels on Thursday
announced a suspension to their economic sabotage campaign, and both
rebels and government said they agreed in principle to meet soon in
Mexico to try to end their civil war.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said it would
suspend all acts of sabotage in El Salvador as of Sunday and asked
the rightist government to respond in kind to create ``a serious
climate'' for peace negotiations.
   The Marxist-led rebel coalition announced no time or date for the
talks and said differences over a mediator still clouded prospects
for a dialogue.
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani called the announcement
encouraging and suggested the first meeting be held in Mexico Sept.
12-13.
   He said that as a gesture of good will, his administration will
let dozens of wounded guerrilla prisoners leave El Salvador for
treatment elsewhere.
   Cristiani spoke to reporters Thursday in San Salvador, his
capital, at a ceremony during which he named four lawyers and a
military officer to represent the government at peace talks.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said the United States is pleased about the prospect of the first
Salvadoran peace talks in two years.
   ``President Cristiani called for dialogue in his inaugural
address, and we believe it is time for the FMLN to realize that
democracy and violence do not mix,'' she said.
   She said the development is a tribute to the resolve Congress has
shown in reaffirming continued U.S. aid to El Salvador and for
observance of human rights standards.
   FMLN leaders told a news conference in Mexico City that rebel
fighters will stop sabotaging telephone and electrical facilities
and stop planting land mines and booby traps at midnight Sunday.
   ``The FMLN will maintain these unilateral measures during a
sufficiently prudent time for the armed forces and the government to
take corresponding steps that will contribute to creating a serious
climate for negotiation,'' said a rebel communique read to the
reporters.
   The leaders would not say what constitutes ``sufficiently
prudent.''
   The communique accused the government and its armed forces of
bombing civilian areas; using mines and booby traps; arresting and
torturing students, workers and other activists, and attacking
journalists.
   It said this must stop and the government must suspend the draft
and must allow the immediate, unrestricted return of all refugees.
   The communique said a positive government response would
``demonstrate a real will for peace.''
   No immediate response came from the government.
   The FMLN has fought a series of U.S.-backed Salvadoran
governments for nearly 10 years. The war has killed about 70,000
people, most of them civilian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
