<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 3rdLd-Writethru a0781 09-07 0951</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0781,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Restaurant Bombed, Rancher Slain, Mayors' Replacement Rescinded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with two bombings in Medellin, government
rescinds plans to replace two mayors, quotes, details. Edits to trim and
conform. No Pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BOG2</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Martinez, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia replaced the mayors of two towns
with army officers in cocaine regions Thursday, but then rescinded
its action after an outcry that the moves were unconstitutional and
antidemocratic.
   The development was the latest wrinkle in this South American
country's fierce anti-narcotics campaign.
   Two bombs exploded Thursday in a pedestrian mall in the drug
center of Medellin, injuring two policemen.
   In Bogota, cattle rancher Jaime Castillo Franco was shot to death
Thursday by two men while driving in the capital. The killers sped
away and it was not known if the shooting was related to the drug
war.
   President Virgilio Barco used emergency anti-drug decrees late
Wednesday to name military officers to replace indefinitely the
elected mayors of Puerto Boyaca and Pacho, two towns believed to be
strongholds of drug kingpins.
   Puerto Boyaca, 95 miles north of Bogota, has been a strongpoint
for right-wing death squads the government says are controlled by
cocaine cartels. The town is in a region believed rife with
cocaine-processing laboratories.
   The government also replaced the mayor of Pacho, 40 northeast of
the capital, saying it too is believed to be a strongpoint for drug
cartels.
   But civil libertarians and politicians vehemently accused the
government of exceeding its constitutional powers. Late Thursday,
Interior Minister Orlando Velasquez canceled the moves because of
``accusations that we are acting anti-democratically.''
   ``I will obey the order, but I don't agree with it,'' Puerto
Boyaca's mayor, Marino Estrada, had told the Radio Caracol. ``They
must have their reasons but I don't know what they are. Everything
has been calm here.''
   The war between drug cartels and government broke out Aug. 18
when assassins believed to be paid by the drug lords killed the
front-running presidential candidate, Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, a
strong foe of drug dealing.
   The private National Radio Network chain and a police spokesman
reported two bombs blew up in a crowded outdoor Medellin mall,
extensively damaging several shops. One bomb was left in a sports
duffle bag under a table in a fast-food restaurant, police said.
   ``By luck, there weren't any more injuries,'' said the police
spokesman, who spoke on condition of not being identified.
   Telephoned warnings of bombs placed in buildings in Barranquilla
forced evacuation Thursday of several government offices and banks,
including the Venezuelan Embassy, Caracol said. No bombs were found.
   In this capital, about 500 students at the National University of
Bogota, shouting ``Gringos, go home!,'' burned a U.S. flag and threw
stones at journalists. University officials evacuated the campus and
suspended classes for the day. They said two students were slightly
hurt.
   The protest came one day after the extradition to Atlanta of
Colombian economist Eduardo Martinez Romero, 37, accused of being
one of the main money launderers for the Medellin cocaine cartel.
   Americans fled Colombia on Thursday fearing a deadly backlash by
the drug lords, who have said they would rather die in Colombia than
live in prison in the United States, and who have threatened to kill
10 judges for every Colombian drug suspect extradited.
   Shortly after Martinez's extradition, two men on a motorcycle
tossed a dynamite bomb at a bank in Medellin, 150 miles northwest of
Bogota, causing $45,000 damage but no injuries, police there told
The Associated Press. Another bomb damaged a Medellin warehouse
Wednesday night, but police said that might have been an act of
personal vengeance, not a drug reprisal.
   Along the 1,000-mile-long Venezuela-Colombia border, 12 U.S.
aircraft with sophisticated reconnaissance gear have begun
overflights of the mountainous Sierra de Perija terrain, observers
in Venezuela reported Thursday. The Indians living in the area said
this week that drug smugglers maintain a vast, 60,000-acre coca
plantation there. Cocaine is made from the coca leaf.
   Colombia's largest newspaper, El Tiempo, reported the crackdown
forced closure of some cocaine laboratories. It predicted a cocaine
shortage within a month in the United States, which gets 80 percent
of the drug from Colombia.
   The Supreme Court began debating whether the draconian state of
siege powers are legal. The opposition Conservative Party called
Barco's decision to impose military rule on violence-plagued towns
unconstitutional.
   Mayor Juan Gomez of Medellin said as long as he is carrying out
his legal duties, ``no one will remove me from this job.''
   Among Americans leaving were 20 families of employees of
U.S.-based Occidental Petroleum Co., which has been developing
Colombia's largest oil field, a source said Thursday on condition of
anonymity. He said they left Wednesday night.
   Three Americans playing on popular semi-pro basketball teams in
Medellin were also reported leaving.
   Ron Davis and Napoleon Petteway, both of New York City, playing
for the Banco Cafetero team, and Kenneth Garrett of Chicago, of the
Sprite squad, ``are returning to the United States right away,''
Jaime Arenas, president of the Colombian Basketball Federation, told
the AP.
   ``Unfortunately, we had to do this because of the violence
affecting Colombia and in particular Medellin.''
   Senior U.S. diplomats and drug enforcement officials in Bogota
have said that once extraditions start, they expect drug-related
terrorism in Colombia to increase.
   For years, drug traffickers have largely evaded justice through
bribery and intimidation, killing or bribing politicians, police,
judges, journalists and others.
   Martinez, who arrived in Atlanta under heavy guard Thursday, has
denied any links to the Medellin cartel. He is accused of laundering
up to $27 million in drug profits by funneling the cash through U.S.
banks, including one in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
