<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1537EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-SununuProfile Adv10   09-07 1176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sununu Profile, Adv10,1211</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 11, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>John Sununu: Outsider Easing into White House Insider's Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Henry Sununu sees his job as White House
chief of staff as something more than Oval Office doorkeeper _ but
something ``not as hectic'' as, say, being chief executive of New
Hamsphire.
   ``There's less pressure to work with each and every department
and agency,'' Sununu says. ``Here a lot is ... rightly or wrongly,
under the control of the bureaucrats.''
   Sununu's approach to the job differs from those of his
predecessors under Ronald Reagan. James A. Baker III, for example,
called it ``a great big catcher's mitt.'' To Donald T. Regan, it was
``a shovel brigade that follows a parade down Main Street.''
   But Sununu, 50, the abrasive three-term New Hampshire governor
who was one of George Bush's earliest campaign workers, may still be
one of the surprise acts of the Bush White House.
   Originally an outsider to Washington politics, Sununu eight
months into the Bush presidency is not only proving himself adept at
survival but has been winning allies in an institution where critics
originally thought he would make only enemies, Congress.
   ``I've tried very hard to make every day a learning day,'' Sununu
said in an interview.
   After an admittedly rocky start that included the failed
nomination of John G. Tower for defense secretary, Sununu says he
has been working hard to keep lines of communication open with
members of Congress and with the bureaucracy, and in keeping his
fabled temper in check.
   And were there mistakes to learn from? ``Lots. And I'm not going
to tell you any of them.''
   Sununu, one of the first aides Bush sees each morning at the
White House and the last one he meets with at the end of each day,
says one of his principal jobs is ``just to make sure that everybody
that the president should see gets a chance to see him.''
   Blunt and quick-witted (he is a member of the high-IQ society,
Mensa), Sununu handles the No. 1 staff job differently than the
three men who held it before him.
   He is less of a behind-the-scenes negotiator and conciliator than
were either James Baker, Reagan's first staff chief and now the
secretary of state, or former Senate Republican leader Howard Baker,
Reagan's third staff chief.
   Where James Baker has been credited with moderating some of
Reagan's more conservative views, Sununu is the in-house
conservative in the Bush White House.
   Sununu has been criticized by some for maintaining too high a
profile compared to the low-key and generally soft-spoken Baker.
   But while he exercises firm control over the staff, Sununu does
not exert the iron discipline that Reagan's middle chief of staff,
Donald T. Regan, did; nor does he attempt to maintain the same
degree of control over the president's personal schedule, according
to White House insiders.
   Some White House staffers have privately criticized Sununu for
appearing at Bush's side so often. Still, Sununu said, ``I can
wander in to any meeting, any time. He (Bush) wants it that way.''
   Stuart Eizenstat, a former senior aide to President Jimmy Carter
and now a Washington lawyer and consultant, says Sununu ``seems to
have subdued his own personal agenda for the president's agenda, and
seems to have achieved a sense of teamwork.''
   Tom Griscom, a former aide in the Reagan White House, which was
rife with staff clashes, said Sununu ``has exceeded expectations.
There are still many tests out there. But, so far, people have to
acknowledge that Gov. Sununu knows his way around more than people
gave him credit for.''
   While Sununu made an early peace with Senate Republican Leader
Bob Dole (something Donald Regan was unable to do) in an effort
salve bitterness remaining from the 1988 presidential primaries, he
hasn't completely retired the hatchet he wielded for Bush during the
presidential campaign.
   A favorite target has been Sen. Joe Biden, D-Del., chairman of
the Senate Judiciary Committee which earlier this month dumped
Bush's nomination of William Lucas to head the Justice Department's
civil rights division.
   ``Sen. Biden is out there, to be blunt about it, trashing the
president,'' Sununu says.
   But the chief of staff also has another role, one not often seen
by the public _ that of White House jester.
   When Bush stepped away from an Oval Office meeting briefly,
Sununu impishly had a White House photographer snap a picture of the
empty presidential chair as he and other top aides looked on
intently.
   Sununu and national security adviser Brent Scowcroft then
presented an autographed enlargement to Bush.
   It was inscribed to ``President Skippy,'' from a staff ``who can
see through you,'' a clear reference to cartoonist G.B. Trudeau's
long-running ``Doonesbury'' depiction of him as an invisible leader
with a fictitious ``evil twin'' brother, Skippy.
   ``It was in the middle of a tough week,'' Sununu said.
   ``People feel comfortable doing something that breaks the tension
a little bit. I think it allows for a decision to be made in a much
more relaxed climate. And you usually end up with better decisions.''
   Then there was the time he talked Budget Director Richard Darman
into donning a gorilla suit to greet the president. Or when the
staff turned the tables and all showed up at a meeting wearing black
arm bands to mark Sununu's 50th birthday.
   The bespectacled, round-faced aide staff chief claims he's gotten
a bad rap in the image department: that the perception of him as
arrogant, imperious and aggressive is all wrong.
   ``What a lot of people miss was that ... I was governor in a
state in which, constitutionally and statutorily, the governor's
office was relatively weak.''
   Running New Hampshire, he said, was in some ways much harder than
running the White House staff. ``The pace down here is not as
hectic,'' he said.
   What Sununu lacked in legal authority in New Hampshire, he made
up for in swagger and bravado. Then he brought the same
aggressiveness to managing Bush's come-from-behind victory in the
1988 New Hampshire primary _ and to his travels around the country
trashing neighboring Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   ``That was before his kinder and gentler days,'' Bush said the
other day in Kennebunkport, Maine, in discussing his chief of staff.
   Bush said Sununu ``has my full, unequivocal confidence. And it
makes life a lot easier for me. ... He's made a lot of friends for
our administration on the basis of competence, sheer competence.''
   Still, while staff morale seems generally high, there have been
some clashes even in this ``kinder and gentler'' White House,
including friction between Sununu and Scowcroft whenever the chief
of staff wanders into the foreign-policy domain, according to White
House sources.
   And while staff members say that Sununu exhibits a sense of
humor, he is not one to cross.
   As Andrew H. Card Jr., a key Sununu deputy and former
Massachusetts legislator, puts it: ``He expects people to have done
their homework.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday AMs Sept. 10</NOTE>
