<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1535EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-DrugsInAmerica Adv10-2Takes   09-07 1159</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drugs In America, Adv10 - 2 Takes,1178</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun AMs Sept. 10 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drugs in America: The Enemy Within</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This time, America cannot simply come home.
   George Bush speaks determinedly of victory, but the fact remains,
a generation after Vietnam, that the United States is losing its
second war.
   Again the carnage, the brutality and the futility radiate nightly
into living rooms across the land.
   The scenes seem so familiar. The dead being carried off in body
bags. Wives and mothers grieving over senseless loss. Bewildered
children, ravaged by violence and disease. Commandos in flak jackets
charging again and again into enemy havens, only to find them
quickly reoccupied.
   This time, the homefolks are not seeing these things just on
television. No matter how sickened, they cannot demand that the
politicians and the generals return their sons and daughters from
some faraway combat zone. Because home is where the war is.
   Guerrillas are roaming the streets, not of Saigon, but of Los
Angeles and Chicago and Washington. Not the jungles of Vietnam, but
the farmlands of Iowa and Minnesota.
   Bush, like every president of the modern era, has promised to win
the drug war. It will happen, he said Tuesday, ``block by block,
child by child.'' He has a new program, latest in a long line. In
eight previous years, Bush, by his own account, was the hands-on
administrator of President Reagan's drug war. Polls show most people
believe that effort failed.
   According to the Drug Enforcement Administration, crack cocaine
has become ``the fast food of drugs'' and has spread from just three
U.S. cities eight years ago to virtually every state, including
rural areas, ``now manifesting itself in all strata of society.''
Not a happy legacy for the crime-fighting Reagan-Bush administration.
   Now, Bush would channel $261 million into Columbia and other
Andean nations to help finance the hunt for drug kingpins and their
henchmen, for whom human life is cheaper than a coca leaf.
Meanwhile, America's drug users are spending an estimated $100
billion each year to keep them in business.
   To this day, some Americans affix exclusive blame to foreign
villains, be they Colombian drug lords, corrupt Third-World generals
or Jamaican immigrants. A recent poll suggests a majority of the
public would favor the use of U.S. troops to wipe out the drug
exporting centers around the globe.
   Others argue that supply only exists to satisfy demand, and speak
boldly of mandatory prison terms or hospital confinement for all
drug abusers, as if there were room for them all.
   There isn't. According to the American Council for Drug
Education, 72 million Americans, or a whopping 37 percent of the
population aged 12 or older, have used illegal drugs at least once
in their lifetime. An estimated 14.5 million people had used them
within a month of the federally sponsored National Household Survey
on Drug Abuse last year.
   An estimated 21 million Americans have tried cocaine, at least 3
million are still occasional users and nearly a million are heavy
users. About 28 million people used one banned drug or another,
counting marijuana, in the last year.
   Drugs favor no race, sex or class. Three-fourths of illicit drug
users are white; 41 percent are women, including 5 million of
child-bearing age. The drug education council says 11 percent of all
babies born over the last year were exposed to illicit drugs during
their mother's pregnancy.
   Drugs are in the schools, the home and in the workplace. Eight
percent of last year's high school seniors said they had used
cocaine over the previous year; 10 percent of college students said
they did so. The drug council says 3 percent of workers between the
ages of 20 and 40 are cocaine users. In a recent survey, the
nation's employers said as many as one in five workers have alcohol
or illegal drug problems. Drug-related absenteeism, medical expenses
and lost productivity are costing employers an estimated 3 percent
of their payroll _ half the typical company's payment for an
employee's Social Security coverage.
   There are some encouraging signs. The national survey on drug
abuse has found a recent decline in so-called ``casual'' drug abuse
by young people. Two years ago, an estimated 17 percent of college
students were occasional users, compared to 10 percent today.
   But the number of heavy abusers _ particularly involving cocaine
_ has risen sharply. The percentage of weekly and daily cocaine
users has doubled since 1986; the number of cocaine-induced deaths
recorded by hospital emergency rooms totaled 1,696 last year, up
from 604 in 1984. Overall, emergency rooms treated 46,020 cocaine
patients last year, compared to 8,831 in 1984, an increase of 421
percent.
   Like the brass-hat body counters in Vietnam, prosecutors and
police often trumpet their battlefield victories to the news media _
seizures of vast quantities of drugs worth fortunes on the street,
massive arrests purporting to destroy this or that trafficking ring.
Like Lyndon Johnson's tunnel light, such announcements bear little
semblance to the real course of the war.
   Fact is, illicit drugs, especially cocaine, are in more plentiful
supply, at cheaper prices, in more potent form, than ever.
   The marijuana smoked today is as much as 10 times more powerful
than the stuff used by the flower child of the 1960s. A California
study shows the purty of cocaine sold on the streets increased from
29 percent to 73 percent in just the two years between 1982 and
1984, and has remained there. The price has dropped to under $100
per gram for the much purer, deadlier drug.
   Urban slums have long been the stomping grounds of drug dealers.
But the arrival of crack, a potent and cheap derivative of cocaine,
has done for those neighborhoods what gunpowder has done for Beirut.
   Cocaine was once considered the rich man's drug. With crack rocks
selling for a mere $5, nearly anyone, children included, can find a
way to obtain it.
   Pharmacologists say the drug itself chemically induces more
paranoia and violence than most any other, though another drug of
choice _ PCP or ``angel dust,'' can be as bad or worse. And
desperation among users, prepared to rob and kill for the money to
buy it, and competition among sellers, eager to establish
trafficking monopolies, heighten the explosive mix.
   The firepower and disregard for innocent life exhibited by the
gangs of young punks marketing crack, from Jamaicans in Washington
to the ``Crips'' and ``Bloods'' in Los Angeles, is astonishing.
``Drive-by'' killings, the spontaneous murder of someone because he
is dressed, sometimes unwittingly, in the colors of a rival gang,
have become commonplace. In Chicago, the cops who raided the arms
cache of one drug gang found the usual assortment of machine guns
and sawed-off shotguns along with, of all things, a cluster bomb.
Cluster bombs, normally dropped from airplanes, are designed to kill
anyone within a wide area.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-DrugsInAmerica Adv10-1stAdd   09-07 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drugs In America, Adv10 - 1st Add,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 10, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: wide area</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Urban Institute recently sent its drug reseachers into
schools located in Washington's poorer neighborhoods, where they
interviewed adolescent boys in the ninth and 10th grades. The
information was later corroborated by criminal activity reports and
school records. Eighty percent denied using or selling drugs. But 28
percent admitted carrying a concealed weapon; 17 percent had
participated in a group attack; 13 percent admitted selling drugs,
making an average $1,000 per week; 11 percent had assaulted an
adult; and 5 percent had shot, stabbed or killed someone.
   And that, from kids only 14 and 15 years old.
   Last month, a Justice Department study in 14 major cities found
that more than half the men arrested for any serious crime _ and who
volunteered for drug testing _ were drug users. In Philadelphia, the
figure was 82 percent. ``There should be no longer any question as
to how much of a catalyst for crime the lust for illegal drugs has
become in America today,'' Attorney General Dick Thornburg said.
``Drug users and traffickers will beat, rob and kill anyone for
drugs and profits.''
   The toll, of course, is not limited to physical violence. The
House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control estimated in
February that there are 6 million to 6.5 million Americans in need
of drug-abuse treatment, including 1.3 million intravenous drug
abusers. Currently, treatment programs are available for only
250,000 abusers, the committee said.
   Meanwhile, quite aside from the thousands of drug-stupified
patients they treat, hospital emergency rooms are soaked with the
blood of drug-related violence. Washington's homicide rate, 59.4 per
100,000 population, edged out Detroit's last year to make the
District of Columbia the nation's murder capital. The majority of
the killings were drug murders, and the rate is climbing again this
year.
   Washington's police arrested 43,000 people last year. The vast
majority were set free, mostly because the city had no place to
imprison them. The same story applies in other cities. In Chicago,
misdemeanor offenders are released on personal recognizance because
there is no room in the Cook County jail. Nationwide, fewer than one
in six people arrested on drug-trafficking charges spend more than a
year in jail.
   Rural America is hardly immune. In a survey of all 93 U.S.
attorneys, the Justice Department found cases involving major drug
trafficking and related contract killings throughout the heartlands.
``We knew that the country was awash in narcotics and dangerous
drugs, but we did not expect to find significant cocaine operations,
for example, in Wyoming, or heroin trafficking in Iowa,'' said
Thornburgh.
   ``Crack,'' he added, ``is everywhere.''
   But cocaine is just the salt in America's drug stew. Colombia's
drug lords are not responsible for the 100,000 elementary school
children who get drunk at least once a week on the beer and
fruit-flavored wine coolers they see consumed by their parents and
television heroes. They are not responsible for the 48,000
youngsters who are killed or injured in automobile accidents caused
by intoxicated drivers every year. They are not responsible for the
five-fold increase in lung cancer since 1963 among women, who now
smoke tobacco in nearly the same numbers as men.
   The American Council for Drug Education says half a billion
workdays are lost each year because of alcoholism alone. That's a 2
percent loss in the nation's productivity.
   The federal government estimates that alcohol and drug abuse
costs the economy nearly $200 billion a year. Two-thirds of that is
attributed to alcohol.
   There is no end to this war. Alcoholics Anonymous and Narcotics
Anonymous, the two most successful, self-supporting treatment
programs, know there is no such thing as a cured addict; only a
recovering one.
   Their members go about it one day at a time. The government can
do no better.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun AMs Sept. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
