<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0921</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government carried out its largest
currency intervention ever from late spring to mid-summer to stem a
rise in the dollar that was spurred by stronger interest rates and
political turmoil in China, a report said.
   The Federal Reserve and the Treasury Department together sold
$11.92 billion in exchange for West German marks and Japanese yen
during the three months ended July 31, according to the report
released Wednesday by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York.
   It was the largest intervention since the winter of 1978-79.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner met with the head of UAL
Corp. in Washington but said the government is merely an observer in
the proposed employee-management takeover of the parent of United
Airlines.
   Skinner said Wednesday one of the department's top priorities has
been scrutinizing the proposed takeover of NWA Inc., parent of
Northwest Airlines, by Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi. He said
his staff will add UAL to its watch list.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House budget office was blamed for
the inability of government statisticians to track significant
changes in the economy and their effect on people and businesses,
even while spending some $2 billion this year trying.
   While the skills of workers are increasingly recognized as key to
economic growth and improving the nation's competitiveness, the
government spends nearly seven times more collecting data on
agriculture than education, the congressional Office of Technology
Assessment said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
