compared with a daily rate of 40,578 during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   While Miss America contestants stroll down the runway in Atlantic
City, N.J., next week, another string of beauties will chug into New
York Harbor for the first-ever Tugboat Beauty Contest, complete with
Bert Parks as emcee.
   The contestants in the Sept. 13 event will be strutting more
horsepower than cheesecake, but organizers believe beauty _ when it
comes to tugboats _ is definitely in the eye of the beholder.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co., a relatively small player in the
world of big trucks, is negotiating with Saab-Scania AB of Stockholm
with an eye on the Swedish company's truck business, experts say.
   Because it has been making and selling cars in Europe for more
than 60 years, Ford wouldn't need Saab's car distribution network.
Ford, in fact, sells more cars in Sweden than does Saab.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market Wednesday suffered the first sizable drop since
reaching all-time highs last month in an atmosphere of uncertainty
about the outlook for Federal Reserve policy and interest rates. But
the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials remained within striking
distance of record levels.
   A healthy bond market helped arrest the slide in stocks, which
saw the Dow Jones average fall nearly 40 points around midday. At
the close the average was down 24.89 points at 2,719.79.
   The dollar retreated after its recent surge, while gold prices
rose.
   Copper futures prices tumbled; oil futures rose; meat futures
rallied; and corn futures gained.
</TEXT>
