<DOCNO> AP890907-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0124EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Value-AddedTax     09-07 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Value-Added Tax,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Value-Added Tax Has Drawbacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 40 percent of chief executives surveyed
nationwide favor introduction of a value-added tax to help reduce
the federal deficit, according to a report.
   But the report released Wednesday by the Conference Board offered
mixed conclusions on whether the enormous revenue potential of a
value-added tax, or VAT, outweighs its drawbacks.
   A value-added tax is passed along during the stages of
production, from raw materials suppliers to manufacturers to
wholesalers to retailers to consumers, who bear the final burden of
the tax.
   At each stage, buyers pay a progressively higher tax to sellers,
who recover a portion of the VAT paid during earlier purchases.
   The Conference Board report estimated that VAT could raise
between $13 billion and $22 billion annually in the United States
for each percentage point of tax levied.
   But it said a VAT would not be cost efficient at below 10 percent
and that countries employing the tax have rates between 15 percent
and 25 percent.
   In a survey of 400 chief executive officers asked recently to
evaluate new revenue sources to reduce the deficit, 42 percent
favored a VAT, 35 percent were opposed and 33 percent were neutral.
   ``Many like VAT because it has demonstrated its feasibility
through a history of good compliance, reasonable administrative
costs and public preference,'' Conference Board research associate
Jessica Skelly said.
   Among concerns cited in the report, though, were the cost and
number of employees that would be needed to implement and operate
the tax.
   The Internal Revenue Service estimated that in 1988 the tax would
have cost the government $700 million and required 20,000 new
employees. Other estimates have been higher, the report said.
   Also, opponents argue that VAT would only allow the government to
spend more money while not necessarily reducing the deficit and
would place a greater burden on poor families who spend more on
goods and services, the report said.
   The report also said that no way of coordinating the federal
value-added tax with state and local taxes such as sales taxes has
been determined.
   The Conference Board is a nonprofit research organization
supported by companies, trade and professional groups, government
agencies, labor unions, schools, libraries and individuals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
