<FIRST>r f PM-BAT     09-07 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BAT,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Takeover Panel To Decide On Extension of Hoylake Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Panel on Takeovers and Mergers says it
will hold a hearing next week to decide whether Hoylake Investments
Ltd. could extend its $21.4 billion hostile bid for BAT Industries
PLC beyond the normal 60-day deadline.
   A ruling on an extension would be pivotal to the outcome of the
13.4 billion-pound hostile offer for the British conglomerate,
analysts said.
   Last week, Sir James Goldsmith, who leads Hoylake, said it would
be difficult for the offer to succeed without an extension from the
panel, an independent body which under British law monitors takeover
developments.
   The panel said Wednesday that Holylake's request would be
considered at a hearing on Wednesday.
   Hoylake made the request for an extension because it is seeking
the required approval from insurance regulators in the United States
for the acquisition of Farmers Group, BAT's U.S. insurance unit.
   Under the laws of the nine states where Farmers operates,
officials must approve any change in control of insurance concerns.
   Hoylake launched its bid for BAT on Aug. 8. Under British law the
first closing date for the offer is Oct. 7.
   Additional delays in gaining approval from insurance regulators
could put Hoylake's ability to meet that deadline into question.
   BAT has argued that the timetable is an integral part of takeover
rules and should not be altered, especially when delays in the U.S.
could have been anticipated.
   Meanwhile, Axa Midi Assurances, the French company that would
acquire Farmers if Hoylake is successful in its bid, said it had
begun seeking regulatory approval to buy the insurance company in
the states where Farmers operates.
   Farmers does business in Texas, Washington, Oregon, Illinois,
Ohio, Kansas, Idaho, Arizona and California.
   Hoylake has filed suit in those states, claiming its purchase of
BAT would not constitute a change in control of Farmers, and that
U.S. regulators have no right to hold up a deal between two foreign
companies.
   Axa has a U.S. subsidiary, Gamma Re, a reinsurer which operates
in 37 states.
   BAT's other businesses include retailing, tobacco and paper
products. It owns Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's stores,
Brown &amp; Williamson Tobacco Corp. and Appleton Papers in Wisconsin.
   Goldsmith announced last month he would sell Farmers to Axa Midi
if his bid succeeded.
</TEXT>
