<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Fed-Currency Bjt   09-07 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Currency, Bjt,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Fed Intervention to Halt Dollar's Rise in May-July Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States intervened in record amounts
from late spring to mid summer to halt the dollar's sharp ascent in
foreign exchange, which resulted from higher interest rates and
political turmoil in China.
   A quarterly foreign-exchange report issued Wednesday by the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York showed the Fed and the Treasury
sold $11.92 billion in exchange for West German marks and Japanese
yen during the three months ended July 31.
   It was the largest intervention since the winter of 1978-79, when
the government leaned the opposite way, buying $6.9 billion with
marks and yen to support a dollar that was being eroded by high
inflation.
   The previous largest sale of dollars occurred when the Fed dumped
$3.2 billion from August to October of 1985. That sale reflected an
agreement among the big industrialized nations, known as the Group
of Seven, to lower the dollar's value to shrink the U.S. trade
deficit.
   The latest quarterly New York Fed report showed the government
bought $7.24 billion worth of yen and $4.68 billion worth of marks.
Overseas central banks also sold dollars, according to the report.
   The United States sold $6.74 billion in May, $4.95 billion in
June and $230 million in July.
   The dollar reached its peak of the year in early June, when it
traded at two-year highs of 2.047 marks and 151.90 yen, up roughly 9
percent and 14 percent respectively from the end of April. However,
by the end of July it was up just 3 percent against the yen and less
than 1 percent vs. the mark.
   Samuel Y. Cross, an executive vice president for the New York
Fed, attributed the retreat from the peak to the central bank dollar
sales and changing perceptions about the economy.
   Lately the dollar has been trading around 1.97 marks and 146 yen,
its highest levels since the May-July period, due to signs of
renewed strength in the economy.
   Currency traders already suspected that the Fed had intervened
heavily during the period, but the Fed's policy is to comment only
well after the fact. In early 1987 the Group of Seven nations _
Japan, West Germany, Britain, France, Italy, Canada and the United
States _ agreed to work together to stabilize the currency markets
following a sharp decline in the dollar. The group also secretly set
target zones for exchange rates, although it has never confirmed
that the zones exist or what they are.
   ``All the intervention we did could be taken as an indication we
wanted to ... bring about greater stability in the exchange rates,''
said Cross. ``We're not driving it down as much as keeping it from
rising.''
   Fed intervention was the strongest in late May, when the dollar
first pierced the psychologically important 2-mark and 142-yen
levels. At that time, investment demand was strong because U.S.
interest rates remained high in comparison to rates abroad.
   During the dollar's surge, the economy appeared strong and the
trade deficit seemed to be shrinking. Traders decided to test the
central bank's firmness in holding down the dollar.
   Also adding support to the dollar was political turmoil abroad,
including the bloody crackdown against student protesters in China
and government scandals in Japan.
   By late June the dollar had softened as interest rates began to
drop and signs of slower economic growth began to emerge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL-ESOPs Bjt   09-07 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL-ESOPs, Bjt,0869</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Employee Buyout Would Have Advantages, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic under ESOPs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest employee-owned company in the nation
would be created if UAL Corp.'s pilots and management succeed with
their $6.75 billion bid for the parent of United Airlines.
   UAL would lead a fast-growing group. In the past two years, more
than 300 U.S. companies have been acquired by their employees,
according to Joseph R. Blasi, a business professor and expert on
employee ownership.
   Federal tax benefits and the wave of hostile buyouts have spurred
employees to take over their companies completely or acquire big
equity stakes.
   The latter category includes big corporations such as J.C. Penney
Co. Inc., Lockheed Corp., Procter &amp; Gamble Co., Polaroid Corp. and
PPG Industries Inc.
   Chicago-based UAL would enjoy marked advantages over other
employee-owned enterprises, some experts say. The company is widely
recognized as one of the strongest and most profitable in the
airline industry, giving it a head start under the new regime of
employee owners.
   UAL Chairman Stephen Wolf, who is part of the takeover team, has
said that under the proposal, the employees do not contemplate
selling any essential assets or revising plans for expanding the
airline fleet and routes.
   ``The fact that United is in good shape certainly does give
(employee ownership) a better start,'' Corey Rosen, executive
director of the National Center for Employee Ownership, said
Wednesday.
   ``It's the first time it's been tried on this scale. If it
succeeds, it would put in a whole new array of weapons for unions to
use.''
   That's a fairly big ``if.'' The Machinists union at United, whose
cooperation is considered critical, has expressed doubt that the
takeover attempt could succeed because it would require enormous new
debt.
   ``I look at it sort of pessimistically now, because we've done an
analysis on United Airlines ... I think they've put a price on it
that's too overpriced,'' John Peterpaul, general vice president of
the Machinists, said Wednesday. ``We don't see the future as rosy as
a lot of people see it.''
   That stance appeared to strengthen the chances that billionaire
investor Marvin Davis could succeed in his rival bid for UAL.
   If the pilot-management attempt does prevail, UAL would displace
car rental giant Avis Inc. as the nation's largest company owned by
its employees.
   An employee stock ownership plan, or ESOP, representing 11,000
Avis workers in the United States took the company private in a
$1.75 billion buyout in September 1987.
   Avis Chairman Joseph Vittoria says he received a letter over a
year ago from the United pilots seeking his advice on ESOPs.
   ``I don't think UAL's size is a hindrance to an ESOP,'' Vittoria
said in a telephone interview. Asked whether its size could actually
be an advantage for employee ownership, he replied, ``It could be,
but it depends on management getting employees involved.''
   Avis has a multi-tiered employee participation program that is
considered a model by some experts. Worker representatives are
elected by their co-workers and participate in monthly
district-level meetings with managers to review operations and make
suggestions.
   The local groups also elect representatives to attend quarterly
zone meetings, semi-annual regional meetings and an annual
company-wide meeting.
   Under the UAL pilot-management proposal, British Airways PLC
would own 15 percent of UAL's stock for an investment of $750
million. The employees would agree to unspecified wage concessions
in exchange for participation in an ESOP that would give them 75
percent of the company.
   News reports have indicated that the pilots union might invest as
much as $1 billion. The rest of the buyout funding apparently would
be borrowed.
   Only a small proportion, about 15 percent, of the employees
participating in ESOPs are unionized. But the pilots, Machinists and
flight attendants at United, the nation's second-largest airline,
are strong unionists.
   UAL under employee ownership ``would have to be run as a
partnership, not as a feudal barony,'' said Blasi, a professor at
California Polytechnic University in San Luis Obispo, whose book,
``Employee Ownership: Revolution or Ripoff?'' is critical of some
ESOPs.
   ``In the airline industry, most ESOPs have not been combined with
a strong employee involvement program. Board seats are not enough,''
he said.
   Blasi said he is waiting to see specific details from Wolf and
the pilots on how labor-management committees would be set up to
address problems and make decisions.
   He cited a 1983-84 experiment with partial employee ownership at
Eastern Airlines, under former chairman Frank Borman, which he
called ``a great success.'' Under the program, Eastern employees
generated ideas to improve productivity.
   An ESOP at Western Airlines, before it was merged into Delta Air
Lines, also was a good example of labor-management cooperation,
Blasi said.
   America West Airlines, an aggressive regional carrier based in
Tempe, Ariz., is about 20 percent owned by its employees. And Delta
established an ESOP in July, in a moved widely viewed as a deterrent
to unwanted suitors as takeover speculation swept through the
airline industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
