<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0136EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EconomicStatistics     09-07 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economic Statistics,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Government Failing to Track Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House budget office has been blamed
for the inability of government statisticians to track significant
changes in the economy and their effect on people and businesses,
even while spending some $2 billion this year trying.
   While the skills of workers are increasingly recognized as key to
economic growth and improving the nation's competitiveness, the
government spends nearly seven times more collecting data on
agriculture than education, said the congressional Office of
Technology Assessment.
   ``It seems unlikely that this is the right ratio, given the
transformation under way in the economy,'' the agency said Wednesday
in a 40-page report. ``Even worse, no organization in either the
executive branch or the Congress has assumed responsibility for
asking whether it's the right ratio.''
   The report, ``Statistical Needs for a Changing U.S. Economy,''
said the White House Office of Management and Budget was told in
1980 to set priorities and coordinate the government's
statistics-collecting efforts.
   ``While it has a mandate to perform this task,'' the technology
experts said, ``OMB has not given it much priority and has dedicated
few resources to the effort.''
   Efforts by agencies in the Labor, Commerce, Health and Human
Services and other departments to correct shortcomings have been
hampered by White House budget officials, said the report, which was
requested by the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
   As an example, it cited cuts in the budgets of most agencies for
collecting and analyzing data during the past eight years and a
resistance by OMB officials to allow new surveys sought by
statisticians.
   ``These organizations are painfully aware of the problems,'' the
researchers said. ``The greatest problem appears to be the absence
of any central place in government where basic questions about
priorities in statistics are being asked.''
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., chairman of the Senate panel's
subcommittee on government information and regulation, said Congress
will likely have to force the issue when the 1980 Paperwork
Reduction Act comes up for reauthorization next year.
   Barbara Clay, a spokeswoman for the White House budget office,
said its officials had not seen the report and so could not comment
on it immediately.
   The congressional researchers acknowledged it has become much
more difficult to develop meaningful statistics on economic growth
and productivity with the emergence of an international market and a
service-based U.S. economy.
   ``The most important inputs purchased by a business may be
research and engineering information and the skills and education of
its employees,'' it said. ``The existing statistical system makes it
extremely difficult to anticipate the potential impact of emerging
technologies.''
   It cited computers and how changes in their capabilities and
prices are reflected in the nation's economic growth, inflation and
productivity figures. For example, it said, the price of one
megabyte of computer memory capacity fell by 95 percent between 1972
and 1987.
   ``Measuring changes in the quality of computers, however, can
seem easy in comparison with the challenge of measuring changes in
the quality of services,'' the report said. ``How do you measure
quality changes in legal services?''
   Changes in the quality of health care and education, which
together account for more than one-sixth of the nation's gross
national product, are not measured at all, the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Milken     09-07 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Milken,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Allow Drexel To Pay Milkens; Firm To Enter Plea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of challenges and delays, Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. is scheduled to plead guilty to securities
crimes Monday and formally settle the highly publicized Wall Street
corruption case.
   The court date was set after prosecutors switched course and
allowed the investment firm to pay its former junk-bond chief,
Michael Milken, his 1988 compensation of more than $100 million,
removing the last roadblock to the plea bargain.
   ``We are pleased that the government has reversed its position
and dropped the unconstitutional provisions of its settlement with
Drexel,'' Arthur Liman, a lawyer for Milken, said in a statement
released Wednesday by a Milken spokesman.
   ``These unconstitutional provisions were a gross abuse of
prosecutorial power,'' the statement said. ``Perhaps now the
government will also reconsider its use and abuse in this case of
the Draconian RICO statute.''
   A 98-count indictment in March charged Milken and his brother
Lowell with wide-ranging securities law and Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organization Act violations. A broader indictment is
expected next month.
   The hearing Monday before U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood in
Manhattan should end months of negotiations and challenges over an
agreement announced in January in the government's insider trading
probe.
   The government's reversal to allow Drexel to pay its indicted
former bond financier was made in court papers filed late last week.
The move was first reported to be under consideration last month.
   Under the plea agreement, Drexel will enter guilty pleas to six
securities and mail fraud felonies. The firm also has agreed to pay
$650 million in fines and restitution.
   The pact had required Drexel to fire Milken and withhold his
compensation for last year, estimated in court papers at more than
$100 million. The agreement also had barred Drexel from giving
Lowell Milken more than half his 1988 pay.
   Both Milkens have since resigned from Drexel.
   In a letter to Wood filed in U.S. District Court late Friday,
Assistant U.S. Attorney John K. Carroll said prosecutors dropped the
pay provisions because of a bail agreement in which the government
will monitor hundreds of millions of dollars of the Milkens' assets.
   ``In light of this security, the matter of any payment to be made
by Drexel to the Milkens can be resolved adequately between Drexel
and the Milkens,'' the letter said.
   Lawyers for the Milkens immediately dropped a motion filed in
January challenging the plea agreement on the grounds that it
unfairly denied the brothers their 1988 pay.
   Defense lawyers and other experts following the case have said
they surmised the government dropped the provision withholding pay
because of a belief it would be rejected in court as
unconstitutional.
   Sources familiar with the case said the government acted
independently.
   ``It was the government deciding on its own, 100 percent, that
they wanted to drop it,'' said one source who asked not to be named.
   A separate settlement with Drexel of fraud and insider trading
charges by the Securities and Exchange Commission is to take effect
once Drexel enters its plea. Under that deal, Drexel has agreed to
broad structural changes and federal supervision for three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
