<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0805EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WPPSSSettlement Bjt   09-07 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WPPSS Settlement, Bjt,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlements Approved in WPPSS Bondholder Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. District judge says that plaintiffs in the
nation's largest municipal-bond default might have gotten
significantly smaller awards had they won their case at trial
instead of settling.
   U.S. District Judge William D. Browning of Tucson, Ariz., on
Tuesday approved settlements to allow $750 million to be distributed
to holders of Washington Public Power Supply System bonds in what he
called ``one of the most complex lawsuits in the history of
securities litigation.''.
   ``There is more than adequate reason to conclude that the
aggregate amount of these settlements ... is fully satisfactory,
given the risks associated with a full trial of the issues,'' said
Chemical Bank of New York, trustee for the bondholders, in a
statement quoting the judge's 106-page opinion, which was not
immediately available.
   It was Browning who presided over the enormously complicated
WPPSS litigation that in the last year resulted in settlements
between Chemical Bank and defendants in the case.
   The trial began a year ago in Tucson but defendants reached
settlements by January. In April, Browning held a fairness hearing
on the settlement in Seattle.
   William H. Berls, a Chemical Bank vice president who has handled
WPPSS matters, on Wednesday called Browning's ruling a ``carte
blanche'' approval of the negotiated settlements.
   ``This is a major milestone in the WPPSS litigation,'' he said.
``The bondholders are just one step away from distribution'' of the
settlement money.
   The final step is for Browning to schedule a distribution
hearing, at which attorneys will argue precisely how the funds
should be distributed, Berls said. No such hearing has been
scheduled, he said.
   In determining the distribution, the judge will emphasize when
each bondholder purchased the bonds, Berls said. The plaintiffs in
the case essentially broke down into two types of bondholders: those
who purchased their bonds before the default on June 15, 1983, and
those who bought bonds afterward.
   In 1983, WPPSS defaulted on $2.25 billion in bonds it had sold to
finance construction of a nuclear power plant at the Hanford nuclear
reservation in Eastern Washington and another at Satsop, west of
Olympia. WPPSS had abandoned construction of those two plants in
1982 because of rising construction costs and doubts about the need
for the plants' power.
   The default was triggered by a Washington state Supreme Court
ruling that the participating utilities lacked the legal power to
sign contracts with WPPSS guaranteeing payment even if no
electricity was generated.
   Dozens of lawsuits were combined into one action against WPPSS,
all 88 utilities that contracted with the consortium to build the
two reactors, engineering firms, Wall Street bond underwriters,
utility and WPPSS directors and a consulting firm.
   The settlements approved require the defendants to pay $580
million into the Chemical Bank-administered settlement fund.
Together with $107 million in settlements approved earlier, plus
interest, the amount available for distribution in December would be
$750 million, Berls said.
   Berls said Chemical Bank was not worried that Browning would have
exercised his other option, that of rejecting the settlements.
   Browning's ruling ``validated all the actions we've taken,''
Berls said.
   ``I think the court by taking the action it did endorsed the end
we were all trying to reach, which was peace,'' he said.
   WPPSS paid no money in the settlement in exchange for cooperation
from its employees at the trial. Plaintiff's attorneys said there
wasn't enough money left in WPPSS to pursue.
   WPPSS was building five nuclear reactors to generate electricity
in the late 1970s, but only one was completed. Two remain
``mothballed'' for construction to resume if enough demand
materializes for the electricity they would produce.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 0844EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AutoSales 1stLd-Writethru f0029 09-07 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf pvs bgng: `For the ... ' to CORRECT year-to-date
sales to first eight, sted nine, months of the year; picks up last graf
pvs bgng: Domestic automakers ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21.4 percent rise in late-August car and light
truck sales may be a sign that sales will drop dramatically as the
calendar year draws to a close, analysts say.
   The eight major U.S. based automakers reported Wednesday that
their vehicles sold at an average daily rate of 49,276 during the
Aug. 21-31 period this year, compared with a rate of 40,578 during
the same time last year.
   ``We think a lot of the volume that we're seeing here is really
coming out of the fourth quarter of this year or the first quarter
of next year,'' said analyst John Kirnan of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. of
New York City.
   ``The $64,000 question is really how bad is volume going to be in
the fourth quarter,'' he said.
   With overseas makers' results added in, car and truck sales were
up 8.4 percent in August over the same month last year. Car sales
rose 11.2 percent and truck sales were 2.2 percent higher for the
month.
   Typically, dealers offer closeout deals as the model year draws
to a close, traditionally on Sept. 30. On top of that, manufacturers
have been offering customers and dealers incentives that lower the
prices of 1989 cars.
   Consumers also have been learning that prices for 1990 cars will
rise, prompting some to buy now rather than later.
   ``Consumers have been bombarded by these price hikes on the 1990
models going up anywhere from 2 (percent) to 9 percent,'' said
analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
of New York City. ``Domestic automakers haven't done that in a long
time.
   ``It's people out there thinking `I've got to buy a car by the
end of the year.'''
   Herb Adcox, owner of Adcox Chevrolet in Chattanooga, Tenn., said
he has seen some increased traffic through his showroom recently,
and incentives are the reason.
   ``With this factory incentive that they have given the dealers,
it's going to lower the price of the car,'' he said. ``I just hope
that it works.
   ``If it doesn't you've got a lot of dealers who are not going to
order '90 models. They can't have inventory on top of inventory.''
   For the first eight months of this year, domestic and imported
car and truck sales were running 3.7 percent behind the pace of last
year, the second-best year in history. Car sales were down 4.1
percent and truck sales were off 2.7 percent.
   Domestic automakers held 77.3 percent of the car and truck market
at the end of August, up from 76 percent at the same time last year.
</TEXT>
