<FIRST>r f PM-McDonald's-Chicken     09-07 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McDonald's-Chicken,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonald's Testing Fried Chicken in Houston, Dallas Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American consumer's continuing taste for
chicken has prompted McDonald's Corp. to begin eyeing the
fried-chicken market.
   McDonald's has begun a new test at six restaurants in Dallas and
six in Houston, selling combination packets of two, three and nine
pieces of deep-fried chicken.
   ``Americans are going toward lighter eating and we're following
the tastes of America,'' said Tom Horler, regional marketing manager
for the Dallas region.
   The company already serves chicken in sandwiches, salads and in
bite-size boneless bits.
   ``The testing is in the embryonic stage,'' said Horler. ``The
question is, can we deliver a good quality, value-priced product in
the quick environment we have?''
   To find this out, the company is looking at how its equipment is
handling the new product and what customers think about it.
   Sometimes, as with the company's experimental pizza, the product
goes back to the kitchen for a recipe makeover after the operational
testing and before it goes out for a full market test.
   McDonald's salads were in the testing phase for 10 years before
being made generally available, Horler said.
   The fried chicken is being sold after 4 p.m., aimed at the family
dinner business.
   There are three combinations: two pieces, a breast and leg,
selling for $1.99; three pieces, breast, leg and thigh, for $2.89;
and nine pieces, three breasts, three legs and three thighs for
$7.89. Dinner rolls are included.
   The chicken is kept frozen and then fried for customers.
   No decision has been made on whether to expand the fried chicken
experiment, Horler said.
</TEXT>
