<FIRST>r f PM-Heinz     09-07 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heinz,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Claim Heinz Kills Dolphins</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.J. Heinz Co. Chairman Anthony J.F. O'Reilly
says his company and animal rights activists stand in agreement _
the slaughter of dolphins caught with yellowfin tuna must end.
   Aside from humanitarian reasons, O'Reilly said, Heinz has a
commercial interest in saving the dolphins because dolphins swim
with tuna in the eastern Pacific Ocean, leading fishing boats to
their catch.
   ``We have more interest in the porpoise than they have ... if you
see them as the sheepdog of the sea,'' O'Reilly said. ``The simple
truth is that releasing dolphins represent a more successful fishing
technique than ignoring their safety.''
   O'Reilly reacted after about 50 protesters, led by the San
Francisco-based Earth Island Institute, picketed Heinz's annual
shareholders meeting at a downtown hotel Wednesday, carrying
anti-Heinz signs and chanting, ``Boycott tuna. Boycott Heinz.''
   Two protesters _ Todd Patterson, 23, of Pittsburgh, and Mark
Heitchue, 24, of Santa Cruz, Calif. _ lowered themselves from a
nearby eight-story building and unfurled a banner reading, ``Heinz
Stop Killing Dolphins,'' before police arrested them on disorderly
conduct, criminal trespass and criminal mischief charges.
   Another protest organizer, Candace Batycki of San Francisco,
briefly disrupted the shareholders' meeting by screaming, ``You're
slaughtering dolphins. What kind of world do you want to live in?''
   Protesters and company officials agreed thousands of dolphins are
being killed with yellowfin tuna in large, encircling nets set
mostly by foreign fishermen.
   Ms. Batycki estimated at least 150,000 dolphins die in the catch
annually.
   ``It's not necessary to fish on dolphins, just easier,'' she
said. ``They (Heinz) have a lot of power in their hands. They have
the power to end this.''
   Protesters claimed a boycott of tuna products has hurt Heinz's
StarKist Seafood Co. subsidiary and other producers. O'Reilly
estimated Pacific yellowfin tuna represents 20 percent of StarKist's
catch.
   But Heinz, in its first-quarter earnings report issued Tuesday,
said StarKist's tuna contributed to a 15 percent increase in
earnings.
   ``Our sales of tuna are at an all-time high,'' O'Reilly said.
   But he told shareholders the killing of dolphins was ``a
legitimate concern.''
   ``We're doing everything we can to save the porpoise,'' O'Reilly
said.
   A new $100,000 research program, announced by StarKist last
Thursday, promises to find ways of using sound to lure dolphins away
or out of fishing nets, he said.
   Heinz spokesman D. Edward I. Smyth said the company is willing to
spend more if early research is fruitful.
   None of about 3,000 Heinz shareholders questioned O'Reilly about
the dolphins issue, but they applauded warmly at a review of Heinz's
television commercials and when O'Reilly announced a two-for-one
stock split and a 16.7 percent increase in quarterly dividends.
   On other matters, O'Reilly said Heinz will not accept irradiated
food from suppliers and will not use radiation in any of its food
processing.
   Sister Patricia Daly of the Sisters of St. Dominic of Caldwell,
N.J., representing several Roman Catholic institutions holding Heinz
stock, said Heinz's policy follows a request by the Interfaith
Center on Corporate Responsibility.
   She called Heinz's policy ``an unprecedented move by any U.S.
corporation.''
   O'Reilly also told reporters the company is trying to expand its
food products into the ``gray market'' of senior citizens. He said
Heinz believes today's consumers will be more concerned with
``health and wellness'' as they age.
   He declined to speculate what products or companies the food
conglomerate might produce or buy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0247 </DOCNO>
