<FIRST>u f PM-RJR-DelMonte     09-07 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RJR-Del Monte,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polly Peck Buying Del Monte's Fresh Fruit from RJR</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. has agreed to sell its fresh
fruit operations of Del Monte Corp. to the British conglomerate
Polly Peck International PLC for $875 million in cash, both
companies announced today.
   The sale of Del Monte Tropical Fruit Co. represents the second
major step by RJR toward divesting around $5.5 billion in food
assets to help offset expenses incurred in the $25 billion buyout by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. earlier this year.
   In June, RJR sold five European food businesses to BSN SA of
France for $2.5 billion.
   The Del Monte unit being acquired sells bananas, pineapples,
papayas, mangoes and other fresh fruits, and represents about a
quarter of Del Monte's sales, which totaled $600 million last year.
   The acquisition, due to be completed by the end of October, is
expected to boost Polly Peck's sales by about 50 percent, according
to the company.
   ``The acquisition of Del Monte represents a remarkable
opportunity for (Polly Peck) to establish itself as one of the
world's largest suppliers of fresh fruit and vegetables,'' Polly
Peck Chairman Asil Nadir said in a statement.
   London-based Polly Peck already markets fruits and vegetables
grown in the Middle East under the brand name of Sun Zest. It also
has interests in electronics, textiles and hotels.
   Del Monte is the world's largest distributor of fresh pineapples
and third largest distributor of bananas. Other Del Monte units
include Del Monte Foods USA and separate units in Europe, Latin
America, Canada and the Far East.
   RJR Chairman Louis V. Gerstner Jr. said several parties have
expressed an interest in acquiring other Del Monte businesses. ``We
are reviewing those proposals but there has been no final decision
yet,'' he said.
   Polly Peck said it planned to finance the acquisition through a
rights issue and bank loans.
</TEXT>
