<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1020EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Obermaier     09-07 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obermaier,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Easy Confirmation Expected for Successor to Manhattan U.S. Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has nominated prominent
Manhattan defense lawyer Otto G. Obermaier as successor to former
U.S. attorney Rudolph Giuliani, the crime-busting prosecutor now
running for New York mayor.
   Obermaier's nomination Wednesday, which had been widely
anticipated, is expected to receive routine confirmation by members
of the Senate Judiciary Committee, though Giuliani once said he
opposed the nomination because Obermaier's firm has represented
targets of securities fraud investigations.
   ``I may be naive in that regard but I am more than happy to
answer any of their questions,'' Obermaier said in an interview from
New York after the nomination was announced.
   ``I've practiced law for 30 years and the great thing about being
a litigator is we do all our professional work in public. The
mistakes and the glories and the victories are all a matter of
public record,'' he said.
   Obermaier, 53, said he has none of the skeletons in the closet
that have derailed some recent federal judicial nominations, as well
as sitting politicians.
   ``I don't think I buy outdated milk,'' he said. ``I don't think I
speed _ at least I don't get caught at it. I pay my taxes. I'll even
answer questions like, Have I ever used drugs? ... The answer is
indeed no.''
   Giuliani, who resigned Jan. 31, has been temporarily succeeded by
acting U.S. attorney Benito Romano, who said he would work with
Obermaier for a smooth transition and then would return to private
law practice.
   As U.S. attorney, Giuliani was at the forefront of the recent
Wall Street scandals, prosecuting numerous cases of insider trading
and stock manipulation.
   Obermaier, of Syosset, N.Y., is a founding partner in the law
firm Obermaier, Morvillo and Abramowitz, which specializes in
white-collar cases. He was recommended for the job in January by
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   From 1964 to 1968, Obermaier was an assistant U.S. attorney in
the Southern District, prosecuting cases involving organized crime,
tax evasion and narcotics. His boss was Robert M. Morgenthau, who is
now Manhattan district attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
