<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru f0019 09-07 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0019,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 7 new grafs to UPDATE with central bank intervention;
picks up 7th graf pvs, `The pound ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several European central banks intervened in
currency markets Thursday in a move apparently intended to hold down
the surging U.S. dollar.
   Central banks in West Germany, France, Spain and Italy confirmed
that they were selling dollars, and sources close to the Bank of
England said that institution was selling dollars against the West
German mark.
   Traders in Frankfurt, West Germany, said the Bank of Canada and
the U.S. Federal Reserve Board also were participating in the
intervention.
   The Swiss National Bank said it had sold dollars against the
Swiss franc.
   The dollar was quoted at 1.9902 marks in Frankfurt in afternoon
trading, only slightly higher than its morning level.
   Gold prices, meanwhile, declined.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 146.87 yen, up 0.22 yen from
Wednesday's close. In afternoon training in London the dollar was
quoted at 147.02 yen.
   The pound sterling fell to $1.5390 in London trading, compared to
Wednesday's late $1.5552 rate.
   Other dollar rates in Europe compared with levels late Wednesday,
included: 1.7180 Swiss francs, up from 1.7045; 6.7050 French francs,
up from 6.6480; 2.2402 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2280; 1,425.50
Italian lire, up from 1,417.50; and 1.1822 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1798.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $359.00 a troy ounce,
down from $360.25 late Wednesday. At mid morning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $359.20.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $359.20, down from $359.75 late
Wednesday.
   Gold in Hong Kong dropped the equivalent of 76 cents an ounce
today to close at $359.71, compared with Wednesday's $360.47.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.11 bid a troy ounce, down
from $5.12 late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
