<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1043EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Miller-WineCoolers     09-07 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miller-Wine Coolers,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miller Brewing Co. Says Will Stop Making Matilda Bay Wine Cooler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miller Brewing Co. says it will stop
production of its Matilda Bay wine cooler in early November because
of poor sales.
   ``From a business standpoint, it is economically imprudent for us
to continue production and marketing of Matilda Bay,'' Thomas A.
Koehler, vice president of sales, said in a prepared statement
Wednesday.
   Koehler said the wine cooler segment declined more than 14
percent in 1988 and industry analysts are predicting this rate of
decline to continue or increase this year.
   Miller said the action would not affect employment at its brewery
in Albany, Ga., the only facility where Matilda Bay is produced.
   Beverly Jurkowski, a Miller spokeswoman, said employees now
working on the Matilda Bay line would get jobs in other areas of the
brewery.
   Ms. Jurkowski said Matilda Bay had climbed to the fourth most
popular wine cooler in the country, but said the brand never made
money nationally.
   ``The chips get pretty spread out by the time you get to No. 4,''
she said.
   The product differed from most wine coolers in that it was
non-carbonated.
   Miller's move means Stroh Brewery Co., Detroit, will be the only
major brewery still selling wine coolers.
</TEXT>
