<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-07 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rise On Crop Forecast, Harvest Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rose strongly early in
today's session on the Chicago Board of Trade, boosted by a bullish
private crop estimate, new export sales and fears that rain could
slow the harvest.
   Grain futures were mostly higher in early trading.
   Some of the soybean buying sprouted from new crop estimates
released late Wednesday by Sparks Commodities Inc., a Memphis,
Tenn.-based analytical firm, that were lower than the Agriculture
Department's August projections.
   Sparks pegged the 1989 U.S. soybean crop at 1.85 billion bushels
compared with the USDA's 1.91-billion-bushel estimate. Sparks
projected the corn harvest at 7.13 billion bushels compared with the
USDA's August estimate of 7.35 billion.
   The USDA will revise its crop estimates on Tuesday.
   A USDA report of a sale of 200,000 metric tons of U.S. soybeans
to unknown destinations prompted further selling, as did fears that
continued wet weather in the Midwest could delay the corn and
soybean harvest, which gets underway in about three weeks.
   ``The ideal weather now would be 80 degrees and dry for the next
four weeks,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of Board of Trade floor
operations for Balfour Maclaine Corp., a futures brokerage firm.
   In early trading, wheat futures were \ cent lower to } cents
higher with the contract for delivery in September at $3.97{ a
bushel; corn was { cent to 1\ cents higher with September at $2.36}
a bushel; oats were unchanged to } cent higher with December at
$1.46\ a bushel; soybeans were 4{ cents to 7 cents higher with
September at $5.94 a bushel.
   Cattle and pork-belly futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange while hog futures declined.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .38 cent higher with October at
72.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .43 cent higher
with September at 82.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to
.10 cent lower with October at 39.57 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .50 cent to 1.38 cent higher with February at 46.20
cents a pound.
   All livestock and meat futures settled higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
