<DOCNO> AP890907-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1946EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-Japan-Britain     09-07 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Britain,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Investment Increases in Britian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese businesses are ``more anxious than ever''
to gain a foothold in Britian before the European Community forms a
single market in 1992, British officials and businessmen said
Thursday.
   ``The Japanese fear that after 1992, they will be locked out by a
fortress Europe,'' said Danny Sharpe, director of investment in the
government's Department of Trade and Industry-Northeast.
   ``They are more anxious than ever to get into our area before
1992 to conform with our way of doing things. Our inquiry rate is
greater than ever before,'' Sharpe said.
   The 12-member European Community in 1992 will form the largest
single market in the world, which will comprise more than 350
million people.
   ``The north of England is the number one choice in Europe for
Japanese investment,'' said Chris Fraser, director of the Agency for
Development in the North of England (NDC).
   With 33 Japanese companies operating in the area _ the majority
in the last few years _ a package that includes tax incentives,
investment allowances and freedom from planning restrictions for
Japanese manufacturers is being offered to attract still more.
   Government efforts are aimed at restoring investment and jobs in
areas that have suffered economically from the decline of
traditional industries such as shipbuilding and coal mining, Sharpe
said.
   The government has alloated more than 150 million pounds, or
about $231.5 million, over the next five years to transform the
industrial structure of the area and will set up a special economic
enterprise in Sunderland, where a Nissan Motor plant is located, to
attract further Japanese investment, said Gordon Ramsey, director of
business development for the Tyne and Wear Development Corporation.
   The northern region has operated a Tokyo office since 1974, and
its presence in Japan has been ``essential'' to efforts to attract
Japanese investment, Fraser told a news conference. It sponsored a
one-day seminar on business opportunities in the region attended by
representatives of more than 200 Japanese companies.
   Nissan Motor Co., Sanyo Electric Group, Komatsu and NSK Bearings
are the leading Japanese companies with plants in northern Britian.
   The Foreign Ministry recently opened an office to deal with
Japanese companies' inquiries about trade barriers and regulations
that will result from the unified market in 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
