<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BorgStrike     09-07 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Borg Strike,0253</SECOND>
<UNK>UAW Strikes Borg Warner in Contract Dispute</UNK>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,200 United Auto Workers walked off
their jobs at Borg Warner Corp. early today after failing to reach
agreement on a new three-year contract.
   Negotiations resumed about 8 a.m. today, said union member Dennis
McKibben, who answered the telephone at UAW Local 287, but he said
he did not know how close the two sides might be to a settlement.
   Borg Warner is the sole supplier of transmissions to Ford Motor
Co. and has several other long-term contracts, said Jack Reising,
vice president of human resources at Borg Warner.
   Those contracts could be in jeopardy if the strike continues for
very long, he said. The company, which has some inventory
stockpiled, met with salaried workers today to come up with a plan
to resume manufacturing, he said.
   Reising said the company had asked the workers to pay a greater
share of health insurance costs in exchange for partial ownership in
the company.
   Hourly and salaried employees could have established 50 percent
or more ownership of the operation, including seats on the baord of
directors, Reising said.
   Salaried workers accepted the plan but the union turned it down,
he said.
   Union officials said sticking points were insurance, pensions and
wages. Local president Sam Dragoo said the two sides had been
negotiating since July.
   The plant, which employs 2,600, produces automotive, marine and
industrial transmissions and transmissions for four-wheel drive
vehicles.
</TEXT>
