<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1542EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Construction     09-07 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Construction,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Orders Construction Firms To Stop Price-Fixing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it has ordered six
Japanese construction firms working on a multibillion-dollar airport
project in western Japan to disband a price-fixing cartel.
   In a similar move, Japan's Fair Trade Commission has ordered 24
shipbuilders to end a production cartel by October, it was reported.
   The actions seem to indicate Japan is responding to U.S.
criticisms that price-fixing cartels prevent foreign firms from
competing for business in Japan.
   James F. Rill, assistant attorney general of the U.S. Justice
Department, told Fair Trade Commission chief Setsuo Umezawa in a
meeting Wednesday that Japan should strictly enforce the
anti-monopoly law, said the Asahi Shimbun, a major national
newspaper.
   Rill participated in Japan-U.S. trade talks earlier in the week
in which American officials said business practices such as
collusion were preventing progress in shrinking the U.S. trade
deficit with Japan.
   Umezawa told Rill the Fair Trade Commission would take strong
action against violators of laws prohibiting private monopolies and
maintaining fair trade and said violators of those laws would be
treated ``with a stern attitude,'' the paper reported.
   The Kyodo News Service, quoting reliable sources, said late
Thursday that the Fair Trade Commission had ordered 24 top
shipbuilders to disband a cartel formed to help them weather a
serious slump in the industry.
   Japanese officials were not immediately available for comment
late Thursday evening.
   The Fair Trade Commission's order to disband the construction
cartel followed a year-long investigation into a price-fixing
agreement among contractors supplying sand for the Kansai
International Airport, said a commission official.
   The Kansai airport became the focus of a major dispute between
Japan and the United States three years ago when U.S. officials
claimed that corporate collusion and obscure bidding procedures were
preventing foreign companies from winning contracts.
   Construction of the $6.7 billion airport off Osaka began in
January 1987, with completion of the first phase of the nation's
first 24-hour commercial airport slated for 1993.
   Mitsuo Omura, representing the eight-company Offshore Reclamation
Construction Association, told a news conference in Osaka Wednesday
the cartel was ``necessary and an appropriate method to smoothly
carry out a big national project'' like the Kansai airport.
   But an official at major construction firm Ohbayashi Corp.,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said, ``We will discuss the
matter with other firms a way to accept the commission's order.''
   The FTC identified the members of the cartel as Ohbayashi, Kajima
Corp., Aoki Corp., Takenaka Doboku Co., Saeki Kensetsu Kogyo, and
Yorigami Construction Co.
   The mass-circulation Mainichi Shimbun said Thursday the six firms
would be fined a total of $2.2 million in surcharges, equivalent to
1.5 percent of the total value of sand supplied to the project.
   The construction association, which has two weeks to notify the
antitrust agency whether it will comply with the order, faces
exclusion from bidding on public works projects, including those of
other local governments, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
