<FIRST>u f AM-HyperCar Bjt   09-07 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hyper Car, Bjt,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toy Companies Bet Big on Super Fast Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As American kids grow bored with video games and
stop buying them, toy companies are hoping to pick up the slack by
importing the latest craze from Japan: 6-inch model cars that move
at the equivalent, when scaled up to full size, of 320 miles per
hour.
   But executives who gathered in Boston for a toy industry
conference Thursday expressed one nagging doubt about their new
``hyper cars.'' The darn things move so fast, how can kids possibly
play with them?
   ``It's a real problem,'' conceded Kenneth A. Bloom, vice
president for finance at Matchbox International Ltd. ``You put it
down on the rug and let it go, and it's just going to shoot off and
keep going until it hits something or flips over.''
   The $5 to $12 cars, powered by two or three AA batteries, move at
actual speeds of about 10 miles per hour. But in comparison with
their scale, which is 1-32 of a full-sized car, they easily outrun
Formula I racers.
   Matchbox and its major competitors _ Hasbro Inc., Mattel Inc. and
Tonka Corp. _ plan to spend a total of $20 million to $25 million by
Christmas to promote the flashy vehicles, most of which are just now
hitting retail stores.
   It's an unusually late product introduction for the industry, and
a marketing gamble driven by equal parts of excitement and worry.
   At the International Toy Fair in New York in January, when new
products traditionally are unveiled, Mattel and Tonka displayed
their super-fast cars but were virtually ignored by retailers.
   Since then, however, two things have happened.
   One is that the cars have taken off in Japan, selling an
estimated 45 million units and whetting the appetites of American
toy store chains.
   The other is that the $2 billion-a-year market for video games
may have peaked, and no ``hot'' new toys have emerged since Cabbage
Patch Dolls and the board game Trivial Pursuit racked up hundreds of
millions of dollars in sales in the mid-1980s.
   Stephen O. Shank, Tonka Corp.'s chief executive officer, told the
Boston toy conference that he expects ``an orderly decline'' in
video game sales starting next year, and Tonka has decided to drop
its Sega video line in 1990.
   The last time there was a downturn in video games, in 1980-81,
several toy companies' profits plunged and ``it got pretty bloody
out there,'' said Steve Eisenberg, a toy industry analyst for the
investment firm of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., the conference's sponsor.
   To avoid such a debacle again, toymakers have been casting about
for something with enough sparkle to pull parents and children back
into the toy stores.
   ``The industry has lacked a hot product for two years, and
everyone thinks this (hyper car) thing could be it,'' said Bruno
Ferretti, president of Tons Of Toys, a chain of 25 stores in the
Northeast.
   The cars come in numerous designs, inclding some with
interchangeable motors and gear boxes. Although they are being
marketed under various names, such as Hyper-Drivers and Record
Breakers, most versions are made in Japan and are nearly identical
in construction.
   Toymakers hope to solve the problem of how to play with the
speeding vehicles by selling plastic track that kids can put
together in their bedrooms, garages or backyards. In Japan, arcades
have installed elaborate tracks that junior racers pay to use. But
some toy executives are doubtful the same thing will happen in
America.
   Tyco Toys Inc., the leading maker of slot cars and
radio-controlled vehicles, has decided to sit out the craze.
   ``We don't think it's a good product, we don't think it has good
play value, and we don't think it's going to be successful,'' Tyco
President Richard E. Grey told the industry conference. ``We're
prepared to be wrong. But we're also willing to stand up and be
counted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
