<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-07 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rise On Increased Exports, Crop Estimate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices posted strong gains
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, boosted by perceptions of
increased foreign demand for U.S. soy products and by a private crop
analysts' bullish harvest forecast.
   Grain futures closed mixed.
   The export news came from three directions, beginning with the
Agriculture Department's announcement late Wednesday that 200,000
metric tons of U.S. soybeans had been sold to unknown destinations.
Traders speculated the beans were bound for China, Russia or Japan.
   Rumors that the USDA would grant Pakistan $80 million in credit
to purchase U.S. soybean oil prompted further buying in the soybean
complex, as did talk that a vegetable oil sale to the Soviet Union
was in the works.
   The soybean market also was supported by new crop estimates by
Sparks Commodities Inc., a Memphis, Tenn.-based analytical firm,
that were lower than the Agriculture Department's August projections.
   Sparks pegged the 1989 U.S. soybean crop at 1.85 billion bushels
compared with the USDA's 1.91 billion-bushel estimate.
   Sparks projected the corn harvest at 7.13 billion bushels
compared with the USDA's August estimate of 7.35 billion.
   The USDA will revise its crop estimates on Tuesday.
   If Sparks' estimates prove correct, soybean prices may be headed
for an extended stay above $6 a bushel, said Pat O'Connell, a grain
market analyst with Refco Inc. in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1\ cents lower to 1} cents
higher with September at $3.97 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 1\
cents higher with September at $2.36} a bushel; oats were } cent to
2 cents higher with September at $1.36\ a bushel; soybeans were 3{
cents to 9} cents higher with September at $5.97 a bushel.
</TEXT>
