<DOCNO> AP890907-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2029EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CapitalGains     09-07 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Says He'll Fight Capital-Gains Tax Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell said
Thursday he will vigorously oppose a capital-gains tax cut, which he
called a giveaway to the rich that would have to be financed by
middle-income taxpayers.
   Mitchell said he favors preferential tax treatment for capital
gains, but only as part of a fair, progressive tax structure that
would include raising the maximum tax rate paid by wealthier
Americans on all types of income.
   ``The present proposal is unfair, unwise and will increase the
deficit,'' Mitchell, D-Maine, told reporters. ``It will require
middle-class taxpayers to make up that tax break for the wealthy.''
   Mitchell cited estimates that on average, a capital-gains
reduction would be worth $31,000 a year to a person with income over
$200,000.
   The House Ways and Means Committee is expected to approve a
capital-gains cut next week.
   Until passage of the 1986 tax overhaul, capital gains _ which are
profits from the sale of stock and other investments _ were taxed at
a lower rate than other income. But the capital-gains preference _
as well as such breaks as deductions for sales taxes and universal
Individual Retirement Accounts _ was taken away so that tax rates on
all kinds of income could be cut significantly.
   President Bush promised during the campaign last year to restore
the preference for capital gains, arguing such action would spur
investment and saving. He has asked Congress to cut the maximum
capital-gains rate, now 33 percent, to 15 percent.
   A compromise reduction, which has the president's support, was
proposed by Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga. It would cut the top rate for 2{
years to 20 percent, then raise it permanently to 28 percent and
ensure that profits caused solely by inflation would not be taxed.
   Jenkins' plan has the backing of a bare majority of the House
Ways and Means Committee, but the panel's Democratic leadership has
delayed a vote in an effort to win support for a third plan.
   Offered by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., the new proposal would
``index'' the value of investments so that inflation-caused gain
would not be taxed. But it would go a big step further for assets
held for five or more years, exempting from taxation as much as half
the price for which such an investment is sold.
   Mitchell said that because of the budget deficit, this is not the
time to consider any cut in capital-gains taxes. Asked if he is
``prepared to go to the mat'' in opposition to a cut, he stomped his
foot and replied ``yes.''
   He said that if a preference is voted for capital gains, that
would increase pressure to restore other breaks that were taken away
in the 1986 overhaul.
   Coincidentally, Sens. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., introduced a bill Thursday that would restore
slightly modified but fully deductible IRAs for all workers. A
worker, regardless of income, could avoid tax on up to $2,000 per
year contributed to an IRA; one with an unemployed spouse could
contribute another $1,000.
   The worker would be allowed a tax credit for 15 percent of the
IRA contribution. Thus, one who made the maximum $2,000 contribution
could save $300 in taxes.
   The 1986 law retained fully deductible IRAs only for those not
covered by a company pension regardless of income, and couples
earning less than $35,000 and single workers earning less than
$25,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MistakenIdentity Bjt   09-07 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mistaken Identity, Bjt,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company's Name Change Contest Attracts 9,000 Entries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Fluorocarbon Co., who felt like a
corporate Al Capone because people wrongly thought his products
zapped the ozone layer, said Thursday he's received more than 9,000
entries in his contest to rename the company.
   The safe-sounding suggestions, from Fluoroseals to Notox to
Pro-Ozone Inc. to Oat Bran Co., came in letters from points as
farflung as Stuttgart, West Germany, to a couple of U.S. jails, said
Peter Churm, chairman of the Laguna Niguel-based company.
   ``One of the jailbirds was in San Diego and one was in the
Cleveland pokey,'' Churm said. ``The guy from the San Diego County
Jail apologized that he couldn't have it typed.''
   Churm decided to rename Fluorocarbon this year after brokers
balked at pitching the stock to investors.
   The problem: A lot of people confused Fluorocarbon with
chlorofluorocarbons, the compounds that are believed to erode the
ozone layer that screens cancer-causing ultraviolet rays.
   In fact, the smallish company ($250 million in 1988 sales) makes
custom seals, gaskets, bearings and the like from Teflon and related
plastics known as fluorocarbons. Whirlpool Corp., Boeing Co. and
Navistar International are among Churm's customers, and Fluorocarbon
seals are even used in the space shuttle.
   The deadline for postmarked entries was Aug. 31, so Churm figured
nearly all of them had arrived by Thursday.
   ``As of this morning, we've had 3,647 letters with somewhere
between 9,000 and 10,000 suggestions altogether,'' he said.
   Some suggestions were silly: Not Chlorofluorocarbon Inc.,
Fiber-Fab, Seals R Us, Fluoraluralura.
   ``And any with American, Laguna, or my name will be instantly
eliminated,'' Churm said.
   There went The Churminators Inc. and Laguna Buna.
   A committee headed by Churm will winnow the entries to 10 in the
next couple of weeks. Then the lawyers will get busy starting with
the first name until they find one that isn't yet taken by another
company. The winner should be announced by late October.
   The prize is 100 shares of Fluorocarbon stock, which has been
trading at about $16 per share.
   ``We'll do something special for the winner,'' Churm said.
   The flood of entries became so huge this summer after the Great
Name Change was announced that Fluorocarbon assigned two workers to
the contest, one hired temporarily to feed names into a computer.
   Most employees will be glad when it's over.
   ``It's been a bit overwhelming,'' Churm said. ``We're set up to
be a manufacturing company, not some PR firm.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0277 </DOCNO>
