<FIRST>r f AM-WarnerBankruptcy     09-07 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner Bankruptcy,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sets Date To Confirm $16 Million Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bankruptcy judge on Thursday pulled
former Ohio financier Marvin Warner's case out of liquidation and
restored it to Chapter 11 reorganization so creditors can decide on
a proposed $16 million settlement.
   The creditors are expected to vote on the plan within the next
few weeks, and U.S. ankrutpcy Judge George Proctor scheduled a Sept.
27 hearing in Orlando to confirm the tally.
   The judge approved a motion to return Warner's case to Chapter 11
protection from the liquidation he'd ordered on July 31, saying,
``The court does not plan to throw a monkey wrench'' in the proposed
settlement filed earlier this week in court.
   Under the plan, Warner would immediately pay $10 million and make
three annual $2 million payments beginning with the first
anniversary of the plan's approval. Warner also will pay all legal
fees and administrative costs, and an estimated $2 million in taxes
associated with liquidation of assets to pay the settlement.
   Warner, 70, has been the target of a flood of lawsuits following
the collapse of his Cincinnati-based Home State Savings Bank in
March 1985. He filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in October
1987 against creditors seeking more than $4.5 billion.
   Warner was convicted on Ohio felony charges in Home State's
collapse but was acquitted of federal charges in a separate trial.
He is appealing the state conviction and a restitution order.
   Home State collapsed four days after Fort Lauderdale-based ESM
Government Securities Inc. was shut down by federal regulators for
insolvency. Home State had invested heavily with ESM through
securities trades and lost $144 million when ESM was closed.
   The creditors, most of whom have already agreed to the
settlement, will formally vote on the plan before attending the
hearing in Orlando.
   At that hearing, the judge will determine whether it was approved
by all classes of creditors and whether it meets the requirements of
the bankruptcy law. If that is the case, he will sign an order
confirming the plan and it will go into effect.
</TEXT>
