<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     09-07 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rose in Latest Week to New All Time High of $344.65 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 463 money market mutual
funds rose by $1.26 billion in the latest week to a new record of
$344.65 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   It was the 10th straight weekly all-time high and reflected the
growing popularity of such investments despite a recent trend toward
lower interest rates.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday followed a $53.7
million rise in fund assets the previous week, the Washington-based
mutual fund trade group said.
   In the latest week, assets of 227 general purpose funds rose
$770.1 million to $110.68 billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds
increased $1.04 billion to $149.21 billion, and assets of 141
institutional funds declined $557.1 million to $84.77 billion, the
institute said.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.24 percent from 8.29 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.30 percent from 8.32 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 37
days, down from 38 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts fell to 6.45 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.46 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was unchanged at 5.11 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.26
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.28 the
previous week. Yields were 8.31 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.30
percent; 8.23 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.21 percent; and 8.21
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.20 percent.
</TEXT>
