<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1657EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CatastrophicCare 1stLd-Writethru f0125 09-07 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0125,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Tax-Writers Ready to Amend Catastrophic Care Provisions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with GOP senators at White House, inserting new 5th
graf, Meanwhile ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate tax-writers, yielding to loud complaints
from many older Americans, indicated Thursday they would join their
House counterparts and go along with major changes in Medicare
insurance covering the costs of a catastrophic illness.
   Several members of the Senate Finance Committee, however,
rejected a revision approved by the House Ways and Means Committee
to cut costs for the higher-income elderly but raise them for older
people with lower incomes.
   ``I want to make it clear at the outset that, as chairman, I will
oppose any increase in the flat premium paid by retirees of modest
means,'' said Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who heads the Finance
Committee.
   ``We should neither repeal ... (catastrophic coverage) nor shift
a greater share of costs ... to beneficiaries who can least afford
them,'' said Sen. Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii.
   Meanwhile, Republican congressional leaders met with President
Bush at the White House. Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., told reporters
afterward that several of the lawmakers told Bush the catastrophic
care act ``ought to be repealed in toto.''
   The program, enacted barely a year ago, is under heavy fire from
some older Americans who say they don't need the protection and from
others _ mainly those with higher incomes _ who object that the
coverage is financed only by the elderly and not by all taxpayers.
   About two-thirds of the cost of the catastrophic care insurance
program is paid by the 41 percent of older citizens whose incomes
are high enough that they owe federal income tax of more than $150.
They pay a surtax of 15 percent on income tax above $150; about 1.8
million of the 33 million Medicare beneficiaries will pay the
maximum surtax of $800 this year.
   The surtax rate is due to increase to 28 percent and the maximum
surtax to $1,050 by 1993.
   The rest of the cost is financed through a flat fee of $4 per
month per retiree. That fee is due to rise to $10.20 by 1993.
   Complaints from the elderly prompted the Ways and Means Committee
to reduce some catastrophic care benefits, cut the surtax rate by
half and raise the flat monthly fee significantly. Those changes
have not been enough to mollify the protesters, as Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., the Ways and Means chairman, learned; he was
chased down a street in his hometown of Chicago by angry retirees
last month.
   ``You almost have a sense when you go home of being unwanted,
unloved and unappreciated on this issue,'' Sen. Robert Packwood,
R-Ore., told colleagues Thursday.
   The Finance Committee is likely to begin voting on how to change
the program Friday.
   The Bush administration said it would prefer no change at all,
but William Diefenderfer, deputy director of the Office of
Management and Budget, conceded ``that doesn't seem to be what's
going to happen.''
   Diefenderfer noted that repeal of catastrophic care coverage
would worsen the federal deficit in 1990 by as much as $7 billion
because taxes earmarked for the program come in faster than benefits
are paid out. Killing the program would automatically trigger
across-the-board cuts in most federal spending.
   There is considerable support in the House for outright repeal of
catastrophic care insurance, an idea that drew the support of Sen.
John C. Danforth, R-Mo.
   ``I question the kind of commitment we made last year,'' he said,
noting the program leans toward long-term hospital care.
   ``This isn't something they (older Americans) want,'' Danforth
said. ``It's something they fear..., being hooked up'' to
life-support equipment and the like.
   The Finance Committee staff outlined seven options for changing
catastrophic care coverage, most of which would require retirees to
pay a larger share of expenses but also allow them to reject the
insurance _ but only if they also drop Medicare Part B, which covers
physicians' fees.
   The panel has two basic proposals for changing the way the
program is financed:
   _Freeze the surtax rate at 10 or 15 percent and reduce the
maximum annual surtax to $585. This would require retirees to
continue paying most of the costs of coverage.
   _Require non-retirees to pay a share of the cost of catastrophic
insurance by raising to $60,000 the $48,000 maximum amount of wages
subject to the 1.45 percent Medicare hospitalization tax. The tax,
paid as part of the Social Security tax through payroll deductions,
is matched by the employer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
