<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Markets Maintain Upward Momentum But Rally Loses Some Energy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures finished with small to moderate gains
Thursday as the recent rally in the energy markets appeared to
weaken.
   Wholesale gasoline prices, which spurted Wednesday on reports of
refinery fires, maintained much of their upward momentum, helped by
a bullish weekly report on stocks.
   But prices of crude oil and wholesale home heating oil ran into
resistance.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for October
delivery of unleaded gasoline rose 0.52 cent to 55.63 cents a
gallon, adding to Wednesday's gain of 1.35 cents. The November,
December and January contracts also moved up.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
the October contract of No.2 heating oil edged 0.02 cent higher to
55.50 cents a gallon, stabilizing after Wednesday's jump of 0.91
cent. Contracts for more distant months ended with minor gains.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $19.41 per 42-gallon barrel, up
13 cents from Wednesday when the contract settled with an increase
of 23 cents. Other delivery months closed with small losses and
gains.
   Richard Kane, a vice president of energy futures trading at
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., said activity in the energy pits retained a
positive tone even though some futures faltered.
   ``The market seemed to stall in crude but continued strong for
gasoline,'' said Kane. ``On the day, we saw a very good
consolidation period.''
   Prices for gasoline recently have benefited from concerns about
possible tightening in supplies temporarily. On Wednesday, a fire at
Shell Oil Co.'s Martinez, Calif. refinery and one at Ashland
Petroleum Co.'s refinery in St. Paul Park, Minn. added to the
speculation.
   After the close of business Wednesday, the American Petroleum
Institute issued its weekly inventory statistics that were viewed as
bullish for gasoline.
   The API reported a 5.8 million-barrel drawdown in gasoline stocks
and a 1.5 million-barrel drawdown in crude stocks. The drop in
gasoline inventories was larger than the market had expected while
the crude figure was in line with projections.
</TEXT>
