<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2100EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CattleDisease     09-07 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle Disease,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experimental Vaccine for Cow Venereal Disease Shows Promise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental vaccine for a venereal disease
that kills unborn calves appears to be controlling the illness that
causes an estimated $500 million in losses annually nationwide, a
researcher said Thursday.
   ``Within the next two or three months we'll begin to get a much
better idea of just how efficient this product is,'' said Bill
Kvasnicka, Nevada Extension Veterinarian. ``But at this point,
everything points toward the fact that this is going to be an
extremely good vaccine for use in the field.
   ``We see it as a major breakthrough to controlling this disease.''
   The vaccine for the sexually transmitted trichomoniasis is now
available in 41 states under conditional license from the U.S.
Department of Agriculture. Researchers estimate the vaccine reduces
the incidence of trichomoniasis by more than 90 percent.
   Kvasnicka, Mark Hall, a microbiologist at the University of
Nevada School of Medicine, and Don Hanks, department chair at UNR's
Veterinary Medicine Department, began developing the vaccine a few
years ago.
   ``Nevada's cattlemen asked us to develop something because so
many cattle were infected with this disease,'' said Kvasnicka,
citing statistics that 44.1 percent of Nevada cattle tested positive
for the disease in 1987.
   Adult cows don't show symptoms of the disease when infected with
trichomoniasis that's spread during breeding. But cows with the
illness can become infertile, abort or their fetuses die, Kvasnicka
said.
   Vaccinated cows tested so far in Nevada are ``clearing'' the
trichomoniasis disease within weeks and there appears to be no
embryonic damages, Kvasnicka said.
   ``It's really amazing,'' he said. ``But we're still measuring the
impact on whether we can save the embryos.''
   Researchers are scheduled next week to check on a couple of
Nevada cattle herds that have been vaccinated to determine whether
the disease has killed any unborn calves.
   ``A key test will come in October when we test the cattle after
120 days of pregnancy,'' he said. ``But we're pretty optimistic
because the disease appears to have the biggest effect in the 30 to
60 day period of pregnancy.''
   Cows have a 282-day gestation period.
   An acutely infected herd can lose up to 40 percent of its calves
while one that has been carrying the disease for years can lose as
many as 10 percent of its unborn calves, Kvasnicka said.
   If the vaccine is proven safe, Kvasnicka said the USDA is
planning by Jan. 1 to decide whether to fully license the product
that was refined by Fort Dodge Laboratories.
   In the early 1980s, researchers in Australia studied the disease,
developing a vaccine for bulls. But Hall said that didn't stop the
disease.
   ``The problem with that approach is that if one bull in a herd
fails to develop immunity and becomes infected, he passes the
disease to every heifer he breeds,'' he explained. ``That is not a
good way to go. We need to protect the whole herd.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890907-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1751EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-07 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Despite Intervention; Gold Down Slightly</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traders carried the dollar to the highest levels
in nearly three months on Thursday, although selling by central
banks knocked the currency off its peak of the day.
   Central banks in West Germany, France, Spain, Italy and
Switzerland confirmed they sold dollars to restrain the currency,
and traders said the Bank of Canada and the U.S. Federal Reserve
joined in the concerted action.
   The bankers are committed to keeping exchange rates stable to
avoid damage to world trade.
   At its peak in late European trading the dollar went above 1.99
West German marks, just shy of the psychologically important level
of 2 marks to the dollar. It ended the New York trading day below
1.98 marks.
   Propelling the dollar upward have been attractive U.S. interest
rates and confidence in the health of the U.S. economy and financial
markets. The dollar is near its levels of mid-June, when a rally
carried it to two-year highs.
   The volume of trading was not especially heavy, reflecting
traders' uncertainty about the strength of the current rally, said
Keith Raphael, an assistant vice president at Bank Brussels Lambert
in New York.
   In the absence of heavy buying demand, central banks were able to
get some results from a relatively modest amount of dollar-selling.
Still, many traders expected the market to keep testing the central
banks' resolve.
   ``There's fundamentally no reason for the dollar to come off,''
said Bill Doyle, a corporate foreign exchange trader at the Hong
Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp. branch in New York.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 146.87 yen, up 0.22 yen from
Wednesday's close. Later in London the dollar was quoted at 147.10
yen. In New York the dollar traded at 146.65 yen, below its levels
of earlier in the day but above its close of 146.10 late Wednesay.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5460 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5552 late Wednesday. In
New York the pound traded at $1.5520, weaker against the dollar than
$1.5525 on Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.9798 West German marks, up from
1.9753; 1.7075 Swiss francs, up from 1.7048; 1.1859 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1802; 6.6685 French francs, up from 6.6560; and
1,419.3 Italian lire, up from 1,417.9.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.9845 West German marks, up from 1.9735; 1.7120
Swiss francs, up from 1.7045; 6.6880 French francs, up from 6.6480;
2.2423 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2280; 1,426.20 Italian lire, up
from 1,417.50; and 1.1842 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1798.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $359.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $360.25. In Zurich, gold was
unchanged at a bid $359.75. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 76
cents to close at a bid $359.71.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $360.20 a troy ounce from $361.60 on Wednesday.
Later Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was bid
at $359.70, down from $360.70 an ounce on Wednesday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market to a late bid
price of $5.11 a troy ounce from Wednesday's $5.12. On New York's
Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $5.117 an ounce
from $5.103 on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
