<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Seagram     09-07 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Seagram,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seagram's Profit Up 20 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Figures are U.S. dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seagram Co. Ltd. reported Thursday that its
second-quarter profit jumped 20 percent from a year earlier, due
partly to continued strength in its beverage business.
   The Montreal-based company said net income for the three months
ended July 31 rose to $198.4 million, or $2.07 a share, from $165.5
million, or $1.74 a share, in the same period in 1988.
   Revenue totaled $1.3 billion, up 5 percent from $1.2 billion last
year.
   For the first half of its fiscal year, Seagram netted $394.9
million, or $4.07 a share, on revenue of $2.5 billion. That was 20
percent higher than earnings in 1988 of $328 billion, or $3.45 a
share, on $2.2 billion in revenue.
   Seagram attributed the increase in earnings to continued strength
in its beverage business, which includes distilled spirits, wine and
juice, and to favorable results of chemical giant Du Pont Co., in
which it holds a 24 percent stake.
   Among Seagram's brand-name products are Chivas Regal, Martell
Cognacs, Mumm and Perrier-Jouet Champagnes, Seagram's Coolers and
Tropicana Pure Premium Orange Juice.
</TEXT>
