<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1816EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     09-07 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belly Futures Surge On Hopes For Polish Pork Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for frozen pork bellies soared the 2-cents-a-pound
daily limit Thursday on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange on
speculation that America's belly surplus could disappear in a
package of food aid to Poland.
   On other markets, soybean futures posted strong gains while
energy futures and precious metals futures were mixed.
   Frozen pork belly futures settled 2 cents higher across the board
with the contract for delivery in February at 46.82 cents a pound.
The rally helped lift livestock futures contracts: live cattle
settled .12 cent to .55 cent higher with October at 72.70 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .58 cent higher with October
at 82.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent lower to .40 cent
higher with October at 39.75 cents a pound.
   The February pork-belly contract has risen about 21 percent in
value since Aug. 1, when February bellies traded as low as 38.70
cents a pound.
   Most of the gains have occurred in the past week on hopes that
some of the near-record supplies of bellies languishing in deep
freeze will be given to Poland along with other U.S. commodities.
   ``We probably will end up shipping bellies to Poland,'' said Dale
Durchholz, a livestock-market analyst with AgriVisor Services Inc.
in Bloomington Ill. ``The question is how many and when.''
   A pork belly is the part of a pig from which bacon is made.
   The Agriculture Department's last count showed 96.4 million
pounds of pork bellies in cold storage as of Aug. 1, the largest
supply for that date since the record year of 1971.
   Analysts say the resulting drop in bacon prices has led to
greater consumption and a more rapid movement of bellies out of
freezers, so that the USDA's Sept. 22 cold-storage report is
expected to show 55 million to 60 million pounds in cold storage as
of Sept. 1.
   When talk of a Polish pork-belly shipment first surfaced last
week, traders were speculating the amount would be about 30 million
pounds.
   On Wednesday, a financial news service reported the Poles were
seeking 50,000 metric tons, or more than 110 million pounds each of
bellies and beef.
   U.S. officials have been cautious in their statements about a
possible shipment. On Thursday, Christopher Goldthwait, an assistant
administrator with the USDA's foreign agriculture service, said it
was premature to talk about quantities or even about what
commodities may be included in an aid package.
   Durchholz said the market may be overreacting, but he conceded
the U.S. belly surplus no longer looked so enormous.
   ``When I start looking at the numbers being batted around, all of
a sudden you're saying that what was an overabundance is not
necessarily so,'' he said.
   Soybean futures prices reached two-week highs on the Chicago
Board of Trade, boosted by perceptions of increased foreign demand
for U.S. soy products and by a bullish harvest forecast from
Memphis, Tenn.-based Sparks Commodities Inc.
   Sparks pegged the 1989 U.S. soybean crop at 1.85 billion bushels
compared with the USDA's August estimate of 1.91 billion bushels.
The USDA will revise its crop estimates on Tuesday.
   If Sparks is right, soybean prices could be headed for an
extended stay above $6 a bushel, said Pat O'Connell, a grain market
analyst with Refco Inc. in Chicago.
   Soybeans settled 4\ cents to 9\ cents higher with September at
$5.96} a bushel; wheat futures settled 1 cent lower to 1\ cents
higher with September at $3.97 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 1
cent higher with September at $2.36{ a bushel; oats were \ cent to 2
cents higher with September at $1.36\ a bushel.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled 4 cents lower to 13 cents higher with October at
$19.41 a barrel; heating oil was .11 cent lower to .04 cent higher
with October at 55.50 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .10 cent
to .54 cent higher with October at 55.63 cents a gallon.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold futures settled $1.40
lower across the board with October at $362.30 a troy ounce; silver
was 1.3 cents to 1.7 cents higher with September at $5.117 a troy
ounce.
</TEXT>
