<HEAD>Jacobs Group Reduces Holding In Allegheny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a year after threatening to seek
control of Allegheny International Inc., an investment group led by
Irwin Jacobs said Thursday it has reduced its holding in the company
to 6.75 percent.
   The group, which includes Minneapolis banker Carl Pohlad,
previously held 9 percent of the appliance maker's stock. It
disclosed the latest move in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, but did not give a reason for reducing its
Allegheny stake.
   Neither Jacobs nor Pohlad returned phone calls seeking comment on
the move and there was no answer after 5 p.m. EDT at Allegheny's
headquarters in Pittsburgh.
   Before Allegheny was given approval in June 1988 to file a
bankruptcy reorganization plan, Jacobs' group had indicated to the
SEC that it might seek control of the company.
   In late July, Allegheny introduced its sixth proposal to
reorganize after management's first five plans failed to win the
approval of creditors.
