<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mazda Motor of America Inc. has formed a
task force to study whether Mazda should make a luxury line for the
U.S. market to compete with Honda's Acura, Nissan's Infiniti and
Toyota's Lexus.
   Mazda, riding high on its hot-selling roadster Miata, made the
announcement Wednesday.
   The company's U.S. sales arm also said it had restructured its
divisions in a move that solidifies George McCabe's spot as the
top-ranking U.S. executive. McCabe, who had been group vice
president of sales and marketing, was promoted to group vice
president in charge of operations as well.
   August sales of trucks and cars from the No. 4 Japanese automaker
increased 11 percent from 1988 to 35,131, including 5,029 Miatas,
which were not available in August 1988. For the first eight months
of 1989, sales were off 1.8 percent, to 239,232.
   Toyota Motor Corp., Nissan Motor Co. and Honda Motor Co. all have
or will have separate luxury car divisions in the United States by
the end of the year. Wednesday's announcement of the task force by
Mazda was the first official indication that it might do the same.
   Richard Colliver, 50, formerly senior vice president of Mazda's
western area operations, was named to head the task force, which
will report to Yoshi Taura, president of Mazda Motor of America.
