<FIRST>r f AM-Datapoint     09-07 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Datapoint,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholder Attempting To Oust Computer Company Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing stock declines and losses
exceeding $126 million, a Datapoint Corp. shareholder said Thursday
he is trying to oust takeover specialist Asher B. Edelman as
chairman and place his own nominees on the company's board.
   ``I think the company needs a workout or turnaround philosophy
rather than its present philosophy,'' said Martin S. Ackerman, a New
York attorney who tries to revive troubled companies.
   Ackerman filed papers with the Securities and Exchange Commission
on Thursday stating why he believes Edelman should be removed from
Datapoint's board.
   Ackerman is awaiting SEC clearance to submit a 25-page proposal
to Datapoint's estimated 4,500 shareholders seeking their consent.
More than 40 percent of the computer company's stock is held by 46
large institutions, he said.
   ``If the institutions think they've had enough of Edelman, then
I'll win,'' said Ackerman, who also is chairman and chief executive
officer of Authorized Distribution Network Inc., a New Jersey-based
computer sales and service company.
   The motion should be put to the stockholders within 60 days, he
said.
   Edelman ousted Datapoint's longtime management in March 1985. He
used some of Datapoint's liquid capital for investments, mostly in
bids to take over other corporations.
   In the SEC filing, Ackerman said a review of public information
indicates that Datapoint's stock value has declined about 58 percent
since Edelman took over in 1985, a period in which the Standard &amp;
Poors Composite Index increased 81 percent.
   Also, according to Ackerman, from fiscal year 1985 to 1988
Datapoint suffered net losses exceeding $106 million, and it had a
$20.3 million net loss for the nine months ending April 29.
   He claims Edelman used Datapoint money for speculation in the
securities of other companies and that Edelman and his associates on
the board were paid large fees by Datapoint.
   Edelman did not immediately return a telephone call Thursday
seeking comment.
   By law, Ackerman said, he could only approach up to 10 Datapoint
stockholder institutions about his plans for the company, and he has
contacted eight. ``So far all of them have encouraged us to go
forward,'' he said.
   Ackerman, a Datapoint stockholder since May, said if he is
successful in taking control of the Datapoint board, he would
immediately halt the company's involvement in investing in the
stocks of potential takeover targets.
   He said Datapoint needs to get back into computers and ``out of
the raid and trade business.''
   Datapoint has about $330 million in annual sales and employs
2,600 people.
   It encountered trouble in the early 1980s because of a soft
computer market, a fight with stockholders who claimed in a lawsuit
the company misled them, and an inability to sell San Antonio real
estate and lease office space in Datapoint-owned buildings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
