<DOCNO> AP890907-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-TimeWarner     09-07 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Time Warner,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaware Judge Rules Chris-Craft Has No Voting Rights in Time-Warner
Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge ruled Thursday that Chris-Craft
Industries Inc., a major shareholder in Warner Communications Inc.,
has no power to veto the merger between Warner and Time Warner Inc.
   Chancery Court Judge William Allen, ruling in Wilmington, Del.,
said the terms of a class of preferred stock held by a Chris-Craft
subsidiary, BHC Inc., did not entitle Chris-Craft to vote on the
merger of the two media giants.
   Allen ruled in response to a request for a declaration of
Chris-Craft's rights by Warner and Time Warner.
   Time Inc. completed a $14 billion tender offer for Warner in
July, and then changed its name to Time Warner Inc. The companies'
merger is expected to be completed later this year.
   A decision by Allen, later upheld by the Delaware Supreme Court,
threw out a challenge to the merger by Paramount Communications
Inc., which had sought to acquire Time Inc. for $12 billion.
   In his latest decision, Allen said that under the terms of the
stock, Chris-Craft does not ``possess a veto over every merger in
which its interests would be adversely affected.''
   Chris-Craft contended it had a right to vote on the merger
because its preferred Warner shares can be converted into preferred
Time Warner shares.
   Warner, Time Warner and Chris-Craft have settled other parts of
their dispute.
   Warner and Chris-Craft Chairman Herbert Siegel have been feuding
ever since Chris-Craft helped Warner fend off an unwanted takeover
bid from publisher Rupert Murdoch in 1984.
</TEXT>
