<FIRST>r f BC-AshlandSettlement     09-07 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ashland Settlement,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ashland Oil, National Iranian Settle for $325 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. said Thursday it had settled
a dispute with the National Iranian Oil Co. for $325 million, less
than a week before a trial was scheduled to begin in Mississippi.
   The dispute has been the subject of litigation between Ashland
and National Iranian since 1980 in courts in England, Bermuda and
the United States, as well as other proceedings, Ashland said.
   It involved National Iranian's claim for about $283 million of
unpaid invoices for crude oil shipments to Ashland in 1979, plus
interest of about $285 million, for a total claim of about $768
million.
   John R. Hall, Ashland Oil's chairman and chief executive officer,
said in a statement the settlement was fair and in the best
interests of both parties.
   ``Ashland never disputed receiving the crude oil or that it was
obligated to pay a reasonable price for it,'' Hall said in the
release. ``Ashland simply wished to recover losses it sustained in
1979 due to breaches of contract by NIOC. Considering Ashland had
the use and benefit of $283 million for almost 10 years, we feel
this settlement satisfactorily addresses our counterclaims.''
   Ashland had counterclaimed in the courts for breaches of contract
by National Iranian.
   A trial regarding National Iranian's claim was scheduled to start
in U.S. District Court in Jackson, Miss., on Sept. 11. No trial date
had been set in a case in Bermuda.
   Hall said the settlement will result in a pre-tax charge of $42
million in Ashland's fiscal fourth quarter, ending Sept. 30.
   Ashland is the nation's largest independent oil refiner.
</TEXT>
