<FIRST>r f BC-Kemper-MurrayJohnstone     09-07 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kemper-Murray Johnstone,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemper and Murray Johnstone Going Separate Ways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kemper Financial Services Inc. said Thursday it
was dissolving its 9-year-old joint venture with Scotland's Murray
Johnstone Group because each firm had reached the goal it
established at the outset.
   The joint-venture firm, Kemper-Murray Johnstone International
Inc. has been providing international asset-management services for
U.S. accounts since 1980.
   Charles M. Kierscht, president of Kemper Financial, said Kemper
had accumulated international investment expertise while Murray
Johnstone had gained a foothold in the U.S. investment-services
market.
   ``These two objectives have been pursued successfully over the
past nine years during which time the businesses of both Kemper and
Murray Johnstone have grown substantially,'' Kierscht said in a news
release.
   On the Kemper side, assets under management increased from $8
billion in 1980 to more than $56 billion today, Kemper said.
   Murray Johnstone has grown from $1 billion in 1980 to $7.5
billion today.
   The breakup is effective Dec. 31, Kemper said.
   ``The primary objective of both parties is to ensure the
continuity of asset management and client servicing during the
transition period and thereafter,'' Kierscht said.
</TEXT>
