<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2344EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Dataproducts     09-07 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dataproducts,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Printer Company Rejects Takeover, Announces Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dataproducts Corp. spurned a buyout bid from a
New York investment firm Thursday and said it would restructure by
laying off 400 employees, a fifth of its U.S. work force, and
selling its headquarters and a New England subsidiary.
   The computer printer maker said it expected to realize about $60
million in cash after completing the sales and paying costs of the
restructuring and taxes. It said it would distribute the profit to
shareholders as a special dividend worth about $3 per share.
   The regular semi-annual dividend of 8 cents per share will be
dropped.
   The company is facing tough domestic and Japanese competition as
well as the takeover proposal by DPC Acquisition Partners, a group
led by John K. Castle, a former chief executive of the Wall Street
investment firm Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette Securities Corp.
   DPC owns 8 percent of Dataproducts' shares and proposed last
month to buy the rest for $273 million, or $15 a share, with at
least $10 per share in cash.
   Dataproducts said neither that offer, nor another buyout proposal
it declined to describe in detail, had adequate financing.
   It said its board decided restructuring was best for its
shareholders after it and its investment bankers, Goldman Sachs &amp;
Co., discussed selling all or part of its businesses ``with more
than 70 entities.''
   Dataproducts shares fell $2.25 Thursday to close at $10 on the
American Stock Exchange.
   The company said it would save about $20 million a year through
the layoffs.
   It said it intended to sell Wallingford, Conn.-based Dataproducts
New England, which makes heavy-duty computer printers and
communications equipment for the military.
   DPC last month offered to buy the New England operation in
exchange for $25 million cash and its existing stake in Dataproducts.
   Dataproducts said it agreed in principle to sell its 21-acre
headquarters property to Trizec Properties Inc. for $63 million. The
company said it will lease back the facilities for two years while
it looks for a cheaper place to relocate in Southern California.
   Dataproducts also said it would:
   _Take one-time charges of $45 million this fiscal year in
connection with the restructuring. The sale of the headquarters and
the New England subsidiary are expected to offset the charges.
   _Save corporate expenses by decentralizing into three stand-alone
operations: printer equipment, printer supplies and solid ink
printers and technology.
   _Phase out most domestic printer manufacturing, relocating it to
its plants in Hong Kong and Dublin, Ireland.
</TEXT>
