<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Chrysler-PartsSuit     09-07 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chrysler-Parts Suit,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Sides With Chrysler Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals panel Thursday upheld
Chrysler Corp. in an antitrust lawsuit filed by three companies that
buy and resell replacement parts for Chrysler-produced vehicles.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld a ruling by U.S. District Judge Robert DeMascio of Detroit in
favor of Chrysler.
   International Logistics Group Ltd., Aargus Truck and Automotive
Supply Inc. and Guardian Auto Supply Inc. sued Chrysler, alleging
the automaker illegally conspired to restrain trade.
   The companies also alleged that Chrysler attempted to monopolize
the resale of Chrysler-produced auto parts to Chrysler-franchised
dealers and to the government.
   Chrysler argued that it and about 2,400 independent manufacturers
or suppliers of compatible replacement parts compete for the
replacement parts market. Chrysler also argued that the plaintiffs
failed to prove their monopoly allegations because Chrysler's share
of the replacement-parts market was only about 20 percent.
   DeMascio, presiding at a trial of the lawsuit, issued rulings in
February and May 1988 in favor of Chrysler. The three plaintiff
companies appealed.
   The companies buy and resell Chrysler-produced and compatible
replacement parts for Chrysler vehicles. Businessman Theodore Henke
owns and operates the three companies through stock ownership.
</TEXT>
