<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0316 09-07 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0316,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Gain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was slightly lower against the
Japanese yen during morning trading Friday, while share prices on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained moderately.
   The dollar closed the morning trading session at 146.55 yen, down
0.32 yen from Thursday's close of 146.87 yen. After opening lower at
146.59 yen, the currency ranged from 146.40 to 146.90 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
118.75 points the previous day, gained 72.03 points, or 0.21
percent, to close the morning session at 34,224.59.
   Currency dealers said there were strong dollar-buying incentives
following Thursday's decision by West Germany's central bank to
leave that nation's interest rates unchanged.
   A dealer with a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke
anonymously, said the dollar edged up from the opening with some
early buying, but profit-taking quickly eased its upward path.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index moved higher as investors
welcomed the yen's reversal against the dollar, dealers said.
   But a dealer at Nikko Securities Co., speaking anonymously, said,
``We still need to determine whether the yen-dollar rate has really
stabilized or is just easing temporarily.''
</TEXT>
